69def _single_replace(self, to_replace, method, inplace, limit): 

70 """ 

71 Replaces values in a Series using the fill method specified when no 

72 replacement value is given in the replace method 

73 """ 

74 if self.ndim != 1: 

75 raise TypeError('cannot replace {0} with method {1} on a {2}' 

76 .format(to_replace, method, type(self).__name__)) 

77 

78 orig_dtype = self.dtype 

79 result = self if inplace else self.copy() 

80 fill_f = missing.get_fill_func(method) 

81 

82 mask = missing.mask_missing(result.values, to_replace) 

83 values = fill_f(result.values, limit=limit, mask=mask) 

84 

85 if values.dtype == orig_dtype and inplace: 

86 return 

87 

88 result = pd.Series(values, index=self.index, 

89 dtype=self.dtype).__finalize__(self) 

90 

91 if inplace: 

92 self._update_inplace(result._data) 

93 return 

94 

95 return result

98class NDFrame(PandasObject, SelectionMixin): 

99 """ 

100 N-dimensional analogue of DataFrame. Store multi-dimensional in a 

101 size-mutable, labeled data structure 

102 

103 Parameters 

104 ---------- 

105 data : BlockManager 

106 axes : list 

107 copy : boolean, default False 

108 """ 

109 _internal_names = ['_data', '_cacher', '_item_cache', '_cache', '_is_copy', 

110 '_subtyp', '_name', '_index', '_default_kind', 

111 '_default_fill_value', '_metadata', '__array_struct__', 

112 '__array_interface__'] 

113 _internal_names_set = set(_internal_names) 

114 _accessors = frozenset() 

115 _deprecations = frozenset(['as_blocks', 'blocks', 

116 'convert_objects', 'is_copy']) 

117 _metadata = [] 

118 _is_copy = None 

119 

120 # dummy attribute so that datetime.__eq__(Series/DataFrame) defers 

121 # by returning NotImplemented 

122 timetuple = None 

123 

124 # ---------------------------------------------------------------------- 

125 # Constructors 

126 

127 def __init__(self, data, axes=None, copy=False, dtype=None, 

128 fastpath=False): 

129 

130 if not fastpath: 

131 if dtype is not None: 

132 data = data.astype(dtype) 

133 elif copy: 

134 data = data.copy() 

135 

136 if axes is not None: 

137 for i, ax in enumerate(axes): 

138 data = data.reindex_axis(ax, axis=i) 

139 

140 object.__setattr__(self, '_is_copy', None) 

141 object.__setattr__(self, '_data', data) 

142 object.__setattr__(self, '_item_cache', {}) 

143 

144 def _init_mgr(self, mgr, axes=None, dtype=None, copy=False): 

145 """ passed a manager and a axes dict """ 

146 for a, axe in axes.items(): 

147 if axe is not None: 

148 mgr = mgr.reindex_axis(axe, 

149 axis=self._get_block_manager_axis(a), 

150 copy=False) 

151 

152 # make a copy if explicitly requested 

153 if copy: 

154 mgr = mgr.copy() 

155 if dtype is not None: 

156 # avoid further copies if we can 

157 if len(mgr.blocks) > 1 or mgr.blocks[0].values.dtype != dtype: 

158 mgr = mgr.astype(dtype=dtype) 

159 return mgr 

160

164 def is_copy(self): 

165 """ 

166 Return the copy. 

167 """ 

168 warnings.warn("Attribute 'is_copy' is deprecated and will be removed " 

169 "in a future version.", FutureWarning, stacklevel=2) 

170 return self._is_copy 

171 

172 @is_copy.setter 

173 def is_copy(self, msg): 

174 warnings.warn("Attribute 'is_copy' is deprecated and will be removed " 

175 "in a future version.", FutureWarning, stacklevel=2) 

176 self._is_copy = msg

178 def _validate_dtype(self, dtype): 

179 """ validate the passed dtype """ 

180 

181 if dtype is not None: 

182 dtype = pandas_dtype(dtype) 

183 

184 # a compound dtype 

185 if dtype.kind == 'V': 

186 raise NotImplementedError("compound dtypes are not implemented" 

187 " in the {0} constructor" 

188 .format(self.__class__.__name__)) 

189 

190 return dtype

219 @classmethod 

220 def _setup_axes(cls, axes, info_axis=None, stat_axis=None, aliases=None, 

221 slicers=None, axes_are_reversed=False, build_axes=True, 

222 ns=None, docs=None): 

223 """Provide axes setup for the major PandasObjects. 

224 

225 Parameters 

226 ---------- 

227 axes : the names of the axes in order (lowest to highest) 

228 info_axis_num : the axis of the selector dimension (int) 

229 stat_axis_num : the number of axis for the default stats (int) 

230 aliases : other names for a single axis (dict) 

231 slicers : how axes slice to others (dict) 

232 axes_are_reversed : boolean whether to treat passed axes as 

233 reversed (DataFrame) 

234 build_axes : setup the axis properties (default True) 

235 """ 

236 

237 cls._AXIS_ORDERS = axes 

238 cls._AXIS_NUMBERS = {a: i for i, a in enumerate(axes)} 

239 cls._AXIS_LEN = len(axes) 

240 cls._AXIS_ALIASES = aliases or dict() 

241 cls._AXIS_IALIASES = {v: k for k, v in cls._AXIS_ALIASES.items()} 

242 cls._AXIS_NAMES = dict(enumerate(axes)) 

243 cls._AXIS_SLICEMAP = slicers or None 

244 cls._AXIS_REVERSED = axes_are_reversed 

245 

246 # typ 

247 setattr(cls, '_typ', cls.__name__.lower()) 

248 

249 # indexing support 

250 cls._ix = None 

251 

252 if info_axis is not None: 

253 cls._info_axis_number = info_axis 

254 cls._info_axis_name = axes[info_axis] 

255 

256 if stat_axis is not None: 

257 cls._stat_axis_number = stat_axis 

258 cls._stat_axis_name = axes[stat_axis] 

259 

260 # setup the actual axis 

261 if build_axes: 

262 

263 def set_axis(a, i): 

264 setattr(cls, a, properties.AxisProperty(i, docs.get(a, a))) 

265 cls._internal_names_set.add(a) 

266 

267 if axes_are_reversed: 

268 m = cls._AXIS_LEN - 1 

269 for i, a in cls._AXIS_NAMES.items(): 

270 set_axis(a, m - i) 

271 else: 

272 for i, a in cls._AXIS_NAMES.items(): 

273 set_axis(a, i) 

274 

275 assert not isinstance(ns, dict) 

276 

277 def _construct_axes_dict(self, axes=None, **kwargs): 

278 """Return an axes dictionary for myself.""" 

279 d = {a: self._get_axis(a) for a in (axes or self._AXIS_ORDERS)} 

280 d.update(kwargs) 

281 return d 

282 

283 @staticmethod 

284 def _construct_axes_dict_from(self, axes, **kwargs): 

285 """Return an axes dictionary for the passed axes.""" 

286 d = {a: ax for a, ax in zip(self._AXIS_ORDERS, axes)} 

287 d.update(kwargs) 

288 return d 

289 

290 def _construct_axes_dict_for_slice(self, axes=None, **kwargs): 

291 """Return an axes dictionary for myself.""" 

292 d = {self._AXIS_SLICEMAP[a]: self._get_axis(a) 

293 for a in (axes or self._AXIS_ORDERS)} 

294 d.update(kwargs) 

295 return d 

296 

297 def _construct_axes_from_arguments( 

298 self, args, kwargs, require_all=False, sentinel=None): 

299 """Construct and returns axes if supplied in args/kwargs. 

300 

301 If require_all, raise if all axis arguments are not supplied 

302 return a tuple of (axes, kwargs). 

303 

304 sentinel specifies the default parameter when an axis is not 

305 supplied; useful to distinguish when a user explicitly passes None 

306 in scenarios where None has special meaning. 

307 """ 

308 

309 # construct the args 

310 args = list(args) 

311 for a in self._AXIS_ORDERS: 

312 

313 # if we have an alias for this axis 

314 alias = self._AXIS_IALIASES.get(a) 

315 if alias is not None: 

316 if a in kwargs: 

317 if alias in kwargs: 

318 raise TypeError("arguments are mutually exclusive " 

319 "for [%s,%s]" % (a, alias)) 

320 continue 

321 if alias in kwargs: 

322 kwargs[a] = kwargs.pop(alias) 

323 continue 

324 

325 # look for a argument by position 

326 if a not in kwargs: 

327 try: 

328 kwargs[a] = args.pop(0) 

329 except IndexError: 

330 if require_all: 

331 raise TypeError("not enough/duplicate arguments " 

332 "specified!") 

333 

334 axes = {a: kwargs.pop(a, sentinel) for a in self._AXIS_ORDERS} 

335 return axes, kwargs 

336 

337 @classmethod 

338 def _from_axes(cls, data, axes, **kwargs): 

339 # for construction from BlockManager 

340 if isinstance(data, BlockManager): 

341 return cls(data, **kwargs) 

342 else: 

343 if cls._AXIS_REVERSED: 

344 axes = axes[::-1] 

345 d = cls._construct_axes_dict_from(cls, axes, copy=False) 

346 d.update(kwargs) 

347 return cls(data, **d) 

348 

349 @classmethod 

350 def _get_axis_number(cls, axis): 

351 axis = cls._AXIS_ALIASES.get(axis, axis) 

352 if is_integer(axis): 

353 if axis in cls._AXIS_NAMES: 

354 return axis 

355 else: 

356 try: 

357 return cls._AXIS_NUMBERS[axis] 

358 except KeyError: 

359 pass 

360 raise ValueError('No axis named {0} for object type {1}' 

361 .format(axis, type(cls))) 

362 

363 @classmethod 

364 def _get_axis_name(cls, axis): 

365 axis = cls._AXIS_ALIASES.get(axis, axis) 

366 if isinstance(axis, string_types): 

367 if axis in cls._AXIS_NUMBERS: 

368 return axis 

369 else: 

370 try: 

371 return cls._AXIS_NAMES[axis] 

372 except KeyError: 

373 pass 

374 raise ValueError('No axis named {0} for object type {1}' 

375 .format(axis, type(cls))) 

376 

377 def _get_axis(self, axis): 

378 name = self._get_axis_name(axis) 

379 return getattr(self, name) 

380 

381 @classmethod 

382 def _get_block_manager_axis(cls, axis): 

383 """Map the axis to the block_manager axis.""" 

384 axis = cls._get_axis_number(axis) 

385 if cls._AXIS_REVERSED: 

386 m = cls._AXIS_LEN - 1 

387 return m - axis 

388 return axis 

389 

390 def _get_axis_resolvers(self, axis): 

391 # index or columns 

392 axis_index = getattr(self, axis) 

393 d = dict() 

394 prefix = axis[0] 

395 

396 for i, name in enumerate(axis_index.names): 

397 if name is not None: 

398 key = level = name 

399 else: 

400 # prefix with 'i' or 'c' depending on the input axis 

401 # e.g., you must do ilevel_0 for the 0th level of an unnamed 

402 # multiiindex 

403 key = '{prefix}level_{i}'.format(prefix=prefix, i=i) 

404 level = i 

405 

406 level_values = axis_index.get_level_values(level) 

407 s = level_values.to_series() 

408 s.index = axis_index 

409 d[key] = s 

410 

411 # put the index/columns itself in the dict 

412 if isinstance(axis_index, MultiIndex): 

413 dindex = axis_index 

414 else: 

415 dindex = axis_index.to_series() 

416 

417 d[axis] = dindex 

418 return d 

419 

420 def _get_index_resolvers(self): 

421 d = {} 

422 for axis_name in self._AXIS_ORDERS: 

423 d.update(self._get_axis_resolvers(axis_name)) 

424 return d

448 return [self._get_axis(a) for a in self._AXIS_ORDERS]

473 @property 

474 def size(self): 

475 """ 

476 Return an int representing the number of elements in this object. 

477

480 

481 See Also 

482 --------

488 >>> s.size 

489 3 

490 

491 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'col1': [1, 2], 'col2': [3, 4]}) 

492 >>> df.size 

493 4 

494 """ 

495 return np.prod(self.shape)

507 def _expand_axes(self, key): 

508 new_axes = [] 

509 for k, ax in zip(key, self.axes): 

510 if k not in ax: 

511 if type(k) != ax.dtype.type: 

512 ax = ax.astype('O') 

513 new_axes.append(ax.insert(len(ax), k)) 

514 else: 

515 new_axes.append(ax) 

516 

517 return new_axes

519 def set_axis(self, labels, axis=0, inplace=None): 

520 """ 

521 Assign desired index to given axis. 

522 

523 Indexes for column or row labels can be changed by assigning 

524 a list-like or Index. 

525 

526 .. versionchanged:: 0.21.0 

527 

528 The signature is now `labels` and `axis`, consistent with 

529 the rest of pandas API. Previously, the `axis` and `labels` 

530 arguments were respectively the first and second positional 

531 arguments. 

532 

533 Parameters 

534 ---------- 

535 labels : list-like, Index 

536 The values for the new index. 

537 

538 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0 

539 The axis to update. The value 0 identifies the rows, and 1 

540 identifies the columns. 

541 

542 inplace : boolean, default None 

543 Whether to return a new %(klass)s instance. 

544 

545 .. warning:: 

546 

547 ``inplace=None`` currently falls back to to True, but in a 

548 future version, will default to False. Use inplace=True 

549 explicitly rather than relying on the default. 

550 

551 Returns 

552 ------- 

553 renamed : %(klass)s or None 

554 An object of same type as caller if inplace=False, None otherwise. 

555 

556 See Also 

557 -------- 

558 DataFrame.rename_axis : Alter the name of the index or columns. 

559 

560 Examples 

561 -------- 

562 **Series** 

563 

564 >>> s = pd.Series([1, 2, 3]) 

565 >>> s 

566 0 1 

567 1 2 

568 2 3 

569 dtype: int64 

570 

571 >>> s.set_axis(['a', 'b', 'c'], axis=0, inplace=False) 

572 a 1 

573 b 2 

574 c 3 

575 dtype: int64 

576 

577 The original object is not modified. 

578 

579 >>> s 

580 0 1 

581 1 2 

582 2 3 

583 dtype: int64 

584 

585 **DataFrame** 

586 

587 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({"A": [1, 2, 3], "B": [4, 5, 6]}) 

588 

589 Change the row labels. 

590 

591 >>> df.set_axis(['a', 'b', 'c'], axis='index', inplace=False) 

592 A B 

593 a 1 4 

594 b 2 5 

595 c 3 6 

596 

597 Change the column labels. 

598 

599 >>> df.set_axis(['I', 'II'], axis='columns', inplace=False) 

600 I II 

601 0 1 4 

602 1 2 5 

603 2 3 6 

604 

605 Now, update the labels inplace. 

606 

607 >>> df.set_axis(['i', 'ii'], axis='columns', inplace=True) 

608 >>> df 

609 i ii 

610 0 1 4 

611 1 2 5 

612 2 3 6 

613 """ 

614 if is_scalar(labels): 

615 warnings.warn( 

616 'set_axis now takes "labels" as first argument, and ' 

617 '"axis" as named parameter. The old form, with "axis" as ' 

618 'first parameter and \"labels\" as second, is still supported ' 

619 'but will be deprecated in a future version of pandas.', 

620 FutureWarning, stacklevel=2) 

621 labels, axis = axis, labels 

622 

623 if inplace is None: 

624 warnings.warn( 

625 'set_axis currently defaults to operating inplace.\nThis ' 

626 'will change in a future version of pandas, use ' 

627 'inplace=True to avoid this warning.', 

628 FutureWarning, stacklevel=2) 

629 inplace = True 

630 if inplace: 

631 setattr(self, self._get_axis_name(axis), labels) 

632 else: 

633 obj = self.copy() 

634 obj.set_axis(labels, axis=axis, inplace=True) 

635 return obj 

636 

637 def _set_axis(self, axis, labels): 

638 self._data.set_axis(axis, labels) 

639 self._clear_item_cache()

641 def transpose(self, *args, **kwargs): 

642 """ 

643 Permute the dimensions of the %(klass)s 

644 

645 Parameters 

646 ---------- 

647 args : %(args_transpose)s 

648 copy : boolean, default False 

649 Make a copy of the underlying data. Mixed-dtype data will 

650 always result in a copy 

651 

652 Returns 

653 ------- 

654 y : same as input 

655 

656 Examples 

657 -------- 

658 >>> p.transpose(2, 0, 1) 

659 >>> p.transpose(2, 0, 1, copy=True) 

660 """ 

661 

662 # construct the args 

663 axes, kwargs = self._construct_axes_from_arguments(args, kwargs, 

664 require_all=True) 

665 axes_names = tuple(self._get_axis_name(axes[a]) 

666 for a in self._AXIS_ORDERS) 

667 axes_numbers = tuple(self._get_axis_number(axes[a]) 

668 for a in self._AXIS_ORDERS) 

669 

670 # we must have unique axes 

671 if len(axes) != len(set(axes)): 

672 raise ValueError('Must specify %s unique axes' % self._AXIS_LEN) 

673 

674 new_axes = self._construct_axes_dict_from(self, [self._get_axis(x) 

675 for x in axes_names]) 

676 new_values = self.values.transpose(axes_numbers) 

677 if kwargs.pop('copy', None) or (len(args) and args[-1]): 

678 new_values = new_values.copy() 

679 

680 nv.validate_transpose_for_generic(self, kwargs) 

681 return self._constructor(new_values, **new_axes).__finalize__(self) 

682 

683 def swapaxes(self, axis1, axis2, copy=True): 

684 """ 

685 Interchange axes and swap values axes appropriately. 

686 

687 Returns 

688 ------- 

689 y : same as input 

690 """ 

691 i = self._get_axis_number(axis1) 

692 j = self._get_axis_number(axis2) 

693 

694 if i == j: 

695 if copy: 

696 return self.copy() 

697 return self 

698 

699 mapping = {i: j, j: i} 

700 

701 new_axes = (self._get_axis(mapping.get(k, k)) 

702 for k in range(self._AXIS_LEN)) 

703 new_values = self.values.swapaxes(i, j) 

704 if copy: 

705 new_values = new_values.copy() 

706 

707 return self._constructor(new_values, *new_axes).__finalize__(self) 

708 

709 def droplevel(self, level, axis=0): 

710 """ 

711 Return DataFrame with requested index / column level(s) removed. 

712 

713 .. versionadded:: 0.24.0 

714 

715 Parameters 

716 ---------- 

717 level : int, str, or list-like 

718 If a string is given, must be the name of a level 

719 If list-like, elements must be names or positional indexes 

720 of levels. 

721 

722 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0 

723 

724 Returns 

725 ------- 

726 DataFrame.droplevel() 

727 

728 Examples 

729 -------- 

730 >>> df = pd.DataFrame([ 

731 ... [1, 2, 3, 4], 

732 ... [5, 6, 7, 8], 

733 ... [9, 10, 11, 12] 

734 ... ]).set_index([0, 1]).rename_axis(['a', 'b']) 

735 

736 >>> df.columns = pd.MultiIndex.from_tuples([ 

737 ... ('c', 'e'), ('d', 'f') 

738 ... ], names=['level_1', 'level_2']) 

739 

740 >>> df 

741 level_1 c d 

742 level_2 e f 

743 a b 

744 1 2 3 4 

745 5 6 7 8 

746 9 10 11 12 

747 

748 >>> df.droplevel('a') 

749 level_1 c d 

750 level_2 e f 

751 b 

752 2 3 4 

753 6 7 8 

754 10 11 12 

755 

756 >>> df.droplevel('level2', axis=1) 

757 level_1 c d 

758 a b 

759 1 2 3 4 

760 5 6 7 8 

761 9 10 11 12 

762 """ 

763 labels = self._get_axis(axis) 

764 new_labels = labels.droplevel(level) 

765 result = self.set_axis(new_labels, axis=axis, inplace=False) 

766 return result 

767 

768 def pop(self, item): 

769 """ 

770 Return item and drop from frame. Raise KeyError if not found. 

771 

772 Parameters 

773 ---------- 

774 item : str 

775 Column label to be popped 

776 

777 Returns 

778 ------- 

779 popped : Series 

780 

781 Examples 

782 -------- 

783 >>> df = pd.DataFrame([('falcon', 'bird', 389.0), 

784 ... ('parrot', 'bird', 24.0), 

785 ... ('lion', 'mammal', 80.5), 

786 ... ('monkey', 'mammal', np.nan)], 

787 ... columns=('name', 'class', 'max_speed')) 

788 >>> df 

789 name class max_speed 

790 0 falcon bird 389.0 

791 1 parrot bird 24.0 

792 2 lion mammal 80.5 

793 3 monkey mammal NaN 

794 

795 >>> df.pop('class') 

796 0 bird 

797 1 bird 

798 2 mammal 

799 3 mammal 

800 Name: class, dtype: object 

801 

802 >>> df 

803 name max_speed 

804 0 falcon 389.0 

805 1 parrot 24.0 

806 2 lion 80.5 

807 3 monkey NaN 

808 """ 

809 result = self[item] 

810 del self[item] 

811 try: 

812 result._reset_cacher() 

813 except AttributeError: 

814 pass 

815 

816 return result 

817 

818 def squeeze(self, axis=None): 

819 """ 

820 Squeeze 1 dimensional axis objects into scalars. 

821 

822 Series or DataFrames with a single element are squeezed to a scalar. 

823 DataFrames with a single column or a single row are squeezed to a 

824 Series. Otherwise the object is unchanged. 

825 

826 This method is most useful when you don't know if your 

827 object is a Series or DataFrame, but you do know it has just a single 

828 column. In that case you can safely call `squeeze` to ensure you have a 

829 Series. 

830 

831 Parameters 

832 ---------- 

833 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns', None}, default None 

834 A specific axis to squeeze. By default, all length-1 axes are 

835 squeezed. 

836 

837 .. versionadded:: 0.20.0 

838 

839 Returns 

840 ------- 

841 DataFrame, Series, or scalar 

842 The projection after squeezing `axis` or all the axes. 

843 

844 See Also 

845 -------- 

846 Series.iloc : Integer-location based indexing for selecting scalars. 

847 DataFrame.iloc : Integer-location based indexing for selecting Series. 

848 Series.to_frame : Inverse of DataFrame.squeeze for a 

849 single-column DataFrame. 

850 

851 Examples 

852 -------- 

853 >>> primes = pd.Series([2, 3, 5, 7]) 

854 

855 Slicing might produce a Series with a single value: 

856 

857 >>> even_primes = primes[primes % 2 == 0] 

858 >>> even_primes 

859 0 2 

860 dtype: int64 

861 

862 >>> even_primes.squeeze() 

863 2 

864 

865 Squeezing objects with more than one value in every axis does nothing: 

866 

867 >>> odd_primes = primes[primes % 2 == 1] 

868 >>> odd_primes 

869 1 3 

870 2 5 

871 3 7 

872 dtype: int64 

873 

874 >>> odd_primes.squeeze() 

875 1 3 

876 2 5 

877 3 7 

878 dtype: int64 

879 

880 Squeezing is even more effective when used with DataFrames. 

881 

882 >>> df = pd.DataFrame([[1, 2], [3, 4]], columns=['a', 'b']) 

883 >>> df 

884 a b 

885 0 1 2 

886 1 3 4 

887 

888 Slicing a single column will produce a DataFrame with the columns 

889 having only one value: 

890 

891 >>> df_a = df[['a']] 

892 >>> df_a 

893 a 

894 0 1 

895 1 3 

896 

897 So the columns can be squeezed down, resulting in a Series: 

898 

899 >>> df_a.squeeze('columns') 

900 0 1 

901 1 3 

902 Name: a, dtype: int64 

903 

904 Slicing a single row from a single column will produce a single 

905 scalar DataFrame: 

906 

907 >>> df_0a = df.loc[df.index < 1, ['a']] 

908 >>> df_0a 

909 a 

910 0 1 

911 

912 Squeezing the rows produces a single scalar Series: 

913 

914 >>> df_0a.squeeze('rows') 

915 a 1 

916 Name: 0, dtype: int64 

917 

918 Squeezing all axes wil project directly into a scalar: 

919 

920 >>> df_0a.squeeze() 

921 1 

922 """ 

923 axis = (self._AXIS_NAMES if axis is None else 

924 (self._get_axis_number(axis),)) 

925 try: 

926 return self.iloc[ 

927 tuple(0 if i in axis and len(a) == 1 else slice(None) 

928 for i, a in enumerate(self.axes))] 

929 except Exception: 

930 return self 

931 

932 def swaplevel(self, i=-2, j=-1, axis=0): 

933 """ 

934 Swap levels i and j in a MultiIndex on a particular axis 

935 

936 Parameters 

937 ---------- 

938 i, j : int, string (can be mixed) 

939 Level of index to be swapped. Can pass level name as string. 

940 

941 Returns 

942 ------- 

943 swapped : same type as caller (new object) 

944 

945 .. versionchanged:: 0.18.1 

946 

947 The indexes ``i`` and ``j`` are now optional, and default to 

948 the two innermost levels of the index. 

949 

950 """ 

951 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

952 result = self.copy() 

953 labels = result._data.axes[axis] 

954 result._data.set_axis(axis, labels.swaplevel(i, j)) 

955 return result 

956 

957 # ---------------------------------------------------------------------- 

958 # Rename 

959 

960 def rename(self, *args, **kwargs): 

961 """ 

962 Alter axes input function or functions. Function / dict values must be 

963 unique (1-to-1). Labels not contained in a dict / Series will be left 

964 as-is. Extra labels listed don't throw an error. Alternatively, change 

965 ``Series.name`` with a scalar value (Series only). 

966 

967 Parameters 

968 ---------- 

969 %(axes)s : scalar, list-like, dict-like or function, optional 

970 Scalar or list-like will alter the ``Series.name`` attribute, 

971 and raise on DataFrame or Panel. 

972 dict-like or functions are transformations to apply to 

973 that axis' values 

974 copy : boolean, default True 

975 Also copy underlying data 

976 inplace : boolean, default False 

977 Whether to return a new %(klass)s. If True then value of copy is 

978 ignored. 

979 level : int or level name, default None 

980 In case of a MultiIndex, only rename labels in the specified 

981 level. 

982 

983 Returns 

984 ------- 

985 renamed : %(klass)s (new object) 

986 

987 See Also 

988 -------- 

989 pandas.NDFrame.rename_axis 

990 

991 Examples 

992 -------- 

993 

994 >>> s = pd.Series([1, 2, 3]) 

995 >>> s 

996 0 1 

997 1 2 

998 2 3 

999 dtype: int64 

1000 >>> s.rename("my_name") # scalar, changes Series.name 

1001 0 1 

1002 1 2 

1003 2 3 

1004 Name: my_name, dtype: int64 

1005 >>> s.rename(lambda x: x ** 2) # function, changes labels 

1006 0 1 

1007 1 2 

1008 4 3 

1009 dtype: int64 

1010 >>> s.rename({1: 3, 2: 5}) # mapping, changes labels 

1011 0 1 

1012 3 2 

1013 5 3 

1014 dtype: int64 

1015 

1016 Since ``DataFrame`` doesn't have a ``.name`` attribute, 

1017 only mapping-type arguments are allowed. 

1018 

1019 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({"A": [1, 2, 3], "B": [4, 5, 6]}) 

1020 >>> df.rename(2) 

1021 Traceback (most recent call last): 

1022 ... 

1023 TypeError: 'int' object is not callable 

1024 

1025 ``DataFrame.rename`` supports two calling conventions 

1026 

1027 * ``(index=index_mapper, columns=columns_mapper, ...)`` 

1028 * ``(mapper, axis={'index', 'columns'}, ...)`` 

1029 

1030 We *highly* recommend using keyword arguments to clarify your 

1031 intent. 

1032 

1033 >>> df.rename(index=str, columns={"A": "a", "B": "c"}) 

1034 a c 

1035 0 1 4 

1036 1 2 5 

1037 2 3 6 

1038 

1039 >>> df.rename(index=str, columns={"A": "a", "C": "c"}) 

1040 a B 

1041 0 1 4 

1042 1 2 5 

1043 2 3 6 

1044 

1045 Using axis-style parameters 

1046 

1047 >>> df.rename(str.lower, axis='columns') 

1048 a b 

1049 0 1 4 

1050 1 2 5 

1051 2 3 6 

1052 

1053 >>> df.rename({1: 2, 2: 4}, axis='index') 

1054 A B 

1055 0 1 4 

1056 2 2 5 

1057 4 3 6 

1058 

1059 See the :ref:`user guide <basics.rename>` for more. 

1060 """ 

1061 axes, kwargs = self._construct_axes_from_arguments(args, kwargs) 

1062 copy = kwargs.pop('copy', True) 

1063 inplace = kwargs.pop('inplace', False) 

1064 level = kwargs.pop('level', None) 

1065 axis = kwargs.pop('axis', None) 

1066 if axis is not None: 

1067 # Validate the axis 

1068 self._get_axis_number(axis) 

1069 

1070 if kwargs: 

1071 raise TypeError('rename() got an unexpected keyword ' 

1072 'argument "{0}"'.format(list(kwargs.keys())[0])) 

1073 

1074 if com.count_not_none(*axes.values()) == 0: 

1075 raise TypeError('must pass an index to rename') 

1076 

1077 self._consolidate_inplace() 

1078 result = self if inplace else self.copy(deep=copy) 

1079 

1080 # start in the axis order to eliminate too many copies 

1081 for axis in lrange(self._AXIS_LEN): 

1082 v = axes.get(self._AXIS_NAMES[axis]) 

1083 if v is None: 

1084 continue 

1085 f = com._get_rename_function(v) 

1086 

1087 baxis = self._get_block_manager_axis(axis) 

1088 if level is not None: 

1089 level = self.axes[axis]._get_level_number(level) 

1090 result._data = result._data.rename_axis(f, axis=baxis, copy=copy, 

1091 level=level) 

1092 result._clear_item_cache() 

1093 

1094 if inplace: 

1095 self._update_inplace(result._data) 

1096 else: 

1097 return result.__finalize__(self) 

1098 

1099 @rewrite_axis_style_signature('mapper', [('copy', True), 

1100 ('inplace', False)]) 

1101 def rename_axis(self, mapper=sentinel, **kwargs): 

1102 """ 

1103 Set the name of the axis for the index or columns. 

1104 

1105 Parameters 

1106 ---------- 

1107 mapper : scalar, list-like, optional 

1108 Value to set the axis name attribute. 

1109 index, columns : scalar, list-like, dict-like or function, optional 

1110 A scalar, list-like, dict-like or functions transformations to 

1111 apply to that axis' values. 

1112 

1113 Use either ``mapper`` and ``axis`` to 

1114 specify the axis to target with ``mapper``, or ``index`` 

1115 and/or ``columns``. 

1116 

1117 .. versionchanged:: 0.24.0 

1118 

1119 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0 

1120 The axis to rename. 

1121 copy : bool, default True 

1122 Also copy underlying data. 

1123 inplace : bool, default False 

1124 Modifies the object directly, instead of creating a new Series 

1125 or DataFrame. 

1126 

1127 Returns 

1128 ------- 

1129 Series, DataFrame, or None 

1130 The same type as the caller or None if `inplace` is True. 

1131 

1132 See Also 

1133 -------- 

1134 Series.rename : Alter Series index labels or name. 

1135 DataFrame.rename : Alter DataFrame index labels or name. 

1136 Index.rename : Set new names on index. 

1137 

1138 Notes 

1139 ----- 

1140 Prior to version 0.21.0, ``rename_axis`` could also be used to change 

1141 the axis *labels* by passing a mapping or scalar. This behavior is 

1142 deprecated and will be removed in a future version. Use ``rename`` 

1143 instead. 

1144 

1145 ``DataFrame.rename_axis`` supports two calling conventions 

1146 

1147 * ``(index=index_mapper, columns=columns_mapper, ...)`` 

1148 * ``(mapper, axis={'index', 'columns'}, ...)`` 

1149 

1150 The first calling convention will only modify the names of 

1151 the index and/or the names of the Index object that is the columns. 

1152 In this case, the parameter ``copy`` is ignored. 

1153 

1154 The second calling convention will modify the names of the 

1155 the corresponding index if mapper is a list or a scalar. 

1156 However, if mapper is dict-like or a function, it will use the 

1157 deprecated behavior of modifying the axis *labels*. 

1158 

1159 We *highly* recommend using keyword arguments to clarify your 

1160 intent. 

1161 

1162 Examples 

1163 -------- 

1164 **Series** 

1165 

1166 >>> s = pd.Series(["dog", "cat", "monkey"]) 

1167 >>> s 

1168 0 dog 

1169 1 cat 

1170 2 monkey 

1171 dtype: object 

1172 >>> s.rename_axis("animal") 

1173 animal 

1174 0 dog 

1175 1 cat 

1176 2 monkey 

1177 dtype: object 

1178 

1179 **DataFrame** 

1180 

1181 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({"num_legs": [4, 4, 2], 

1182 ... "num_arms": [0, 0, 2]}, 

1183 ... ["dog", "cat", "monkey"]) 

1184 >>> df 

1185 num_legs num_arms 

1186 dog 4 0 

1187 cat 4 0 

1188 monkey 2 2 

1189 >>> df = df.rename_axis("animal") 

1190 >>> df 

1191 num_legs num_arms 

1192 animal 

1193 dog 4 0 

1194 cat 4 0 

1195 monkey 2 2 

1196 >>> df = df.rename_axis("limbs", axis="columns") 

1197 >>> df 

1198 limbs num_legs num_arms 

1199 animal 

1200 dog 4 0 

1201 cat 4 0 

1202 monkey 2 2 

1203 

1204 **MultiIndex** 

1205 

1206 >>> df.index = pd.MultiIndex.from_product([['mammal'], 

1207 ... ['dog', 'cat', 'monkey']], 

1208 ... names=['type', 'name']) 

1209 >>> df 

1210 limbs num_legs num_arms 

1211 type name 

1212 mammal dog 4 0 

1213 cat 4 0 

1214 monkey 2 2 

1215 

1216 >>> df.rename_axis(index={'type': 'class'}) 

1217 limbs num_legs num_arms 

1218 class name 

1219 mammal dog 4 0 

1220 cat 4 0 

1221 monkey 2 2 

1222 

1223 >>> df.rename_axis(columns=str.upper) 

1224 LIMBS num_legs num_arms 

1225 type name 

1226 mammal dog 4 0 

1227 cat 4 0 

1228 monkey 2 2 

1229 """ 

1230 axes, kwargs = self._construct_axes_from_arguments( 

1231 (), kwargs, sentinel=sentinel) 

1232 copy = kwargs.pop('copy', True) 

1233 inplace = kwargs.pop('inplace', False) 

1234 axis = kwargs.pop('axis', 0) 

1235 if axis is not None: 

1236 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

1237 

1238 if kwargs: 

1239 raise TypeError('rename_axis() got an unexpected keyword ' 

1240 'argument "{0}"'.format(list(kwargs.keys())[0])) 

1241 

1242 inplace = validate_bool_kwarg(inplace, 'inplace') 

1243 

1244 if (mapper is not sentinel): 

1245 # Use v0.23 behavior if a scalar or list 

1246 non_mapper = is_scalar(mapper) or (is_list_like(mapper) and not 

1247 is_dict_like(mapper)) 

1248 if non_mapper: 

1249 return self._set_axis_name(mapper, axis=axis, inplace=inplace) 

1250 else: 

1251 # Deprecated (v0.21) behavior is if mapper is specified, 

1252 # and not a list or scalar, then call rename 

1253 msg = ("Using 'rename_axis' to alter labels is deprecated. " 

1254 "Use '.rename' instead") 

1255 warnings.warn(msg, FutureWarning, stacklevel=3) 

1256 axis = self._get_axis_name(axis) 

1257 d = {'copy': copy, 'inplace': inplace} 

1258 d[axis] = mapper 

1259 return self.rename(**d) 

1260 else: 

1261 # Use new behavior. Means that index and/or columns 

1262 # is specified 

1263 result = self if inplace else self.copy(deep=copy) 

1264 

1265 for axis in lrange(self._AXIS_LEN): 

1266 v = axes.get(self._AXIS_NAMES[axis]) 

1267 if v is sentinel: 

1268 continue 

1269 non_mapper = is_scalar(v) or (is_list_like(v) and not 

1270 is_dict_like(v)) 

1271 if non_mapper: 

1272 newnames = v 

1273 else: 

1274 f = com._get_rename_function(v) 

1275 curnames = self._get_axis(axis).names 

1276 newnames = [f(name) for name in curnames] 

1277 result._set_axis_name(newnames, axis=axis, 

1278 inplace=True) 

1279 if not inplace: 

1280 return result 

1281 

1282 def _set_axis_name(self, name, axis=0, inplace=False): 

1283 """ 

1284 Set the name(s) of the axis. 

1285 

1286 Parameters 

1287 ---------- 

1288 name : str or list of str 

1289 Name(s) to set. 

1290 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0 

1291 The axis to set the label. The value 0 or 'index' specifies index, 

1292 and the value 1 or 'columns' specifies columns. 

1293 inplace : bool, default False 

1294 If `True`, do operation inplace and return None. 

1295 

1296 .. versionadded:: 0.21.0 

1297 

1298 Returns 

1299 ------- 

1300 Series, DataFrame, or None 

1301 The same type as the caller or `None` if `inplace` is `True`. 

1302 

1303 See Also 

1304 -------- 

1305 DataFrame.rename : Alter the axis labels of :class:`DataFrame`. 

1306 Series.rename : Alter the index labels or set the index name 

1307 of :class:`Series`. 

1308 Index.rename : Set the name of :class:`Index` or :class:`MultiIndex`. 

1309 

1310 Examples 

1311 -------- 

1312 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({"num_legs": [4, 4, 2]}, 

1313 ... ["dog", "cat", "monkey"]) 

1314 >>> df 

1315 num_legs 

1316 dog 4 

1317 cat 4 

1318 monkey 2 

1319 >>> df._set_axis_name("animal") 

1320 num_legs 

1321 animal 

1322 dog 4 

1323 cat 4 

1324 monkey 2 

1325 >>> df.index = pd.MultiIndex.from_product( 

1326 ... [["mammal"], ['dog', 'cat', 'monkey']]) 

1327 >>> df._set_axis_name(["type", "name"]) 

1328 legs 

1329 type name 

1330 mammal dog 4 

1331 cat 4 

1332 monkey 2 

1333 """ 

1334 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

1335 idx = self._get_axis(axis).set_names(name) 

1336 

1337 inplace = validate_bool_kwarg(inplace, 'inplace') 

1338 renamed = self if inplace else self.copy() 

1339 renamed.set_axis(idx, axis=axis, inplace=True) 

1340 if not inplace: 

1341 return renamed 

1342 

1343 # ---------------------------------------------------------------------- 

1344 # Comparison Methods 

1345 

1346 def _indexed_same(self, other): 

1347 return all(self._get_axis(a).equals(other._get_axis(a)) 

1348 for a in self._AXIS_ORDERS) 

1349 

1350 def equals(self, other): 

1351 """ 

1352 Test whether two objects contain the same elements. 

1353 

1354 This function allows two Series or DataFrames to be compared against 

1355 each other to see if they have the same shape and elements. NaNs in 

1356 the same location are considered equal. The column headers do not 

1357 need to have the same type, but the elements within the columns must 

1358 be the same dtype. 

1359 

1360 Parameters 

1361 ---------- 

1362 other : Series or DataFrame 

1363 The other Series or DataFrame to be compared with the first. 

1364 

1365 Returns 

1366 ------- 

1367 bool 

1368 True if all elements are the same in both objects, False 

1369 otherwise. 

1370 

1371 See Also 

1372 -------- 

1373 Series.eq : Compare two Series objects of the same length 

1374 and return a Series where each element is True if the element 

1375 in each Series is equal, False otherwise. 

1376 DataFrame.eq : Compare two DataFrame objects of the same shape and 

1377 return a DataFrame where each element is True if the respective 

1378 element in each DataFrame is equal, False otherwise. 

1379 assert_series_equal : Return True if left and right Series are equal, 

1380 False otherwise. 

1381 assert_frame_equal : Return True if left and right DataFrames are 

1382 equal, False otherwise. 

1383 numpy.array_equal : Return True if two arrays have the same shape 

1384 and elements, False otherwise. 

1385 

1386 Notes 

1387 ----- 

1388 This function requires that the elements have the same dtype as their 

1389 respective elements in the other Series or DataFrame. However, the 

1390 column labels do not need to have the same type, as long as they are 

1391 still considered equal. 

1392 

1393 Examples 

1394 -------- 

1395 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({1: [10], 2: [20]}) 

1396 >>> df 

1397 1 2 

1398 0 10 20 

1399 

1400 DataFrames df and exactly_equal have the same types and values for 

1401 their elements and column labels, which will return True. 

1402 

1403 >>> exactly_equal = pd.DataFrame({1: [10], 2: [20]}) 

1404 >>> exactly_equal 

1405 1 2 

1406 0 10 20 

1407 >>> df.equals(exactly_equal) 

1408 True 

1409 

1410 DataFrames df and different_column_type have the same element 

1411 types and values, but have different types for the column labels, 

1412 which will still return True. 

1413 

1414 >>> different_column_type = pd.DataFrame({1.0: [10], 2.0: [20]}) 

1415 >>> different_column_type 

1416 1.0 2.0 

1417 0 10 20 

1418 >>> df.equals(different_column_type) 

1419 True 

1420 

1421 DataFrames df and different_data_type have different types for the 

1422 same values for their elements, and will return False even though 

1423 their column labels are the same values and types. 

1424 

1425 >>> different_data_type = pd.DataFrame({1: [10.0], 2: [20.0]}) 

1426 >>> different_data_type 

1427 1 2 

1428 0 10.0 20.0 

1429 >>> df.equals(different_data_type) 

1430 False 

1431 """ 

1432 if not isinstance(other, self._constructor): 

1433 return False 

1434 return self._data.equals(other._data) 

1435 

1436 # ------------------------------------------------------------------------- 

1437 # Unary Methods 

1438 

1439 def __neg__(self): 

1440 values = com.values_from_object(self) 

1441 if is_bool_dtype(values): 

1442 arr = operator.inv(values) 

1443 elif (is_numeric_dtype(values) or is_timedelta64_dtype(values) 

1444 or is_object_dtype(values)): 

1445 arr = operator.neg(values) 

1446 else: 

1447 raise TypeError("Unary negative expects numeric dtype, not {}" 

1448 .format(values.dtype)) 

1449 return self.__array_wrap__(arr) 

1450 

1451 def __pos__(self): 

1452 values = com.values_from_object(self) 

1453 if (is_bool_dtype(values) or is_period_arraylike(values)): 

1454 arr = values 

1455 elif (is_numeric_dtype(values) or is_timedelta64_dtype(values) 

1456 or is_object_dtype(values)): 

1457 arr = operator.pos(values) 

1458 else: 

1459 raise TypeError("Unary plus expects numeric dtype, not {}" 

1460 .format(values.dtype)) 

1461 return self.__array_wrap__(arr) 

1462 

1463 def __invert__(self): 

1464 try: 

1465 arr = operator.inv(com.values_from_object(self)) 

1466 return self.__array_wrap__(arr) 

1467 except Exception: 

1468 

1469 # inv fails with 0 len 

1470 if not np.prod(self.shape): 

1471 return self 

1472 

1473 raise 

1474 

1475 def __nonzero__(self): 

1476 raise ValueError("The truth value of a {0} is ambiguous. " 

1477 "Use a.empty, a.bool(), a.item(), a.any() or a.all()." 

1478 .format(self.__class__.__name__)) 

1479 

1480 __bool__ = __nonzero__ 

1481 

1482 def bool(self): 

1483 """ 

1484 Return the bool of a single element PandasObject. 

1485 

1486 This must be a boolean scalar value, either True or False. Raise a 

1487 ValueError if the PandasObject does not have exactly 1 element, or that 

1488 element is not boolean 

1489 """ 

1490 v = self.squeeze() 

1491 if isinstance(v, (bool, np.bool_)): 

1492 return bool(v) 

1493 elif is_scalar(v): 

1494 raise ValueError("bool cannot act on a non-boolean single element " 

1495 "{0}".format(self.__class__.__name__)) 

1496 

1497 self.__nonzero__() 

1498 

1499 def __abs__(self): 

1500 return self.abs() 

1501 

1502 def __round__(self, decimals=0): 

1503 return self.round(decimals) 

1504 

1505 # ------------------------------------------------------------------------- 

1506 # Label or Level Combination Helpers 

1507 # 

1508 # A collection of helper methods for DataFrame/Series operations that 

1509 # accept a combination of column/index labels and levels. All such 

1510 # operations should utilize/extend these methods when possible so that we 

1511 # have consistent precedence and validation logic throughout the library. 

1512 

1513 def _is_level_reference(self, key, axis=0): 

1514 """ 

1515 Test whether a key is a level reference for a given axis. 

1516 

1517 To be considered a level reference, `key` must be a string that: 

1518 - (axis=0): Matches the name of an index level and does NOT match 

1519 a column label. 

1520 - (axis=1): Matches the name of a column level and does NOT match 

1521 an index label. 

1522 

1523 Parameters 

1524 ---------- 

1525 key : str 

1526 Potential level name for the given axis 

1527 axis : int, default 0 

1528 Axis that levels are associated with (0 for index, 1 for columns) 

1529 

1530 Returns 

1531 ------- 

1532 is_level : bool 

1533 """ 

1534 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

1535 

1536 if self.ndim > 2: 

1537 raise NotImplementedError( 

1538 "_is_level_reference is not implemented for {type}" 

1539 .format(type=type(self))) 

1540 

1541 return (key is not None and 

1542 is_hashable(key) and 

1543 key in self.axes[axis].names and 

1544 not self._is_label_reference(key, axis=axis)) 

1545 

1546 def _is_label_reference(self, key, axis=0): 

1547 """ 

1548 Test whether a key is a label reference for a given axis. 

1549 

1550 To be considered a label reference, `key` must be a string that: 

1551 - (axis=0): Matches a column label 

1552 - (axis=1): Matches an index label 

1553 

1554 Parameters 

1555 ---------- 

1556 key: str 

1557 Potential label name 

1558 axis: int, default 0 

1559 Axis perpendicular to the axis that labels are associated with 

1560 (0 means search for column labels, 1 means search for index labels) 

1561 

1562 Returns 

1563 ------- 

1564 is_label: bool 

1565 """ 

1566 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

1567 other_axes = [ax for ax in range(self._AXIS_LEN) if ax != axis] 

1568 

1569 if self.ndim > 2: 

1570 raise NotImplementedError( 

1571 "_is_label_reference is not implemented for {type}" 

1572 .format(type=type(self))) 

1573 

1574 return (key is not None and 

1575 is_hashable(key) and 

1576 any(key in self.axes[ax] for ax in other_axes)) 

1577 

1578 def _is_label_or_level_reference(self, key, axis=0): 

1579 """ 

1580 Test whether a key is a label or level reference for a given axis. 

1581 

1582 To be considered either a label or a level reference, `key` must be a 

1583 string that: 

1584 - (axis=0): Matches a column label or an index level 

1585 - (axis=1): Matches an index label or a column level 

1586 

1587 Parameters 

1588 ---------- 

1589 key: str 

1590 Potential label or level name 

1591 axis: int, default 0 

1592 Axis that levels are associated with (0 for index, 1 for columns) 

1593 

1594 Returns 

1595 ------- 

1596 is_label_or_level: bool 

1597 """ 

1598 

1599 if self.ndim > 2: 

1600 raise NotImplementedError( 

1601 "_is_label_or_level_reference is not implemented for {type}" 

1602 .format(type=type(self))) 

1603 

1604 return (self._is_level_reference(key, axis=axis) or 

1605 self._is_label_reference(key, axis=axis)) 

1606 

1607 def _check_label_or_level_ambiguity(self, key, axis=0): 

1608 """ 

1609 Check whether `key` is ambiguous. 

1610 

1611 By ambiguous, we mean that it matches both a level of the input 

1612 `axis` and a label of the other axis. 

1613 

1614 Parameters 

1615 ---------- 

1616 key: str or object 

1617 label or level name 

1618 axis: int, default 0 

1619 Axis that levels are associated with (0 for index, 1 for columns) 

1620 

1621 Raises 

1622 ------ 

1623 ValueError: `key` is ambiguous 

1624 """ 

1625 

1626 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

1627 other_axes = [ax for ax in range(self._AXIS_LEN) if ax != axis] 

1628 

1629 if self.ndim > 2: 

1630 raise NotImplementedError( 

1631 "_check_label_or_level_ambiguity is not implemented for {type}" 

1632 .format(type=type(self))) 

1633 

1634 if (key is not None and 

1635 is_hashable(key) and 

1636 key in self.axes[axis].names and 

1637 any(key in self.axes[ax] for ax in other_axes)): 

1638 

1639 # Build an informative and grammatical warning 

1640 level_article, level_type = (('an', 'index') 

1641 if axis == 0 else 

1642 ('a', 'column')) 

1643 

1644 label_article, label_type = (('a', 'column') 

1645 if axis == 0 else 

1646 ('an', 'index')) 

1647 

1648 msg = ("'{key}' is both {level_article} {level_type} level and " 

1649 "{label_article} {label_type} label, which is ambiguous." 

1650 ).format(key=key, 

1651 level_article=level_article, 

1652 level_type=level_type, 

1653 label_article=label_article, 

1654 label_type=label_type) 

1655 raise ValueError(msg) 

1656 

1657 def _get_label_or_level_values(self, key, axis=0): 

1658 """ 

1659 Return a 1-D array of values associated with `key`, a label or level 

1660 from the given `axis`. 

1661 

1662 Retrieval logic: 

1663 - (axis=0): Return column values if `key` matches a column label. 

1664 Otherwise return index level values if `key` matches an index 

1665 level. 

1666 - (axis=1): Return row values if `key` matches an index label. 

1667 Otherwise return column level values if 'key' matches a column 

1668 level 

1669 

1670 Parameters 

1671 ---------- 

1672 key: str 

1673 Label or level name. 

1674 axis: int, default 0 

1675 Axis that levels are associated with (0 for index, 1 for columns) 

1676 

1677 Returns 

1678 ------- 

1679 values: np.ndarray 

1680 

1681 Raises 

1682 ------ 

1683 KeyError 

1684 if `key` matches neither a label nor a level 

1685 ValueError 

1686 if `key` matches multiple labels 

1687 FutureWarning 

1688 if `key` is ambiguous. This will become an ambiguity error in a 

1689 future version 

1690 """ 

1691 

1692 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

1693 other_axes = [ax for ax in range(self._AXIS_LEN) if ax != axis] 

1694 

1695 if self.ndim > 2: 

1696 raise NotImplementedError( 

1697 "_get_label_or_level_values is not implemented for {type}" 

1698 .format(type=type(self))) 

1699 

1700 if self._is_label_reference(key, axis=axis): 

1701 self._check_label_or_level_ambiguity(key, axis=axis) 

1702 values = self.xs(key, axis=other_axes[0])._values 

1703 elif self._is_level_reference(key, axis=axis): 

1704 values = self.axes[axis].get_level_values(key)._values 

1705 else: 

1706 raise KeyError(key) 

1707 

1708 # Check for duplicates 

1709 if values.ndim > 1: 

1710 

1711 if other_axes and isinstance( 

1712 self._get_axis(other_axes[0]), MultiIndex): 

1713 multi_message = ('\n' 

1714 'For a multi-index, the label must be a ' 

1715 'tuple with elements corresponding to ' 

1716 'each level.') 

1717 else: 

1718 multi_message = '' 

1719 

1720 label_axis_name = 'column' if axis == 0 else 'index' 

1721 raise ValueError(("The {label_axis_name} label '{key}' " 

1722 "is not unique.{multi_message}") 

1723 .format(key=key, 

1724 label_axis_name=label_axis_name, 

1725 multi_message=multi_message)) 

1726 

1727 return values 

1728 

1729 def _drop_labels_or_levels(self, keys, axis=0): 

1730 """ 

1731 Drop labels and/or levels for the given `axis`. 

1732 

1733 For each key in `keys`: 

1734 - (axis=0): If key matches a column label then drop the column. 

1735 Otherwise if key matches an index level then drop the level. 

1736 - (axis=1): If key matches an index label then drop the row. 

1737 Otherwise if key matches a column level then drop the level. 

1738 

1739 Parameters 

1740 ---------- 

1741 keys: str or list of str 

1742 labels or levels to drop 

1743 axis: int, default 0 

1744 Axis that levels are associated with (0 for index, 1 for columns) 

1745 

1746 Returns 

1747 ------- 

1748 dropped: DataFrame 

1749 

1750 Raises 

1751 ------ 

1752 ValueError 

1753 if any `keys` match neither a label nor a level 

1754 """ 

1755 

1756 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

1757 

1758 if self.ndim > 2: 

1759 raise NotImplementedError( 

1760 "_drop_labels_or_levels is not implemented for {type}" 

1761 .format(type=type(self))) 

1762 

1763 # Validate keys 

1764 keys = com.maybe_make_list(keys) 

1765 invalid_keys = [k for k in keys if not 

1766 self._is_label_or_level_reference(k, axis=axis)] 

1767 

1768 if invalid_keys: 

1769 raise ValueError(("The following keys are not valid labels or " 

1770 "levels for axis {axis}: {invalid_keys}") 

1771 .format(axis=axis, 

1772 invalid_keys=invalid_keys)) 

1773 

1774 # Compute levels and labels to drop 

1775 levels_to_drop = [k for k in keys 

1776 if self._is_level_reference(k, axis=axis)] 

1777 

1778 labels_to_drop = [k for k in keys 

1779 if not self._is_level_reference(k, axis=axis)] 

1780 

1781 # Perform copy upfront and then use inplace operations below. 

1782 # This ensures that we always perform exactly one copy. 

1783 # ``copy`` and/or ``inplace`` options could be added in the future. 

1784 dropped = self.copy() 

1785 

1786 if axis == 0: 

1787 # Handle dropping index levels 

1788 if levels_to_drop: 

1789 dropped.reset_index(levels_to_drop, drop=True, inplace=True) 

1790 

1791 # Handle dropping columns labels 

1792 if labels_to_drop: 

1793 dropped.drop(labels_to_drop, axis=1, inplace=True) 

1794 else: 

1795 # Handle dropping column levels 

1796 if levels_to_drop: 

1797 if isinstance(dropped.columns, MultiIndex): 

1798 # Drop the specified levels from the MultiIndex 

1799 dropped.columns = dropped.columns.droplevel(levels_to_drop) 

1800 else: 

1801 # Drop the last level of Index by replacing with 

1802 # a RangeIndex 

1803 dropped.columns = RangeIndex(dropped.columns.size) 

1804 

1805 # Handle dropping index labels 

1806 if labels_to_drop: 

1807 dropped.drop(labels_to_drop, axis=0, inplace=True) 

1808 

1809 return dropped 

1810

1815 raise TypeError('{0!r} objects are mutable, thus they cannot be' 

1816 ' hashed'.format(self.__class__.__name__))

1819 """Iterate over infor axis"""

1823 def keys(self): 

1824 """Get the 'info axis' (see Indexing for more) 

1825 

1826 This is index for Series, columns for DataFrame and major_axis for 

1827 Panel. 

1828 """ 

1829 return self._info_axis 

1830 

1831 def iteritems(self): 

1832 """Iterate over (label, values) on info axis 

1833 

1834 This is index for Series, columns for DataFrame, major_axis for Panel, 

1835 and so on. 

1836 """ 

1837 for h in self._info_axis: 

1838 yield h, self[h]

1843

1848 @property 

1849 def empty(self): 

1850 """ 

1851 Indicator whether DataFrame is empty. 

1852 

1853 True if DataFrame is entirely empty (no items), meaning any of the 

1854 axes are of length 0. 

1855 

1856 Returns 

1857 ------- 

1858 bool 

1859 If DataFrame is empty, return True, if not return False. 

1860 

1861 See Also 

1862 -------- 

1863 pandas.Series.dropna 

1864 pandas.DataFrame.dropna 

1865 

1866 Notes 

1867 ----- 

1868 If DataFrame contains only NaNs, it is still not considered empty. See 

1869 the example below. 

1870 

1871 Examples 

1872 -------- 

1873 An example of an actual empty DataFrame. Notice the index is empty: 

1874 

1875 >>> df_empty = pd.DataFrame({'A' : []}) 

1876 >>> df_empty 

1877 Empty DataFrame 

1878 Columns: [A] 

1879 Index: [] 

1880 >>> df_empty.empty 

1881 True 

1882 

1883 If we only have NaNs in our DataFrame, it is not considered empty! We 

1884 will need to drop the NaNs to make the DataFrame empty: 

1885 

1886 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'A' : [np.nan]}) 

1887 >>> df 

1888 A 

1889 0 NaN 

1890 >>> df.empty 

1891 False 

1892 >>> df.dropna().empty 

1893 True 

1894 """ 

1895 return any(len(self._get_axis(a)) == 0 for a in self._AXIS_ORDERS)

1926 # ---------------------------------------------------------------------- 

1927 # Picklability 

1928 

1929 def __getstate__(self): 

1930 meta = {k: getattr(self, k, None) for k in self._metadata} 

1931 return dict(_data=self._data, _typ=self._typ, _metadata=self._metadata, 

1932 **meta) 

1933 

1934 def __setstate__(self, state): 

1935 

1936 if isinstance(state, BlockManager): 

1937 self._data = state 

1938 elif isinstance(state, dict): 

1939 typ = state.get('_typ') 

1940 if typ is not None: 

1941 

1942 # set in the order of internal names 

1943 # to avoid definitional recursion 

1944 # e.g. say fill_value needing _data to be 

1945 # defined 

1946 meta = set(self._internal_names + self._metadata) 

1947 for k in list(meta): 

1948 if k in state: 

1949 v = state[k] 

1950 object.__setattr__(self, k, v) 

1951 

1952 for k, v in state.items(): 

1953 if k not in meta: 

1954 object.__setattr__(self, k, v) 

1955 

1956 else: 

1957 self._unpickle_series_compat(state) 

1958 elif isinstance(state[0], dict): 

1959 if len(state) == 5: 

1960 self._unpickle_sparse_frame_compat(state) 

1961 else: 

1962 self._unpickle_frame_compat(state) 

1963 elif len(state) == 4: 

1964 self._unpickle_panel_compat(state) 

1965 elif len(state) == 2: 

1966 self._unpickle_series_compat(state) 

1967 else: # pragma: no cover 

1968 # old pickling format, for compatibility 

1969 self._unpickle_matrix_compat(state) 

1970 

1971 self._item_cache = {} 

1972 

1973 # ---------------------------------------------------------------------- 

1974 # Rendering Methods 

1975 

1976 def __unicode__(self): 

1977 # unicode representation based upon iterating over self 

1978 # (since, by definition, `PandasContainers` are iterable) 

1979 prepr = '[%s]' % ','.join(map(pprint_thing, self)) 

1980 return '%s(%s)' % (self.__class__.__name__, prepr) 

1981 

1982 def _repr_latex_(self): 

1983 """ 

1984 Returns a LaTeX representation for a particular object. 

1985 Mainly for use with nbconvert (jupyter notebook conversion to pdf). 

1986 """ 

1987 if config.get_option('display.latex.repr'): 

1988 return self.to_latex() 

1989 else: 

1990 return None 

1991 

1992 def _repr_data_resource_(self): 

1993 """ 

1994 Not a real Jupyter special repr method, but we use the same 

1995 naming convention. 

1996 """ 

1997 if config.get_option("display.html.table_schema"): 

1998 data = self.head(config.get_option('display.max_rows')) 

1999 payload = json.loads(data.to_json(orient='table'), 

2000 object_pairs_hook=collections.OrderedDict) 

2001 return payload

2006 _shared_docs['to_excel'] = """ 

2007 Write %(klass)s to an Excel sheet. 

2008 

2009 To write a single %(klass)s to an Excel .xlsx file it is only necessary to 

2010 specify a target file name. To write to multiple sheets it is necessary to 

2011 create an `ExcelWriter` object with a target file name, and specify a sheet 

2012 in the file to write to. 

2013 

2014 Multiple sheets may be written to by specifying unique `sheet_name`. 

2015 With all data written to the file it is necessary to save the changes. 

2016 Note that creating an `ExcelWriter` object with a file name that already 

2017 exists will result in the contents of the existing file being erased. 

2018 

2019 Parameters 

2020 ---------- 

2021 excel_writer : str or ExcelWriter object 

2022 File path or existing ExcelWriter. 

2023 sheet_name : str, default 'Sheet1' 

2024 Name of sheet which will contain DataFrame. 

2025 na_rep : str, default '' 

2026 Missing data representation. 

2027 float_format : str, optional 

2028 Format string for floating point numbers. For example 

2029 ``float_format="%%.2f"`` will format 0.1234 to 0.12. 

2030 columns : sequence or list of str, optional 

2031 Columns to write. 

2032 header : bool or list of str, default True 

2033 Write out the column names. If a list of string is given it is 

2034 assumed to be aliases for the column names. 

2035 index : bool, default True 

2036 Write row names (index). 

2037 index_label : str or sequence, optional 

2038 Column label for index column(s) if desired. If not specified, and 

2039 `header` and `index` are True, then the index names are used. A 

2040 sequence should be given if the DataFrame uses MultiIndex. 

2041 startrow : int, default 0 

2042 Upper left cell row to dump data frame. 

2043 startcol : int, default 0 

2044 Upper left cell column to dump data frame. 

2045 engine : str, optional 

2046 Write engine to use, 'openpyxl' or 'xlsxwriter'. You can also set this 

2047 via the options ``io.excel.xlsx.writer``, ``io.excel.xls.writer``, and 

2048 ``io.excel.xlsm.writer``. 

2049 merge_cells : bool, default True 

2050 Write MultiIndex and Hierarchical Rows as merged cells. 

2051 encoding : str, optional 

2052 Encoding of the resulting excel file. Only necessary for xlwt, 

2053 other writers support unicode natively. 

2054 inf_rep : str, default 'inf' 

2055 Representation for infinity (there is no native representation for 

2056 infinity in Excel). 

2057 verbose : bool, default True 

2058 Display more information in the error logs. 

2059 freeze_panes : tuple of int (length 2), optional 

2060 Specifies the one-based bottommost row and rightmost column that 

2061 is to be frozen. 

2062 

2063 .. versionadded:: 0.20.0. 

2064 

2065 See Also 

2066 -------- 

2067 to_csv : Write DataFrame to a comma-separated values (csv) file. 

2068 ExcelWriter : Class for writing DataFrame objects into excel sheets. 

2069 read_excel : Read an Excel file into a pandas DataFrame. 

2070 read_csv : Read a comma-separated values (csv) file into DataFrame. 

2071 

2072 Notes 

2073 ----- 

2074 For compatibility with :meth:`~DataFrame.to_csv`, 

2075 to_excel serializes lists and dicts to strings before writing. 

2076 

2077 Once a workbook has been saved it is not possible write further data 

2078 without rewriting the whole workbook. 

2079 

2080 Examples 

2081 -------- 

2082 

2083 Create, write to and save a workbook: 

2084 

2085 >>> df1 = pd.DataFrame([['a', 'b'], ['c', 'd']], 

2086 ... index=['row 1', 'row 2'], 

2087 ... columns=['col 1', 'col 2']) 

2088 >>> df1.to_excel("output.xlsx") # doctest: +SKIP 

2089 

2090 To specify the sheet name: 

2091 

2092 >>> df1.to_excel("output.xlsx", 

2093 ... sheet_name='Sheet_name_1') # doctest: +SKIP 

2094 

2095 If you wish to write to more than one sheet in the workbook, it is 

2096 necessary to specify an ExcelWriter object: 

2097 

2098 >>> df2 = df1.copy() 

2099 >>> with pd.ExcelWriter('output.xlsx') as writer: # doctest: +SKIP 

2100 ... df1.to_excel(writer, sheet_name='Sheet_name_1') 

2101 ... df2.to_excel(writer, sheet_name='Sheet_name_2') 

2102 

2103 To set the library that is used to write the Excel file, 

2104 you can pass the `engine` keyword (the default engine is 

2105 automatically chosen depending on the file extension): 

2106 

2107 >>> df1.to_excel('output1.xlsx', engine='xlsxwriter') # doctest: +SKIP 

2108 """ 

2109 

2110 @Appender(_shared_docs["to_excel"] % dict(klass="object")) 

2111 def to_excel(self, excel_writer, sheet_name="Sheet1", na_rep="", 

2112 float_format=None, columns=None, header=True, index=True, 

2113 index_label=None, startrow=0, startcol=0, engine=None, 

2114 merge_cells=True, encoding=None, inf_rep="inf", verbose=True, 

2115 freeze_panes=None): 

2116 df = self if isinstance(self, ABCDataFrame) else self.to_frame() 

2117 

2118 from pandas.io.formats.excel import ExcelFormatter 

2119 formatter = ExcelFormatter(df, na_rep=na_rep, cols=columns, 

2120 header=header, 

2121 float_format=float_format, index=index, 

2122 index_label=index_label, 

2123 merge_cells=merge_cells, 

2124 inf_rep=inf_rep) 

2125 formatter.write(excel_writer, sheet_name=sheet_name, startrow=startrow, 

2126 startcol=startcol, freeze_panes=freeze_panes, 

2127 engine=engine) 

2128 

2129 def to_json(self, path_or_buf=None, orient=None, date_format=None, 

2130 double_precision=10, force_ascii=True, date_unit='ms', 

2131 default_handler=None, lines=False, compression='infer', 

2132 index=True): 

2133 """ 

2134 Convert the object to a JSON string. 

2135 

2136 Note NaN's and None will be converted to null and datetime objects 

2137 will be converted to UNIX timestamps. 

2138 

2139 Parameters 

2140 ---------- 

2141 path_or_buf : string or file handle, optional 

2142 File path or object. If not specified, the result is returned as 

2143 a string. 

2144 orient : string 

2145 Indication of expected JSON string format. 

2146 

2147 * Series 

2148 

2149 - default is 'index' 

2150 - allowed values are: {'split','records','index','table'} 

2151 

2152 * DataFrame 

2153 

2154 - default is 'columns' 

2155 - allowed values are: 

2156 {'split','records','index','columns','values','table'} 

2157 

2158 * The format of the JSON string 

2159 

2160 - 'split' : dict like {'index' -> [index], 

2161 'columns' -> [columns], 'data' -> [values]} 

2162 - 'records' : list like 

2163 [{column -> value}, ... , {column -> value}] 

2164 - 'index' : dict like {index -> {column -> value}} 

2165 - 'columns' : dict like {column -> {index -> value}} 

2166 - 'values' : just the values array 

2167 - 'table' : dict like {'schema': {schema}, 'data': {data}} 

2168 describing the data, and the data component is 

2169 like ``orient='records'``. 

2170 

2171 .. versionchanged:: 0.20.0 

2172 

2173 date_format : {None, 'epoch', 'iso'} 

2174 Type of date conversion. 'epoch' = epoch milliseconds, 

2175 'iso' = ISO8601. The default depends on the `orient`. For 

2176 ``orient='table'``, the default is 'iso'. For all other orients, 

2177 the default is 'epoch'. 

2178 double_precision : int, default 10 

2179 The number of decimal places to use when encoding 

2180 floating point values. 

2181 force_ascii : bool, default True 

2182 Force encoded string to be ASCII. 

2183 date_unit : string, default 'ms' (milliseconds) 

2184 The time unit to encode to, governs timestamp and ISO8601 

2185 precision. One of 's', 'ms', 'us', 'ns' for second, millisecond, 

2186 microsecond, and nanosecond respectively. 

2187 default_handler : callable, default None 

2188 Handler to call if object cannot otherwise be converted to a 

2189 suitable format for JSON. Should receive a single argument which is 

2190 the object to convert and return a serialisable object. 

2191 lines : bool, default False 

2192 If 'orient' is 'records' write out line delimited json format. Will 

2193 throw ValueError if incorrect 'orient' since others are not list 

2194 like. 

2195 

2196 .. versionadded:: 0.19.0 

2197 

2198 compression : {'infer', 'gzip', 'bz2', 'zip', 'xz', None} 

2199 

2200 A string representing the compression to use in the output file, 

2201 only used when the first argument is a filename. By default, the 

2202 compression is inferred from the filename. 

2203 

2204 .. versionadded:: 0.21.0 

2205 .. versionchanged:: 0.24.0 

2206 'infer' option added and set to default 

2207 index : bool, default True 

2208 Whether to include the index values in the JSON string. Not 

2209 including the index (``index=False``) is only supported when 

2210 orient is 'split' or 'table'. 

2211 

2212 .. versionadded:: 0.23.0 

2213 

2214 See Also 

2215 -------- 

2216 read_json 

2217 

2218 Examples 

2219 -------- 

2220 

2221 >>> df = pd.DataFrame([['a', 'b'], ['c', 'd']], 

2222 ... index=['row 1', 'row 2'], 

2223 ... columns=['col 1', 'col 2']) 

2224 >>> df.to_json(orient='split') 

2225 '{"columns":["col 1","col 2"], 

2226 "index":["row 1","row 2"], 

2227 "data":[["a","b"],["c","d"]]}' 

2228 

2229 Encoding/decoding a Dataframe using ``'records'`` formatted JSON. 

2230 Note that index labels are not preserved with this encoding. 

2231 

2232 >>> df.to_json(orient='records') 

2233 '[{"col 1":"a","col 2":"b"},{"col 1":"c","col 2":"d"}]' 

2234 

2235 Encoding/decoding a Dataframe using ``'index'`` formatted JSON: 

2236 

2237 >>> df.to_json(orient='index') 

2238 '{"row 1":{"col 1":"a","col 2":"b"},"row 2":{"col 1":"c","col 2":"d"}}' 

2239 

2240 Encoding/decoding a Dataframe using ``'columns'`` formatted JSON: 

2241 

2242 >>> df.to_json(orient='columns') 

2243 '{"col 1":{"row 1":"a","row 2":"c"},"col 2":{"row 1":"b","row 2":"d"}}' 

2244 

2245 Encoding/decoding a Dataframe using ``'values'`` formatted JSON: 

2246 

2247 >>> df.to_json(orient='values') 

2248 '[["a","b"],["c","d"]]' 

2249 

2250 Encoding with Table Schema 

2251 

2252 >>> df.to_json(orient='table') 

2253 '{"schema": {"fields": [{"name": "index", "type": "string"}, 

2254 {"name": "col 1", "type": "string"}, 

2255 {"name": "col 2", "type": "string"}], 

2256 "primaryKey": "index", 

2257 "pandas_version": "0.20.0"}, 

2258 "data": [{"index": "row 1", "col 1": "a", "col 2": "b"}, 

2259 {"index": "row 2", "col 1": "c", "col 2": "d"}]}' 

2260 """ 

2261 

2262 from pandas.io import json 

2263 if date_format is None and orient == 'table': 

2264 date_format = 'iso' 

2265 elif date_format is None: 

2266 date_format = 'epoch' 

2267 return json.to_json(path_or_buf=path_or_buf, obj=self, orient=orient, 

2268 date_format=date_format, 

2269 double_precision=double_precision, 

2270 force_ascii=force_ascii, date_unit=date_unit, 

2271 default_handler=default_handler, 

2272 lines=lines, compression=compression, 

2273 index=index) 

2274 

2275 def to_hdf(self, path_or_buf, key, **kwargs): 

2276 """ 

2277 Write the contained data to an HDF5 file using HDFStore. 

2278 

2279 Hierarchical Data Format (HDF) is self-describing, allowing an 

2280 application to interpret the structure and contents of a file with 

2281 no outside information. One HDF file can hold a mix of related objects 

2282 which can be accessed as a group or as individual objects. 

2283 

2284 In order to add another DataFrame or Series to an existing HDF file 

2285 please use append mode and a different a key. 

2286 

2287 For more information see the :ref:`user guide <io.hdf5>`. 

2288 

2289 Parameters 

2290 ---------- 

2291 path_or_buf : str or pandas.HDFStore 

2292 File path or HDFStore object. 

2293 key : str 

2294 Identifier for the group in the store. 

2295 mode : {'a', 'w', 'r+'}, default 'a' 

2296 Mode to open file: 

2297 

2298 - 'w': write, a new file is created (an existing file with 

2299 the same name would be deleted). 

2300 - 'a': append, an existing file is opened for reading and 

2301 writing, and if the file does not exist it is created. 

2302 - 'r+': similar to 'a', but the file must already exist. 

2303 format : {'fixed', 'table'}, default 'fixed' 

2304 Possible values: 

2305 

2306 - 'fixed': Fixed format. Fast writing/reading. Not-appendable, 

2307 nor searchable. 

2308 - 'table': Table format. Write as a PyTables Table structure 

2309 which may perform worse but allow more flexible operations 

2310 like searching / selecting subsets of the data. 

2311 append : bool, default False 

2312 For Table formats, append the input data to the existing. 

2313 data_columns : list of columns or True, optional 

2314 List of columns to create as indexed data columns for on-disk 

2315 queries, or True to use all columns. By default only the axes 

2316 of the object are indexed. See :ref:`io.hdf5-query-data-columns`. 

2317 Applicable only to format='table'. 

2318 complevel : {0-9}, optional 

2319 Specifies a compression level for data. 

2320 A value of 0 disables compression. 

2321 complib : {'zlib', 'lzo', 'bzip2', 'blosc'}, default 'zlib' 

2322 Specifies the compression library to be used. 

2323 As of v0.20.2 these additional compressors for Blosc are supported 

2324 (default if no compressor specified: 'blosc:blosclz'): 

2325 {'blosc:blosclz', 'blosc:lz4', 'blosc:lz4hc', 'blosc:snappy', 

2326 'blosc:zlib', 'blosc:zstd'}. 

2327 Specifying a compression library which is not available issues 

2328 a ValueError. 

2329 fletcher32 : bool, default False 

2330 If applying compression use the fletcher32 checksum. 

2331 dropna : bool, default False 

2332 If true, ALL nan rows will not be written to store. 

2333 errors : str, default 'strict' 

2334 Specifies how encoding and decoding errors are to be handled. 

2335 See the errors argument for :func:`open` for a full list 

2336 of options. 

2337 

2338 See Also 

2339 -------- 

2340 DataFrame.read_hdf : Read from HDF file. 

2341 DataFrame.to_parquet : Write a DataFrame to the binary parquet format. 

2342 DataFrame.to_sql : Write to a sql table. 

2343 DataFrame.to_feather : Write out feather-format for DataFrames. 

2344 DataFrame.to_csv : Write out to a csv file. 

2345 

2346 Examples 

2347 -------- 

2348 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'A': [1, 2, 3], 'B': [4, 5, 6]}, 

2349 ... index=['a', 'b', 'c']) 

2350 >>> df.to_hdf('data.h5', key='df', mode='w') 

2351 

2352 We can add another object to the same file: 

2353 

2354 >>> s = pd.Series([1, 2, 3, 4]) 

2355 >>> s.to_hdf('data.h5', key='s') 

2356 

2357 Reading from HDF file: 

2358 

2359 >>> pd.read_hdf('data.h5', 'df') 

2360 A B 

2361 a 1 4 

2362 b 2 5 

2363 c 3 6 

2364 >>> pd.read_hdf('data.h5', 's') 

2365 0 1 

2366 1 2 

2367 2 3 

2368 3 4 

2369 dtype: int64 

2370 

2371 Deleting file with data: 

2372 

2373 >>> import os 

2374 >>> os.remove('data.h5') 

2375 """ 

2376 from pandas.io import pytables 

2377 return pytables.to_hdf(path_or_buf, key, self, **kwargs) 

2378 

2379 def to_msgpack(self, path_or_buf=None, encoding='utf-8', **kwargs): 

2380 """ 

2381 Serialize object to input file path using msgpack format. 

2382 

2383 THIS IS AN EXPERIMENTAL LIBRARY and the storage format 

2384 may not be stable until a future release. 

2385 

2386 Parameters 

2387 ---------- 

2388 path : string File path, buffer-like, or None 

2389 if None, return generated string 

2390 append : bool whether to append to an existing msgpack 

2391 (default is False) 

2392 compress : type of compressor (zlib or blosc), default to None (no 

2393 compression) 

2394 """ 

2395 

2396 from pandas.io import packers 

2397 return packers.to_msgpack(path_or_buf, self, encoding=encoding, 

2398 **kwargs) 

2399 

2400 def to_sql(self, name, con, schema=None, if_exists='fail', index=True, 

2401 index_label=None, chunksize=None, dtype=None, method=None): 

2402 """ 

2403 Write records stored in a DataFrame to a SQL database. 

2404 

2405 Databases supported by SQLAlchemy [1]_ are supported. Tables can be 

2406 newly created, appended to, or overwritten. 

2407 

2408 Parameters 

2409 ---------- 

2410 name : string 

2411 Name of SQL table. 

2412 con : sqlalchemy.engine.Engine or sqlite3.Connection 

2413 Using SQLAlchemy makes it possible to use any DB supported by that 

2414 library. Legacy support is provided for sqlite3.Connection objects. 

2415 schema : string, optional 

2416 Specify the schema (if database flavor supports this). If None, use 

2417 default schema. 

2418 if_exists : {'fail', 'replace', 'append'}, default 'fail' 

2419 How to behave if the table already exists. 

2420 

2421 * fail: Raise a ValueError. 

2422 * replace: Drop the table before inserting new values. 

2423 * append: Insert new values to the existing table. 

2424 

2425 index : bool, default True 

2426 Write DataFrame index as a column. Uses `index_label` as the column 

2427 name in the table. 

2428 index_label : string or sequence, default None 

2429 Column label for index column(s). If None is given (default) and 

2430 `index` is True, then the index names are used. 

2431 A sequence should be given if the DataFrame uses MultiIndex. 

2432 chunksize : int, optional 

2433 Rows will be written in batches of this size at a time. By default, 

2434 all rows will be written at once. 

2435 dtype : dict, optional 

2436 Specifying the datatype for columns. The keys should be the column 

2437 names and the values should be the SQLAlchemy types or strings for 

2438 the sqlite3 legacy mode. 

2439 method : {None, 'multi', callable}, default None 

2440 Controls the SQL insertion clause used: 

2441 

2442 * None : Uses standard SQL ``INSERT`` clause (one per row). 

2443 * 'multi': Pass multiple values in a single ``INSERT`` clause. 

2444 * callable with signature ``(pd_table, conn, keys, data_iter)``. 

2445 

2446 Details and a sample callable implementation can be found in the 

2447 section :ref:`insert method <io.sql.method>`. 

2448 

2449 .. versionadded:: 0.24.0 

2450 

2451 Raises 

2452 ------ 

2453 ValueError 

2454 When the table already exists and `if_exists` is 'fail' (the 

2455 default). 

2456 

2457 See Also 

2458 -------- 

2459 read_sql : Read a DataFrame from a table. 

2460 

2461 Notes 

2462 ----- 

2463 Timezone aware datetime columns will be written as 

2464 ``Timestamp with timezone`` type with SQLAlchemy if supported by the 

2465 database. Otherwise, the datetimes will be stored as timezone unaware 

2466 timestamps local to the original timezone. 

2467 

2468 .. versionadded:: 0.24.0 

2469 

2470 References 

2471 ---------- 

2472 .. [1] http://docs.sqlalchemy.org 

2473 .. [2] https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0249/ 

2474 

2475 Examples 

2476 -------- 

2477 

2478 Create an in-memory SQLite database. 

2479 

2480 >>> from sqlalchemy import create_engine 

2481 >>> engine = create_engine('sqlite://', echo=False) 

2482 

2483 Create a table from scratch with 3 rows. 

2484 

2485 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'name' : ['User 1', 'User 2', 'User 3']}) 

2486 >>> df 

2487 name 

2488 0 User 1 

2489 1 User 2 

2490 2 User 3 

2491 

2492 >>> df.to_sql('users', con=engine) 

2493 >>> engine.execute("SELECT * FROM users").fetchall() 

2494 [(0, 'User 1'), (1, 'User 2'), (2, 'User 3')] 

2495 

2496 >>> df1 = pd.DataFrame({'name' : ['User 4', 'User 5']}) 

2497 >>> df1.to_sql('users', con=engine, if_exists='append') 

2498 >>> engine.execute("SELECT * FROM users").fetchall() 

2499 [(0, 'User 1'), (1, 'User 2'), (2, 'User 3'), 

2500 (0, 'User 4'), (1, 'User 5')] 

2501 

2502 Overwrite the table with just ``df1``. 

2503 

2504 >>> df1.to_sql('users', con=engine, if_exists='replace', 

2505 ... index_label='id') 

2506 >>> engine.execute("SELECT * FROM users").fetchall() 

2507 [(0, 'User 4'), (1, 'User 5')] 

2508 

2509 Specify the dtype (especially useful for integers with missing values). 

2510 Notice that while pandas is forced to store the data as floating point, 

2511 the database supports nullable integers. When fetching the data with 

2512 Python, we get back integer scalars. 

2513 

2514 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({"A": [1, None, 2]}) 

2515 >>> df 

2516 A 

2517 0 1.0 

2518 1 NaN 

2519 2 2.0 

2520 

2521 >>> from sqlalchemy.types import Integer 

2522 >>> df.to_sql('integers', con=engine, index=False, 

2523 ... dtype={"A": Integer()}) 

2524 

2525 >>> engine.execute("SELECT * FROM integers").fetchall() 

2526 [(1,), (None,), (2,)] 

2527 """ 

2528 from pandas.io import sql 

2529 sql.to_sql(self, name, con, schema=schema, if_exists=if_exists, 

2530 index=index, index_label=index_label, chunksize=chunksize, 

2531 dtype=dtype, method=method) 

2532 

2533 def to_pickle(self, path, compression='infer', 

2534 protocol=pkl.HIGHEST_PROTOCOL): 

2535 """ 

2536 Pickle (serialize) object to file. 

2537 

2538 Parameters 

2539 ---------- 

2540 path : str 

2541 File path where the pickled object will be stored. 

2542 compression : {'infer', 'gzip', 'bz2', 'zip', 'xz', None}, \ 

2543 default 'infer' 

2544 A string representing the compression to use in the output file. By 

2545 default, infers from the file extension in specified path. 

2546 

2547 .. versionadded:: 0.20.0 

2548 protocol : int 

2549 Int which indicates which protocol should be used by the pickler, 

2550 default HIGHEST_PROTOCOL (see [1]_ paragraph 12.1.2). The possible 

2551 values for this parameter depend on the version of Python. For 

2552 Python 2.x, possible values are 0, 1, 2. For Python>=3.0, 3 is a 

2553 valid value. For Python >= 3.4, 4 is a valid value. A negative 

2554 value for the protocol parameter is equivalent to setting its value 

2555 to HIGHEST_PROTOCOL. 

2556 

2557 .. [1] https://docs.python.org/3/library/pickle.html 

2558 .. versionadded:: 0.21.0 

2559 

2560 See Also 

2561 -------- 

2562 read_pickle : Load pickled pandas object (or any object) from file. 

2563 DataFrame.to_hdf : Write DataFrame to an HDF5 file. 

2564 DataFrame.to_sql : Write DataFrame to a SQL database. 

2565 DataFrame.to_parquet : Write a DataFrame to the binary parquet format. 

2566 

2567 Examples 

2568 -------- 

2569 >>> original_df = pd.DataFrame({"foo": range(5), "bar": range(5, 10)}) 

2570 >>> original_df 

2571 foo bar 

2572 0 0 5 

2573 1 1 6 

2574 2 2 7 

2575 3 3 8 

2576 4 4 9 

2577 >>> original_df.to_pickle("./dummy.pkl") 

2578 

2579 >>> unpickled_df = pd.read_pickle("./dummy.pkl") 

2580 >>> unpickled_df 

2581 foo bar 

2582 0 0 5 

2583 1 1 6 

2584 2 2 7 

2585 3 3 8 

2586 4 4 9 

2587 

2588 >>> import os 

2589 >>> os.remove("./dummy.pkl") 

2590 """ 

2591 from pandas.io.pickle import to_pickle 

2592 return to_pickle(self, path, compression=compression, 

2593 protocol=protocol) 

2594 

2595 def to_clipboard(self, excel=True, sep=None, **kwargs): 

2596 r""" 

2597 Copy object to the system clipboard. 

2598 

2599 Write a text representation of object to the system clipboard. 

2600 This can be pasted into Excel, for example. 

2601 

2602 Parameters 

2603 ---------- 

2604 excel : bool, default True 

2605 - True, use the provided separator, writing in a csv format for 

2606 allowing easy pasting into excel. 

2607 - False, write a string representation of the object to the 

2608 clipboard. 

2609 

2610 sep : str, default ``'\t'`` 

2611 Field delimiter. 

2612 **kwargs 

2613 These parameters will be passed to DataFrame.to_csv. 

2614 

2615 See Also 

2616 -------- 

2617 DataFrame.to_csv : Write a DataFrame to a comma-separated values 

2618 (csv) file. 

2619 read_clipboard : Read text from clipboard and pass to read_table. 

2620 

2621 Notes 

2622 ----- 

2623 Requirements for your platform. 

2624 

2625 - Linux : `xclip`, or `xsel` (with `gtk` or `PyQt4` modules) 

2626 - Windows : none 

2627 - OS X : none 

2628 

2629 Examples 

2630 -------- 

2631 Copy the contents of a DataFrame to the clipboard. 

2632 

2633 >>> df = pd.DataFrame([[1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6]], columns=['A', 'B', 'C']) 

2634 >>> df.to_clipboard(sep=',') 

2635 ... # Wrote the following to the system clipboard: 

2636 ... # ,A,B,C 

2637 ... # 0,1,2,3 

2638 ... # 1,4,5,6 

2639 

2640 We can omit the the index by passing the keyword `index` and setting 

2641 it to false. 

2642 

2643 >>> df.to_clipboard(sep=',', index=False) 

2644 ... # Wrote the following to the system clipboard: 

2645 ... # A,B,C 

2646 ... # 1,2,3 

2647 ... # 4,5,6 

2648 """ 

2649 from pandas.io import clipboards 

2650 clipboards.to_clipboard(self, excel=excel, sep=sep, **kwargs)
