2652 def to_xarray(self): 

2653 """ 

2654 Return an xarray object from the pandas object. 

2655 

2656 Returns 

2657 ------- 

2658 xarray.DataArray or xarray.Dataset 

2659 Data in the pandas structure converted to Dataset if the object is 

2660 a DataFrame, or a DataArray if the object is a Series. 

2661 

2662 See Also 

2663 -------- 

2664 DataFrame.to_hdf : Write DataFrame to an HDF5 file. 

2665 DataFrame.to_parquet : Write a DataFrame to the binary parquet format. 

2666 

2667 Notes 

2668 ----- 

2669 See the `xarray docs <http://xarray.pydata.org/en/stable/>`__ 

2670 

2671 Examples 

2672 -------- 

2673 >>> df = pd.DataFrame([('falcon', 'bird', 389.0, 2), 

2674 ... ('parrot', 'bird', 24.0, 2), 

2675 ... ('lion', 'mammal', 80.5, 4), 

2676 ... ('monkey', 'mammal', np.nan, 4)], 

2677 ... columns=['name', 'class', 'max_speed', 

2678 ... 'num_legs']) 

2679 >>> df 

2680 name class max_speed num_legs 

2681 0 falcon bird 389.0 2 

2682 1 parrot bird 24.0 2 

2683 2 lion mammal 80.5 4 

2684 3 monkey mammal NaN 4 

2685 

2686 >>> df.to_xarray() 

2687 <xarray.Dataset> 

2688 Dimensions: (index: 4) 

2689 Coordinates: 

2690 * index (index) int64 0 1 2 3 

2691 Data variables: 

2692 name (index) object 'falcon' 'parrot' 'lion' 'monkey' 

2693 class (index) object 'bird' 'bird' 'mammal' 'mammal' 

2694 max_speed (index) float64 389.0 24.0 80.5 nan 

2695 num_legs (index) int64 2 2 4 4 

2696 

2697 >>> df['max_speed'].to_xarray() 

2698 <xarray.DataArray 'max_speed' (index: 4)> 

2699 array([389. , 24. , 80.5, nan]) 

2700 Coordinates: 

2701 * index (index) int64 0 1 2 3 

2702 

2703 >>> dates = pd.to_datetime(['2018-01-01', '2018-01-01', 

2704 ... '2018-01-02', '2018-01-02']) 

2705 >>> df_multiindex = pd.DataFrame({'date': dates, 

2706 ... 'animal': ['falcon', 'parrot', 'falcon', 

2707 ... 'parrot'], 

2708 ... 'speed': [350, 18, 361, 15]}).set_index(['date', 

2709 ... 'animal']) 

2710 >>> df_multiindex 

2711 speed 

2712 date animal 

2713 2018-01-01 falcon 350 

2714 parrot 18 

2715 2018-01-02 falcon 361 

2716 parrot 15 

2717 

2718 >>> df_multiindex.to_xarray() 

2719 <xarray.Dataset>

2749 def to_latex(self, buf=None, columns=None, col_space=None, header=True, 

2750 index=True, na_rep='NaN', formatters=None, float_format=None, 

2751 sparsify=None, index_names=True, bold_rows=False, 

2752 column_format=None, longtable=None, escape=None, 

2753 encoding=None, decimal='.', multicolumn=None, 

2754 multicolumn_format=None, multirow=None): 

2755 r""" 

2756 Render an object to a LaTeX tabular environment table. 

2757 

2758 Render an object to a tabular environment table. You can splice 

2759 this into a LaTeX document. Requires \usepackage{booktabs}. 

2760 

2761 .. versionchanged:: 0.20.2 

2762 Added to Series 

2763 

2764 Parameters 

2765 ---------- 

2766 buf : file descriptor or None 

2767 Buffer to write to. If None, the output is returned as a string. 

2768 columns : list of label, optional 

2769 The subset of columns to write. Writes all columns by default. 

2770 col_space : int, optional 

2771 The minimum width of each column. 

2772 header : bool or list of str, default True 

2773 Write out the column names. If a list of strings is given, 

2774 it is assumed to be aliases for the column names. 

2775 index : bool, default True 

2776 Write row names (index). 

2777 na_rep : str, default 'NaN' 

2778 Missing data representation. 

2779 formatters : list of functions or dict of {str: function}, optional 

2780 Formatter functions to apply to columns' elements by position or 

2781 name. The result of each function must be a unicode string. 

2782 List must be of length equal to the number of columns. 

2783 float_format : str, optional 

2784 Format string for floating point numbers. 

2785 sparsify : bool, optional 

2786 Set to False for a DataFrame with a hierarchical index to print 

2787 every multiindex key at each row. By default, the value will be 

2788 read from the config module. 

2789 index_names : bool, default True 

2790 Prints the names of the indexes. 

2791 bold_rows : bool, default False 

2792 Make the row labels bold in the output. 

2793 column_format : str, optional 

2794 The columns format as specified in `LaTeX table format 

2795 <https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/LaTeX/Tables>`__ e.g. 'rcl' for 3 

2796 columns. By default, 'l' will be used for all columns except 

2797 columns of numbers, which default to 'r'. 

2798 longtable : bool, optional 

2799 By default, the value will be read from the pandas config 

2800 module. Use a longtable environment instead of tabular. Requires 

2801 adding a \usepackage{longtable} to your LaTeX preamble. 

2802 escape : bool, optional 

2803 By default, the value will be read from the pandas config 

2804 module. When set to False prevents from escaping latex special 

2805 characters in column names. 

2806 encoding : str, optional 

2807 A string representing the encoding to use in the output file, 

2808 defaults to 'ascii' on Python 2 and 'utf-8' on Python 3. 

2809 decimal : str, default '.' 

2810 Character recognized as decimal separator, e.g. ',' in Europe. 

2811 .. versionadded:: 0.18.0 

2812 multicolumn : bool, default True 

2813 Use \multicolumn to enhance MultiIndex columns. 

2814 The default will be read from the config module. 

2815 .. versionadded:: 0.20.0 

2816 multicolumn_format : str, default 'l' 

2817 The alignment for multicolumns, similar to `column_format` 

2818 The default will be read from the config module. 

2819 .. versionadded:: 0.20.0 

2820 multirow : bool, default False 

2821 Use \multirow to enhance MultiIndex rows. Requires adding a 

2822 \usepackage{multirow} to your LaTeX preamble. Will print 

2823 centered labels (instead of top-aligned) across the contained 

2824 rows, separating groups via clines. The default will be read 

2825 from the pandas config module. 

2826 .. versionadded:: 0.20.0 

2827 

2828 Returns 

2829 ------- 

2830 str or None 

2831 If buf is None, returns the resulting LateX format as a 

2832 string. Otherwise returns None. 

2833 

2834 See Also 

2835 -------- 

2836 DataFrame.to_string : Render a DataFrame to a console-friendly 

2837 tabular output. 

2838 DataFrame.to_html : Render a DataFrame as an HTML table. 

2839 

2840 Examples 

2841 -------- 

2842 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'name': ['Raphael', 'Donatello'], 

2843 ... 'mask': ['red', 'purple'], 

2844 ... 'weapon': ['sai', 'bo staff']}) 

2845 >>> df.to_latex(index=False) # doctest: +NORMALIZE_WHITESPACE 

2846 '\\begin{tabular}{lll}\n\\toprule\n name & mask & weapon 

2847 \\\\\n\\midrule\n Raphael & red & sai \\\\\n Donatello & 

2848 purple & bo staff \\\\\n\\bottomrule\n\\end{tabular}\n' 

2849 """ 

2850 # Get defaults from the pandas config 

2851 if self.ndim == 1: 

2852 self = self.to_frame() 

2853 if longtable is None: 

2854 longtable = config.get_option("display.latex.longtable") 

2855 if escape is None: 

2856 escape = config.get_option("display.latex.escape") 

2857 if multicolumn is None: 

2858 multicolumn = config.get_option("display.latex.multicolumn") 

2859 if multicolumn_format is None: 

2860 multicolumn_format = config.get_option( 

2861 "display.latex.multicolumn_format") 

2862 if multirow is None: 

2863 multirow = config.get_option("display.latex.multirow") 

2864 

2865 formatter = DataFrameFormatter(self, buf=buf, columns=columns, 

2866 col_space=col_space, na_rep=na_rep, 

2867 header=header, index=index, 

2868 formatters=formatters, 

2869 float_format=float_format, 

2870 bold_rows=bold_rows, 

2871 sparsify=sparsify,

2882 def to_csv(self, path_or_buf=None, sep=",", na_rep='', float_format=None,

2887 escapechar=None, decimal='.'): 

2888 r"""

2890 

2891 .. versionchanged:: 0.24.0 

2892 The order of arguments for Series was changed. 

2893 

2894 Parameters 

2895 ---------- 

2896 path_or_buf : str or file handle, default None 

2897 File path or object, if None is provided the result is returned as 

2898 a string. If a file object is passed it should be opened with 

2899 `newline=''`, disabling universal newlines. 

2900 

2901 .. versionchanged:: 0.24.0 

2902 

2903 Was previously named "path" for Series. 

2904

2906 String of length 1. Field delimiter for the output file. 

2907 na_rep : str, default '' 

2908 Missing data representation. 

2909 float_format : str, default None 

2910 Format string for floating point numbers. 

2911 columns : sequence, optional 

2912 Columns to write. 

2913 header : bool or list of str, default True

2920

2936 'gzip', 'bz2', 'zip', 'xz', None}. If 'infer' and `path_or_buf` 

2937 is path-like, then detect compression from the following 

2938 extensions: '.gz', '.bz2', '.zip' or '.xz'. (otherwise no 

2939 compression). 

2940

2942 

2943 'infer' option added and set to default. 

2944

2946 Defaults to csv.QUOTE_MINIMAL. If you have set a `float_format` 

2947 then floats are converted to strings and thus csv.QUOTE_NONNUMERIC 

2948 will treat them as non-numeric.

2950 String of length 1. Character used to quote fields. 

2951 line_terminator : string, optional

2957 chunksize : int or None 

2958 Rows to write at a time. 

2959 tupleize_cols : bool, default False

2962 in the CSV (if False). 

2963 

2964 .. deprecated:: 0.21.0 

2965 This argument will be removed and will always write each row 

2966 of the multi-index as a separate row in the CSV file. 

2967 date_format : str, default None 

2968 Format string for datetime objects. 

2969 doublequote : bool, default True 

2970 Control quoting of `quotechar` inside a field. 

2971 escapechar : str, default None 

2972 String of length 1. Character used to escape `sep` and `quotechar` 

2973 when appropriate. 

2974 decimal : str, default '.' 

2975 Character recognized as decimal separator. E.g. use ',' for 

2976 European data. 

2977 

2978 Returns 

2979 ------- 

2980 None or str 

2981 If path_or_buf is None, returns the resulting csv format as a 

2982 string. Otherwise returns None. 

2983 

2984 See Also 

2985 -------- 

2986 read_csv : Load a CSV file into a DataFrame. 

2987 to_excel : Load an Excel file into a DataFrame. 

2988 

2989 Examples 

2990 -------- 

2991 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'name': ['Raphael', 'Donatello'], 

2992 ... 'mask': ['red', 'purple'], 

2993 ... 'weapon': ['sai', 'bo staff']}) 

2994 >>> df.to_csv(index=False) 

2995 'name,mask,weapon\nRaphael,red,sai\nDonatello,purple,bo staff\n' 

2996 """

3028 @classmethod 

3029 def _create_indexer(cls, name, indexer): 

3030 """Create an indexer like _name in the class.""" 

3031 if getattr(cls, name, None) is None: 

3032 _indexer = functools.partial(indexer, name)

3035 def get(self, key, default=None): 

3036 """ 

3037 Get item from object for given key (DataFrame column, Panel slice, 

3038 etc.). Returns default value if not found. 

3039 

3040 Parameters 

3041 ---------- 

3042 key : object 

3043 

3044 Returns 

3045 ------- 

3046 value : same type as items contained in object 

3047 """ 

3048 try: 

3049 return self[key] 

3050 except (KeyError, ValueError, IndexError): 

3051 return default 

3052 

3053 def __getitem__(self, item): 

3054 return self._get_item_cache(item) 

3055 

3056 def _get_item_cache(self, item): 

3057 """Return the cached item, item represents a label indexer.""" 

3058 cache = self._item_cache 

3059 res = cache.get(item) 

3060 if res is None: 

3061 values = self._data.get(item) 

3062 res = self._box_item_values(item, values) 

3063 cache[item] = res 

3064 res._set_as_cached(item, self) 

3065 

3066 # for a chain 

3067 res._is_copy = self._is_copy 

3068 return res 

3069 

3070 def _set_as_cached(self, item, cacher): 

3071 """Set the _cacher attribute on the calling object with a weakref to 

3072 cacher. 

3073 """ 

3074 self._cacher = (item, weakref.ref(cacher)) 

3075 

3076 def _reset_cacher(self): 

3077 """Reset the cacher.""" 

3078 if hasattr(self, '_cacher'): 

3079 del self._cacher 

3080 

3081 def _iget_item_cache(self, item): 

3082 """Return the cached item, item represents a positional indexer.""" 

3083 ax = self._info_axis 

3084 if ax.is_unique: 

3085 lower = self._get_item_cache(ax[item]) 

3086 else: 

3087 lower = self._take(item, axis=self._info_axis_number) 

3088 return lower 

3089 

3090 def _box_item_values(self, key, values): 

3091 raise AbstractMethodError(self) 

3092 

3093 def _maybe_cache_changed(self, item, value): 

3094 """The object has called back to us saying maybe it has changed. 

3095 """ 

3096 self._data.set(item, value) 

3097 

3098 @property 

3099 def _is_cached(self): 

3100 """Return boolean indicating if self is cached or not.""" 

3101 return getattr(self, '_cacher', None) is not None 

3102 

3103 def _get_cacher(self): 

3104 """return my cacher or None""" 

3105 cacher = getattr(self, '_cacher', None) 

3106 if cacher is not None: 

3107 cacher = cacher[1]() 

3108 return cacher 

3109 

3110 @property 

3111 def _is_view(self): 

3112 """Return boolean indicating if self is view of another array """ 

3113 return self._data.is_view 

3114 

3115 def _maybe_update_cacher(self, clear=False, verify_is_copy=True): 

3116 """ 

3117 See if we need to update our parent cacher if clear, then clear our 

3118 cache. 

3119 

3120 Parameters 

3121 ---------- 

3122 clear : boolean, default False 

3123 clear the item cache 

3124 verify_is_copy : boolean, default True 

3125 provide is_copy checks 

3126 

3127 """ 

3128 

3129 cacher = getattr(self, '_cacher', None) 

3130 if cacher is not None: 

3131 ref = cacher[1]() 

3132 

3133 # we are trying to reference a dead referant, hence 

3134 # a copy 

3135 if ref is None: 

3136 del self._cacher 

3137 else: 

3138 try: 

3139 ref._maybe_cache_changed(cacher[0], self) 

3140 except Exception: 

3141 pass 

3142 

3143 if verify_is_copy: 

3144 self._check_setitem_copy(stacklevel=5, t='referant') 

3145 

3146 if clear: 

3147 self._clear_item_cache() 

3148 

3149 def _clear_item_cache(self, i=None): 

3150 if i is not None: 

3151 self._item_cache.pop(i, None) 

3152 else: 

3153 self._item_cache.clear() 

3154 

3155 def _slice(self, slobj, axis=0, kind=None): 

3156 """ 

3157 Construct a slice of this container. 

3158 

3159 kind parameter is maintained for compatibility with Series slicing. 

3160 """ 

3161 axis = self._get_block_manager_axis(axis) 

3162 result = self._constructor(self._data.get_slice(slobj, axis=axis)) 

3163 result = result.__finalize__(self) 

3164 

3165 # this could be a view 

3166 # but only in a single-dtyped view slicable case 

3167 is_copy = axis != 0 or result._is_view 

3168 result._set_is_copy(self, copy=is_copy) 

3169 return result 

3170 

3171 def _set_item(self, key, value): 

3172 self._data.set(key, value) 

3173 self._clear_item_cache() 

3174 

3175 def _set_is_copy(self, ref=None, copy=True): 

3176 if not copy: 

3177 self._is_copy = None 

3178 else: 

3179 if ref is not None: 

3180 self._is_copy = weakref.ref(ref) 

3181 else: 

3182 self._is_copy = None 

3183 

3184 def _check_is_chained_assignment_possible(self): 

3185 """ 

3186 Check if we are a view, have a cacher, and are of mixed type. 

3187 If so, then force a setitem_copy check. 

3188 

3189 Should be called just near setting a value 

3190 

3191 Will return a boolean if it we are a view and are cached, but a 

3192 single-dtype meaning that the cacher should be updated following 

3193 setting. 

3194 """ 

3195 if self._is_view and self._is_cached: 

3196 ref = self._get_cacher() 

3197 if ref is not None and ref._is_mixed_type: 

3198 self._check_setitem_copy(stacklevel=4, t='referant', 

3199 force=True) 

3200 return True 

3201 elif self._is_copy: 

3202 self._check_setitem_copy(stacklevel=4, t='referant') 

3203 return False 

3204 

3205 def _check_setitem_copy(self, stacklevel=4, t='setting', force=False): 

3206 """ 

3207 

3208 Parameters 

3209 ---------- 

3210 stacklevel : integer, default 4 

3211 the level to show of the stack when the error is output 

3212 t : string, the type of setting error 

3213 force : boolean, default False 

3214 if True, then force showing an error 

3215 

3216 validate if we are doing a settitem on a chained copy. 

3217 

3218 If you call this function, be sure to set the stacklevel such that the 

3219 user will see the error *at the level of setting* 

3220 

3221 It is technically possible to figure out that we are setting on 

3222 a copy even WITH a multi-dtyped pandas object. In other words, some 

3223 blocks may be views while other are not. Currently _is_view will ALWAYS 

3224 return False for multi-blocks to avoid having to handle this case. 

3225 

3226 df = DataFrame(np.arange(0,9), columns=['count']) 

3227 df['group'] = 'b' 

3228 

3229 # This technically need not raise SettingWithCopy if both are view 

3230 # (which is not # generally guaranteed but is usually True. However, 

3231 # this is in general not a good practice and we recommend using .loc. 

3232 df.iloc[0:5]['group'] = 'a' 

3233 

3234 """ 

3235 

3236 if force or self._is_copy: 

3237 

3238 value = config.get_option('mode.chained_assignment') 

3239 if value is None: 

3240 return 

3241 

3242 # see if the copy is not actually referred; if so, then dissolve 

3243 # the copy weakref 

3244 try: 

3245 gc.collect(2) 

3246 if not gc.get_referents(self._is_copy()): 

3247 self._is_copy = None 

3248 return 

3249 except Exception: 

3250 pass 

3251 

3252 # we might be a false positive 

3253 try: 

3254 if self._is_copy().shape == self.shape: 

3255 self._is_copy = None 

3256 return 

3257 except Exception: 

3258 pass 

3259 

3260 # a custom message 

3261 if isinstance(self._is_copy, string_types): 

3262 t = self._is_copy 

3263 

3264 elif t == 'referant': 

3265 t = ("\n" 

3266 "A value is trying to be set on a copy of a slice from a " 

3267 "DataFrame\n\n" 

3268 "See the caveats in the documentation: " 

3269 "http://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/" 

3270 "indexing.html#indexing-view-versus-copy" 

3271 ) 

3272 

3273 else: 

3274 t = ("\n" 

3275 "A value is trying to be set on a copy of a slice from a " 

3276 "DataFrame.\n" 

3277 "Try using .loc[row_indexer,col_indexer] = value " 

3278 "instead\n\nSee the caveats in the documentation: " 

3279 "http://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/" 

3280 "indexing.html#indexing-view-versus-copy" 

3281 ) 

3282 

3283 if value == 'raise': 

3284 raise com.SettingWithCopyError(t) 

3285 elif value == 'warn': 

3286 warnings.warn(t, com.SettingWithCopyWarning, 

3287 stacklevel=stacklevel) 

3288 

3289 def __delitem__(self, key): 

3290 """ 

3291 Delete item 

3292 """ 

3293 deleted = False 

3294 

3295 maybe_shortcut = False 

3296 if hasattr(self, 'columns') and isinstance(self.columns, MultiIndex): 

3297 try: 

3298 maybe_shortcut = key not in self.columns._engine 

3299 except TypeError: 

3300 pass 

3301 

3302 if maybe_shortcut: 

3303 # Allow shorthand to delete all columns whose first len(key) 

3304 # elements match key: 

3305 if not isinstance(key, tuple): 

3306 key = (key, ) 

3307 for col in self.columns: 

3308 if isinstance(col, tuple) and col[:len(key)] == key: 

3309 del self[col] 

3310 deleted = True 

3311 if not deleted: 

3312 # If the above loop ran and didn't delete anything because 

3313 # there was no match, this call should raise the appropriate 

3314 # exception: 

3315 self._data.delete(key) 

3316 

3317 # delete from the caches 

3318 try: 

3319 del self._item_cache[key] 

3320 except KeyError: 

3321 pass 

3322 

3323 def _take(self, indices, axis=0, is_copy=True): 

3324 """ 

3325 Return the elements in the given *positional* indices along an axis. 

3326 

3327 This means that we are not indexing according to actual values in 

3328 the index attribute of the object. We are indexing according to the 

3329 actual position of the element in the object. 

3330 

3331 This is the internal version of ``.take()`` and will contain a wider 

3332 selection of parameters useful for internal use but not as suitable 

3333 for public usage. 

3334 

3335 Parameters 

3336 ---------- 

3337 indices : array-like 

3338 An array of ints indicating which positions to take. 

3339 axis : int, default 0 

3340 The axis on which to select elements. "0" means that we are 

3341 selecting rows, "1" means that we are selecting columns, etc. 

3342 is_copy : bool, default True 

3343 Whether to return a copy of the original object or not. 

3344 

3345 Returns 

3346 ------- 

3347 taken : same type as caller 

3348 An array-like containing the elements taken from the object. 

3349 

3350 See Also 

3351 -------- 

3352 numpy.ndarray.take 

3353 numpy.take 

3354 """ 

3355 self._consolidate_inplace() 

3356 

3357 new_data = self._data.take(indices, 

3358 axis=self._get_block_manager_axis(axis), 

3359 verify=True) 

3360 result = self._constructor(new_data).__finalize__(self) 

3361 

3362 # Maybe set copy if we didn't actually change the index. 

3363 if is_copy: 

3364 if not result._get_axis(axis).equals(self._get_axis(axis)): 

3365 result._set_is_copy(self) 

3366 

3367 return result 

3368 

3369 def take(self, indices, axis=0, convert=None, is_copy=True, **kwargs): 

3370 """ 

3371 Return the elements in the given *positional* indices along an axis. 

3372 

3373 This means that we are not indexing according to actual values in 

3374 the index attribute of the object. We are indexing according to the 

3375 actual position of the element in the object. 

3376 

3377 Parameters 

3378 ---------- 

3379 indices : array-like 

3380 An array of ints indicating which positions to take. 

3381 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns', None}, default 0 

3382 The axis on which to select elements. ``0`` means that we are 

3383 selecting rows, ``1`` means that we are selecting columns. 

3384 convert : bool, default True 

3385 Whether to convert negative indices into positive ones. 

3386 For example, ``-1`` would map to the ``len(axis) - 1``. 

3387 The conversions are similar to the behavior of indexing a 

3388 regular Python list. 

3389 

3390 .. deprecated:: 0.21.0 

3391 In the future, negative indices will always be converted. 

3392 

3393 is_copy : bool, default True 

3394 Whether to return a copy of the original object or not. 

3395 **kwargs 

3396 For compatibility with :meth:`numpy.take`. Has no effect on the 

3397 output. 

3398 

3399 Returns 

3400 ------- 

3401 taken : same type as caller 

3402 An array-like containing the elements taken from the object. 

3403 

3404 See Also 

3405 -------- 

3406 DataFrame.loc : Select a subset of a DataFrame by labels. 

3407 DataFrame.iloc : Select a subset of a DataFrame by positions. 

3408 numpy.take : Take elements from an array along an axis. 

3409 

3410 Examples 

3411 -------- 

3412 >>> df = pd.DataFrame([('falcon', 'bird', 389.0), 

3413 ... ('parrot', 'bird', 24.0), 

3414 ... ('lion', 'mammal', 80.5), 

3415 ... ('monkey', 'mammal', np.nan)], 

3416 ... columns=['name', 'class', 'max_speed'], 

3417 ... index=[0, 2, 3, 1]) 

3418 >>> df 

3419 name class max_speed 

3420 0 falcon bird 389.0 

3421 2 parrot bird 24.0 

3422 3 lion mammal 80.5 

3423 1 monkey mammal NaN 

3424 

3425 Take elements at positions 0 and 3 along the axis 0 (default). 

3426 

3427 Note how the actual indices selected (0 and 1) do not correspond to 

3428 our selected indices 0 and 3. That's because we are selecting the 0th 

3429 and 3rd rows, not rows whose indices equal 0 and 3. 

3430 

3431 >>> df.take([0, 3]) 

3432 name class max_speed 

3433 0 falcon bird 389.0 

3434 1 monkey mammal NaN 

3435 

3436 Take elements at indices 1 and 2 along the axis 1 (column selection). 

3437 

3438 >>> df.take([1, 2], axis=1) 

3439 class max_speed 

3440 0 bird 389.0 

3441 2 bird 24.0 

3442 3 mammal 80.5 

3443 1 mammal NaN 

3444 

3445 We may take elements using negative integers for positive indices, 

3446 starting from the end of the object, just like with Python lists. 

3447 

3448 >>> df.take([-1, -2]) 

3449 name class max_speed 

3450 1 monkey mammal NaN 

3451 3 lion mammal 80.5 

3452 """ 

3453 if convert is not None: 

3454 msg = ("The 'convert' parameter is deprecated " 

3455 "and will be removed in a future version.") 

3456 warnings.warn(msg, FutureWarning, stacklevel=2) 

3457 

3458 nv.validate_take(tuple(), kwargs) 

3459 return self._take(indices, axis=axis, is_copy=is_copy) 

3460 

3461 def xs(self, key, axis=0, level=None, drop_level=True): 

3462 """ 

3463 Return cross-section from the Series/DataFrame. 

3464 

3465 This method takes a `key` argument to select data at a particular 

3466 level of a MultiIndex. 

3467 

3468 Parameters 

3469 ---------- 

3470 key : label or tuple of label 

3471 Label contained in the index, or partially in a MultiIndex. 

3472 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0 

3473 Axis to retrieve cross-section on. 

3474 level : object, defaults to first n levels (n=1 or len(key)) 

3475 In case of a key partially contained in a MultiIndex, indicate 

3476 which levels are used. Levels can be referred by label or position. 

3477 drop_level : bool, default True 

3478 If False, returns object with same levels as self. 

3479 

3480 Returns 

3481 ------- 

3482 Series or DataFrame 

3483 Cross-section from the original Series or DataFrame 

3484 corresponding to the selected index levels. 

3485 

3486 See Also 

3487 -------- 

3488 DataFrame.loc : Access a group of rows and columns 

3489 by label(s) or a boolean array. 

3490 DataFrame.iloc : Purely integer-location based indexing 

3491 for selection by position. 

3492 

3493 Notes 

3494 ----- 

3495 `xs` can not be used to set values. 

3496 

3497 MultiIndex Slicers is a generic way to get/set values on 

3498 any level or levels. 

3499 It is a superset of `xs` functionality, see 

3500 :ref:`MultiIndex Slicers <advanced.mi_slicers>`. 

3501 

3502 Examples 

3503 -------- 

3504 >>> d = {'num_legs': [4, 4, 2, 2], 

3505 ... 'num_wings': [0, 0, 2, 2], 

3506 ... 'class': ['mammal', 'mammal', 'mammal', 'bird'], 

3507 ... 'animal': ['cat', 'dog', 'bat', 'penguin'], 

3508 ... 'locomotion': ['walks', 'walks', 'flies', 'walks']} 

3509 >>> df = pd.DataFrame(data=d) 

3510 >>> df = df.set_index(['class', 'animal', 'locomotion']) 

3511 >>> df 

3512 num_legs num_wings 

3513 class animal locomotion 

3514 mammal cat walks 4 0 

3515 dog walks 4 0 

3516 bat flies 2 2 

3517 bird penguin walks 2 2 

3518 

3519 Get values at specified index 

3520 

3521 >>> df.xs('mammal') 

3522 num_legs num_wings 

3523 animal locomotion 

3524 cat walks 4 0 

3525 dog walks 4 0 

3526 bat flies 2 2 

3527 

3528 Get values at several indexes 

3529 

3530 >>> df.xs(('mammal', 'dog')) 

3531 num_legs num_wings 

3532 locomotion 

3533 walks 4 0 

3534 

3535 Get values at specified index and level 

3536 

3537 >>> df.xs('cat', level=1) 

3538 num_legs num_wings 

3539 class locomotion 

3540 mammal walks 4 0 

3541 

3542 Get values at several indexes and levels 

3543 

3544 >>> df.xs(('bird', 'walks'), 

3545 ... level=[0, 'locomotion']) 

3546 num_legs num_wings 

3547 animal 

3548 penguin 2 2 

3549 

3550 Get values at specified column and axis 

3551 

3552 >>> df.xs('num_wings', axis=1) 

3553 class animal locomotion 

3554 mammal cat walks 0 

3555 dog walks 0 

3556 bat flies 2 

3557 bird penguin walks 2 

3558 Name: num_wings, dtype: int64 

3559 """ 

3560 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

3561 labels = self._get_axis(axis) 

3562 if level is not None: 

3563 loc, new_ax = labels.get_loc_level(key, level=level, 

3564 drop_level=drop_level) 

3565 

3566 # create the tuple of the indexer 

3567 indexer = [slice(None)] * self.ndim 

3568 indexer[axis] = loc 

3569 indexer = tuple(indexer) 

3570 

3571 result = self.iloc[indexer] 

3572 setattr(result, result._get_axis_name(axis), new_ax) 

3573 return result 

3574 

3575 if axis == 1: 

3576 return self[key] 

3577 

3578 self._consolidate_inplace() 

3579 

3580 index = self.index 

3581 if isinstance(index, MultiIndex): 

3582 loc, new_index = self.index.get_loc_level(key, 

3583 drop_level=drop_level) 

3584 else: 

3585 loc = self.index.get_loc(key) 

3586 

3587 if isinstance(loc, np.ndarray): 

3588 if loc.dtype == np.bool_: 

3589 inds, = loc.nonzero() 

3590 return self._take(inds, axis=axis) 

3591 else: 

3592 return self._take(loc, axis=axis) 

3593 

3594 if not is_scalar(loc): 

3595 new_index = self.index[loc] 

3596 

3597 if is_scalar(loc): 

3598 new_values = self._data.fast_xs(loc) 

3599 

3600 # may need to box a datelike-scalar 

3601 # 

3602 # if we encounter an array-like and we only have 1 dim 

3603 # that means that their are list/ndarrays inside the Series! 

3604 # so just return them (GH 6394) 

3605 if not is_list_like(new_values) or self.ndim == 1: 

3606 return com.maybe_box_datetimelike(new_values) 

3607 

3608 result = self._constructor_sliced( 

3609 new_values, index=self.columns, 

3610 name=self.index[loc], dtype=new_values.dtype) 

3611 

3612 else: 

3613 result = self.iloc[loc] 

3614 result.index = new_index 

3615 

3616 # this could be a view 

3617 # but only in a single-dtyped view slicable case 

3618 result._set_is_copy(self, copy=not result._is_view) 

3619 return result 

3620 

3621 _xs = xs 

3622 

3623 def select(self, crit, axis=0): 

3624 """ 

3625 Return data corresponding to axis labels matching criteria. 

3626 

3627 .. deprecated:: 0.21.0 

3628 Use df.loc[df.index.map(crit)] to select via labels 

3629 

3630 Parameters 

3631 ---------- 

3632 crit : function 

3633 To be called on each index (label). Should return True or False 

3634 axis : int 

3635 

3636 Returns 

3637 ------- 

3638 selection : same type as caller 

3639 """ 

3640 warnings.warn("'select' is deprecated and will be removed in a " 

3641 "future release. You can use " 

3642 ".loc[labels.map(crit)] as a replacement", 

3643 FutureWarning, stacklevel=2) 

3644 

3645 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

3646 axis_name = self._get_axis_name(axis) 

3647 axis_values = self._get_axis(axis) 

3648 

3649 if len(axis_values) > 0: 

3650 new_axis = axis_values[ 

3651 np.asarray([bool(crit(label)) for label in axis_values])] 

3652 else: 

3653 new_axis = axis_values 

3654 

3655 return self.reindex(**{axis_name: new_axis}) 

3656 

3657 def reindex_like(self, other, method=None, copy=True, limit=None, 

3658 tolerance=None): 

3659 """ 

3660 Return an object with matching indices as other object. 

3661 

3662 Conform the object to the same index on all axes. Optional 

3663 filling logic, placing NaN in locations having no value 

3664 in the previous index. A new object is produced unless the 

3665 new index is equivalent to the current one and copy=False. 

3666 

3667 Parameters 

3668 ---------- 

3669 other : Object of the same data type 

3670 Its row and column indices are used to define the new indices 

3671 of this object. 

3672 method : {None, 'backfill'/'bfill', 'pad'/'ffill', 'nearest'} 

3673 Method to use for filling holes in reindexed DataFrame. 

3674 Please note: this is only applicable to DataFrames/Series with a 

3675 monotonically increasing/decreasing index. 

3676 

3677 * None (default): don't fill gaps 

3678 * pad / ffill: propagate last valid observation forward to next 

3679 valid 

3680 * backfill / bfill: use next valid observation to fill gap 

3681 * nearest: use nearest valid observations to fill gap 

3682 

3683 copy : bool, default True 

3684 Return a new object, even if the passed indexes are the same. 

3685 limit : int, default None 

3686 Maximum number of consecutive labels to fill for inexact matches. 

3687 tolerance : optional 

3688 Maximum distance between original and new labels for inexact 

3689 matches. The values of the index at the matching locations most 

3690 satisfy the equation ``abs(index[indexer] - target) <= tolerance``. 

3691 

3692 Tolerance may be a scalar value, which applies the same tolerance 

3693 to all values, or list-like, which applies variable tolerance per 

3694 element. List-like includes list, tuple, array, Series, and must be 

3695 the same size as the index and its dtype must exactly match the 

3696 index's type. 

3697 

3698 .. versionadded:: 0.21.0 (list-like tolerance) 

3699 

3700 Returns 

3701 ------- 

3702 Series or DataFrame 

3703 Same type as caller, but with changed indices on each axis. 

3704 

3705 See Also 

3706 -------- 

3707 DataFrame.set_index : Set row labels. 

3708 DataFrame.reset_index : Remove row labels or move them to new columns. 

3709 DataFrame.reindex : Change to new indices or expand indices. 

3710 

3711 Notes 

3712 ----- 

3713 Same as calling 

3714 ``.reindex(index=other.index, columns=other.columns,...)``. 

3715 

3716 Examples 

3717 -------- 

3718 >>> df1 = pd.DataFrame([[24.3, 75.7, 'high'], 

3719 ... [31, 87.8, 'high'], 

3720 ... [22, 71.6, 'medium'], 

3721 ... [35, 95, 'medium']], 

3722 ... columns=['temp_celsius', 'temp_fahrenheit', 'windspeed'], 

3723 ... index=pd.date_range(start='2014-02-12', 

3724 ... end='2014-02-15', freq='D')) 

3725 

3726 >>> df1 

3727 temp_celsius temp_fahrenheit windspeed 

3728 2014-02-12 24.3 75.7 high 

3729 2014-02-13 31.0 87.8 high 

3730 2014-02-14 22.0 71.6 medium 

3731 2014-02-15 35.0 95.0 medium 

3732 

3733 >>> df2 = pd.DataFrame([[28, 'low'], 

3734 ... [30, 'low'], 

3735 ... [35.1, 'medium']], 

3736 ... columns=['temp_celsius', 'windspeed'], 

3737 ... index=pd.DatetimeIndex(['2014-02-12', '2014-02-13', 

3738 ... '2014-02-15'])) 

3739 

3740 >>> df2 

3741 temp_celsius windspeed 

3742 2014-02-12 28.0 low 

3743 2014-02-13 30.0 low 

3744 2014-02-15 35.1 medium 

3745 

3746 >>> df2.reindex_like(df1) 

3747 temp_celsius temp_fahrenheit windspeed 

3748 2014-02-12 28.0 NaN low 

3749 2014-02-13 30.0 NaN low 

3750 2014-02-14 NaN NaN NaN 

3751 2014-02-15 35.1 NaN medium 

3752 """ 

3753 d = other._construct_axes_dict(axes=self._AXIS_ORDERS, method=method, 

3754 copy=copy, limit=limit, 

3755 tolerance=tolerance) 

3756 

3757 return self.reindex(**d) 

3758 

3759 def drop(self, labels=None, axis=0, index=None, columns=None, level=None, 

3760 inplace=False, errors='raise'): 

3761 

3762 inplace = validate_bool_kwarg(inplace, 'inplace') 

3763 

3764 if labels is not None: 

3765 if index is not None or columns is not None: 

3766 raise ValueError("Cannot specify both 'labels' and " 

3767 "'index'/'columns'") 

3768 axis_name = self._get_axis_name(axis) 

3769 axes = {axis_name: labels} 

3770 elif index is not None or columns is not None: 

3771 axes, _ = self._construct_axes_from_arguments((index, columns), {}) 

3772 else: 

3773 raise ValueError("Need to specify at least one of 'labels', " 

3774 "'index' or 'columns'") 

3775 

3776 obj = self 

3777 

3778 for axis, labels in axes.items(): 

3779 if labels is not None: 

3780 obj = obj._drop_axis(labels, axis, level=level, errors=errors) 

3781 

3782 if inplace: 

3783 self._update_inplace(obj) 

3784 else: 

3785 return obj 

3786 

3787 def _drop_axis(self, labels, axis, level=None, errors='raise'): 

3788 """ 

3789 Drop labels from specified axis. Used in the ``drop`` method 

3790 internally. 

3791 

3792 Parameters 

3793 ---------- 

3794 labels : single label or list-like 

3795 axis : int or axis name 

3796 level : int or level name, default None 

3797 For MultiIndex 

3798 errors : {'ignore', 'raise'}, default 'raise' 

3799 If 'ignore', suppress error and existing labels are dropped. 

3800 

3801 """ 

3802 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

3803 axis_name = self._get_axis_name(axis) 

3804 axis = self._get_axis(axis) 

3805 

3806 if axis.is_unique: 

3807 if level is not None: 

3808 if not isinstance(axis, MultiIndex): 

3809 raise AssertionError('axis must be a MultiIndex') 

3810 new_axis = axis.drop(labels, level=level, errors=errors) 

3811 else: 

3812 new_axis = axis.drop(labels, errors=errors) 

3813 result = self.reindex(**{axis_name: new_axis}) 

3814 

3815 # Case for non-unique axis 

3816 else: 

3817 labels = ensure_object(com.index_labels_to_array(labels)) 

3818 if level is not None: 

3819 if not isinstance(axis, MultiIndex): 

3820 raise AssertionError('axis must be a MultiIndex') 

3821 indexer = ~axis.get_level_values(level).isin(labels) 

3822 

3823 # GH 18561 MultiIndex.drop should raise if label is absent 

3824 if errors == 'raise' and indexer.all(): 

3825 raise KeyError('{} not found in axis'.format(labels)) 

3826 else: 

3827 indexer = ~axis.isin(labels) 

3828 # Check if label doesn't exist along axis 

3829 labels_missing = (axis.get_indexer_for(labels) == -1).any() 

3830 if errors == 'raise' and labels_missing: 

3831 raise KeyError('{} not found in axis'.format(labels)) 

3832 

3833 slicer = [slice(None)] * self.ndim 

3834 slicer[self._get_axis_number(axis_name)] = indexer 

3835 

3836 result = self.loc[tuple(slicer)] 

3837 

3838 return result 

3839 

3840 def _update_inplace(self, result, verify_is_copy=True): 

3841 """ 

3842 Replace self internals with result. 

3843 

3844 Parameters 

3845 ---------- 

3846 verify_is_copy : boolean, default True 

3847 provide is_copy checks 

3848 

3849 """ 

3850 # NOTE: This does *not* call __finalize__ and that's an explicit 

3851 # decision that we may revisit in the future. 

3852 

3853 self._reset_cache() 

3854 self._clear_item_cache() 

3855 self._data = getattr(result, '_data', result) 

3856 self._maybe_update_cacher(verify_is_copy=verify_is_copy) 

3857 

3858 def add_prefix(self, prefix): 

3859 """ 

3860 Prefix labels with string `prefix`. 

3861 

3862 For Series, the row labels are prefixed. 

3863 For DataFrame, the column labels are prefixed. 

3864 

3865 Parameters 

3866 ---------- 

3867 prefix : str 

3868 The string to add before each label. 

3869 

3870 Returns 

3871 ------- 

3872 Series or DataFrame 

3873 New Series or DataFrame with updated labels. 

3874 

3875 See Also 

3876 -------- 

3877 Series.add_suffix: Suffix row labels with string `suffix`. 

3878 DataFrame.add_suffix: Suffix column labels with string `suffix`. 

3879 

3880 Examples 

3881 -------- 

3882 >>> s = pd.Series([1, 2, 3, 4]) 

3883 >>> s 

3884 0 1 

3885 1 2 

3886 2 3 

3887 3 4 

3888 dtype: int64 

3889 

3890 >>> s.add_prefix('item_') 

3891 item_0 1 

3892 item_1 2 

3893 item_2 3 

3894 item_3 4 

3895 dtype: int64 

3896 

3897 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'A': [1, 2, 3, 4], 'B': [3, 4, 5, 6]}) 

3898 >>> df 

3899 A B 

3900 0 1 3 

3901 1 2 4 

3902 2 3 5 

3903 3 4 6 

3904 

3905 >>> df.add_prefix('col_') 

3906 col_A col_B 

3907 0 1 3 

3908 1 2 4 

3909 2 3 5 

3910 3 4 6 

3911 """ 

3912 f = functools.partial('{prefix}{}'.format, prefix=prefix) 

3913 

3914 mapper = {self._info_axis_name: f} 

3915 return self.rename(**mapper)

3976 def sort_values(self, by=None, axis=0, ascending=True, inplace=False, 

3977 kind='quicksort', na_position='last'): 

3978 """ 

3979 Sort by the values along either axis 

3980 

3981 Parameters 

3982 ----------%(optional_by)s 

3983 axis : %(axes_single_arg)s, default 0 

3984 Axis to be sorted 

3985 ascending : bool or list of bool, default True 

3986 Sort ascending vs. descending. Specify list for multiple sort 

3987 orders. If this is a list of bools, must match the length of 

3988 the by. 

3989 inplace : bool, default False 

3990 if True, perform operation in-place 

3991 kind : {'quicksort', 'mergesort', 'heapsort'}, default 'quicksort' 

3992 Choice of sorting algorithm. See also ndarray.np.sort for more 

3993 information. `mergesort` is the only stable algorithm. For 

3994 DataFrames, this option is only applied when sorting on a single 

3995 column or label. 

3996 na_position : {'first', 'last'}, default 'last' 

3997 `first` puts NaNs at the beginning, `last` puts NaNs at the end 

3998 

3999 Returns 

4000 ------- 

4001 sorted_obj : %(klass)s 

4002 

4003 Examples 

4004 -------- 

4005 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({ 

4006 ... 'col1' : ['A', 'A', 'B', np.nan, 'D', 'C'], 

4007 ... 'col2' : [2, 1, 9, 8, 7, 4], 

4008 ... 'col3': [0, 1, 9, 4, 2, 3], 

4009 ... }) 

4010 >>> df 

4011 col1 col2 col3 

4012 0 A 2 0 

4013 1 A 1 1 

4014 2 B 9 9 

4015 3 NaN 8 4 

4016 4 D 7 2 

4017 5 C 4 3 

4018 

4019 Sort by col1 

4020 

4021 >>> df.sort_values(by=['col1']) 

4022 col1 col2 col3 

4023 0 A 2 0 

4024 1 A 1 1 

4025 2 B 9 9 

4026 5 C 4 3 

4027 4 D 7 2 

4028 3 NaN 8 4 

4029 

4030 Sort by multiple columns 

4031 

4032 >>> df.sort_values(by=['col1', 'col2']) 

4033 col1 col2 col3 

4034 1 A 1 1 

4035 0 A 2 0 

4036 2 B 9 9 

4037 5 C 4 3 

4038 4 D 7 2 

4039 3 NaN 8 4 

4040 

4041 Sort Descending 

4042 

4043 >>> df.sort_values(by='col1', ascending=False) 

4044 col1 col2 col3 

4045 4 D 7 2 

4046 5 C 4 3 

4047 2 B 9 9 

4048 0 A 2 0 

4049 1 A 1 1 

4050 3 NaN 8 4 

4051 

4052 Putting NAs first 

4053 

4054 >>> df.sort_values(by='col1', ascending=False, na_position='first') 

4055 col1 col2 col3 

4056 3 NaN 8 4 

4057 4 D 7 2 

4058 5 C 4 3 

4059 2 B 9 9 

4060 0 A 2 0 

4061 1 A 1 1 

4062 """ 

4063 raise NotImplementedError("sort_values has not been implemented " 

4064 "on Panel or Panel4D objects.") 

4065 

4066 def sort_index(self, axis=0, level=None, ascending=True, inplace=False, 

4067 kind='quicksort', na_position='last', sort_remaining=True): 

4068 """ 

4069 Sort object by labels (along an axis) 

4070 

4071 Parameters 

4072 ---------- 

4073 axis : %(axes)s to direct sorting 

4074 level : int or level name or list of ints or list of level names 

4075 if not None, sort on values in specified index level(s) 

4076 ascending : boolean, default True 

4077 Sort ascending vs. descending 

4078 inplace : bool, default False 

4079 if True, perform operation in-place 

4080 kind : {'quicksort', 'mergesort', 'heapsort'}, default 'quicksort' 

4081 Choice of sorting algorithm. See also ndarray.np.sort for more 

4082 information. `mergesort` is the only stable algorithm. For 

4083 DataFrames, this option is only applied when sorting on a single 

4084 column or label. 

4085 na_position : {'first', 'last'}, default 'last' 

4086 `first` puts NaNs at the beginning, `last` puts NaNs at the end. 

4087 Not implemented for MultiIndex. 

4088 sort_remaining : bool, default True 

4089 if true and sorting by level and index is multilevel, sort by other 

4090 levels too (in order) after sorting by specified level 

4091 

4092 Returns 

4093 ------- 

4094 sorted_obj : %(klass)s 

4095 """ 

4096 inplace = validate_bool_kwarg(inplace, 'inplace') 

4097 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

4098 axis_name = self._get_axis_name(axis) 

4099 labels = self._get_axis(axis) 

4100 

4101 if level is not None: 

4102 raise NotImplementedError("level is not implemented") 

4103 if inplace: 

4104 raise NotImplementedError("inplace is not implemented") 

4105 

4106 sort_index = labels.argsort() 

4107 if not ascending: 

4108 sort_index = sort_index[::-1] 

4109 

4110 new_axis = labels.take(sort_index) 

4111 return self.reindex(**{axis_name: new_axis}) 

4112 

4113 def reindex(self, *args, **kwargs): 

4114 """ 

4115 Conform %(klass)s to new index with optional filling logic, placing 

4116 NA/NaN in locations having no value in the previous index. A new object 

4117 is produced unless the new index is equivalent to the current one and 

4118 ``copy=False``. 

4119 

4120 Parameters 

4121 ---------- 

4122 %(optional_labels)s 

4123 %(axes)s : array-like, optional 

4124 New labels / index to conform to, should be specified using 

4125 keywords. Preferably an Index object to avoid duplicating data 

4126 %(optional_axis)s 

4127 method : {None, 'backfill'/'bfill', 'pad'/'ffill', 'nearest'} 

4128 Method to use for filling holes in reindexed DataFrame. 

4129 Please note: this is only applicable to DataFrames/Series with a 

4130 monotonically increasing/decreasing index. 

4131 

4132 * None (default): don't fill gaps 

4133 * pad / ffill: propagate last valid observation forward to next 

4134 valid 

4135 * backfill / bfill: use next valid observation to fill gap 

4136 * nearest: use nearest valid observations to fill gap 

4137 

4138 copy : bool, default True 

4139 Return a new object, even if the passed indexes are the same. 

4140 level : int or name 

4141 Broadcast across a level, matching Index values on the 

4142 passed MultiIndex level. 

4143 fill_value : scalar, default np.NaN 

4144 Value to use for missing values. Defaults to NaN, but can be any 

4145 "compatible" value. 

4146 limit : int, default None 

4147 Maximum number of consecutive elements to forward or backward fill. 

4148 tolerance : optional 

4149 Maximum distance between original and new labels for inexact 

4150 matches. The values of the index at the matching locations most 

4151 satisfy the equation ``abs(index[indexer] - target) <= tolerance``. 

4152 

4153 Tolerance may be a scalar value, which applies the same tolerance 

4154 to all values, or list-like, which applies variable tolerance per 

4155 element. List-like includes list, tuple, array, Series, and must be 

4156 the same size as the index and its dtype must exactly match the 

4157 index's type. 

4158 

4159 .. versionadded:: 0.21.0 (list-like tolerance) 

4160 

4161 Returns 

4162 ------- 

4163 %(klass)s with changed index. 

4164 

4165 See Also 

4166 -------- 

4167 DataFrame.set_index : Set row labels. 

4168 DataFrame.reset_index : Remove row labels or move them to new columns. 

4169 DataFrame.reindex_like : Change to same indices as other DataFrame. 

4170 

4171 Examples 

4172 -------- 

4173 

4174 ``DataFrame.reindex`` supports two calling conventions 

4175 

4176 * ``(index=index_labels, columns=column_labels, ...)`` 

4177 * ``(labels, axis={'index', 'columns'}, ...)`` 

4178 

4179 We *highly* recommend using keyword arguments to clarify your 

4180 intent. 

4181 

4182 Create a dataframe with some fictional data. 

4183 

4184 >>> index = ['Firefox', 'Chrome', 'Safari', 'IE10', 'Konqueror'] 

4185 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({ 

4186 ... 'http_status': [200,200,404,404,301], 

4187 ... 'response_time': [0.04, 0.02, 0.07, 0.08, 1.0]}, 

4188 ... index=index) 

4189 >>> df 

4190 http_status response_time 

4191 Firefox 200 0.04 

4192 Chrome 200 0.02 

4193 Safari 404 0.07 

4194 IE10 404 0.08 

4195 Konqueror 301 1.00 

4196 

4197 Create a new index and reindex the dataframe. By default 

4198 values in the new index that do not have corresponding 

4199 records in the dataframe are assigned ``NaN``. 

4200 

4201 >>> new_index= ['Safari', 'Iceweasel', 'Comodo Dragon', 'IE10', 

4202 ... 'Chrome'] 

4203 >>> df.reindex(new_index) 

4204 http_status response_time 

4205 Safari 404.0 0.07 

4206 Iceweasel NaN NaN 

4207 Comodo Dragon NaN NaN 

4208 IE10 404.0 0.08 

4209 Chrome 200.0 0.02 

4210 

4211 We can fill in the missing values by passing a value to 

4212 the keyword ``fill_value``. Because the index is not monotonically 

4213 increasing or decreasing, we cannot use arguments to the keyword 

4214 ``method`` to fill the ``NaN`` values. 

4215 

4216 >>> df.reindex(new_index, fill_value=0) 

4217 http_status response_time 

4218 Safari 404 0.07 

4219 Iceweasel 0 0.00 

4220 Comodo Dragon 0 0.00 

4221 IE10 404 0.08 

4222 Chrome 200 0.02 

4223 

4224 >>> df.reindex(new_index, fill_value='missing') 

4225 http_status response_time 

4226 Safari 404 0.07 

4227 Iceweasel missing missing 

4228 Comodo Dragon missing missing 

4229 IE10 404 0.08 

4230 Chrome 200 0.02 

4231 

4232 We can also reindex the columns. 

4233 

4234 >>> df.reindex(columns=['http_status', 'user_agent']) 

4235 http_status user_agent 

4236 Firefox 200 NaN 

4237 Chrome 200 NaN 

4238 Safari 404 NaN 

4239 IE10 404 NaN 

4240 Konqueror 301 NaN 

4241 

4242 Or we can use "axis-style" keyword arguments 

4243 

4244 >>> df.reindex(['http_status', 'user_agent'], axis="columns") 

4245 http_status user_agent 

4246 Firefox 200 NaN 

4247 Chrome 200 NaN 

4248 Safari 404 NaN 

4249 IE10 404 NaN 

4250 Konqueror 301 NaN 

4251 

4252 To further illustrate the filling functionality in 

4253 ``reindex``, we will create a dataframe with a 

4254 monotonically increasing index (for example, a sequence 

4255 of dates). 

4256 

4257 >>> date_index = pd.date_range('1/1/2010', periods=6, freq='D') 

4258 >>> df2 = pd.DataFrame({"prices": [100, 101, np.nan, 100, 89, 88]}, 

4259 ... index=date_index) 

4260 >>> df2 

4261 prices 

4262 2010-01-01 100.0 

4263 2010-01-02 101.0 

4264 2010-01-03 NaN 

4265 2010-01-04 100.0 

4266 2010-01-05 89.0 

4267 2010-01-06 88.0 

4268 

4269 Suppose we decide to expand the dataframe to cover a wider 

4270 date range. 

4271 

4272 >>> date_index2 = pd.date_range('12/29/2009', periods=10, freq='D') 

4273 >>> df2.reindex(date_index2) 

4274 prices 

4275 2009-12-29 NaN 

4276 2009-12-30 NaN 

4277 2009-12-31 NaN 

4278 2010-01-01 100.0 

4279 2010-01-02 101.0 

4280 2010-01-03 NaN 

4281 2010-01-04 100.0 

4282 2010-01-05 89.0 

4283 2010-01-06 88.0 

4284 2010-01-07 NaN 

4285 

4286 The index entries that did not have a value in the original data frame 

4287 (for example, '2009-12-29') are by default filled with ``NaN``. 

4288 If desired, we can fill in the missing values using one of several 

4289 options. 

4290 

4291 For example, to back-propagate the last valid value to fill the ``NaN`` 

4292 values, pass ``bfill`` as an argument to the ``method`` keyword. 

4293 

4294 >>> df2.reindex(date_index2, method='bfill') 

4295 prices 

4296 2009-12-29 100.0 

4297 2009-12-30 100.0 

4298 2009-12-31 100.0 

4299 2010-01-01 100.0 

4300 2010-01-02 101.0 

4301 2010-01-03 NaN 

4302 2010-01-04 100.0 

4303 2010-01-05 89.0 

4304 2010-01-06 88.0 

4305 2010-01-07 NaN 

4306 

4307 Please note that the ``NaN`` value present in the original dataframe 

4308 (at index value 2010-01-03) will not be filled by any of the 

4309 value propagation schemes. This is because filling while reindexing 

4310 does not look at dataframe values, but only compares the original and 

4311 desired indexes. If you do want to fill in the ``NaN`` values present 

4312 in the original dataframe, use the ``fillna()`` method. 

4313 

4314 See the :ref:`user guide <basics.reindexing>` for more. 

4315 """ 

4316 # TODO: Decide if we care about having different examples for different 

4317 # kinds 

4318 

4319 # construct the args 

4320 axes, kwargs = self._construct_axes_from_arguments(args, kwargs) 

4321 method = missing.clean_reindex_fill_method(kwargs.pop('method', None)) 

4322 level = kwargs.pop('level', None) 

4323 copy = kwargs.pop('copy', True) 

4324 limit = kwargs.pop('limit', None) 

4325 tolerance = kwargs.pop('tolerance', None) 

4326 fill_value = kwargs.pop('fill_value', None) 

4327 

4328 # Series.reindex doesn't use / need the axis kwarg 

4329 # We pop and ignore it here, to make writing Series/Frame generic code 

4330 # easier 

4331 kwargs.pop("axis", None) 

4332 

4333 if kwargs: 

4334 raise TypeError('reindex() got an unexpected keyword ' 

4335 'argument "{0}"'.format(list(kwargs.keys())[0])) 

4336 

4337 self._consolidate_inplace() 

4338 

4339 # if all axes that are requested to reindex are equal, then only copy 

4340 # if indicated must have index names equal here as well as values 

4341 if all(self._get_axis(axis).identical(ax) 

4342 for axis, ax in axes.items() if ax is not None): 

4343 if copy: 

4344 return self.copy() 

4345 return self 

4346 

4347 # check if we are a multi reindex 

4348 if self._needs_reindex_multi(axes, method, level): 

4349 try: 

4350 return self._reindex_multi(axes, copy, fill_value) 

4351 except Exception: 

4352 pass 

4353 

4354 # perform the reindex on the axes 

4355 return self._reindex_axes(axes, level, limit, tolerance, method, 

4356 fill_value, copy).__finalize__(self) 

4357 

4358 def _reindex_axes(self, axes, level, limit, tolerance, method, fill_value, 

4359 copy): 

4360 """Perform the reindex for all the axes.""" 

4361 obj = self 

4362 for a in self._AXIS_ORDERS: 

4363 labels = axes[a] 

4364 if labels is None: 

4365 continue 

4366 

4367 ax = self._get_axis(a) 

4368 new_index, indexer = ax.reindex(labels, level=level, limit=limit, 

4369 tolerance=tolerance, method=method) 

4370 

4371 axis = self._get_axis_number(a) 

4372 obj = obj._reindex_with_indexers({axis: [new_index, indexer]}, 

4373 fill_value=fill_value, 

4374 copy=copy, allow_dups=False) 

4375 

4376 return obj 

4377 

4378 def _needs_reindex_multi(self, axes, method, level): 

4379 """Check if we do need a multi reindex.""" 

4380 return ((com.count_not_none(*axes.values()) == self._AXIS_LEN) and 

4381 method is None and level is None and not self._is_mixed_type) 

4382 

4383 def _reindex_multi(self, axes, copy, fill_value): 

4384 return NotImplemented 

4385 

4386 _shared_docs['reindex_axis'] = (""" 

4387 Conform input object to new index. 

4388 

4389 .. deprecated:: 0.21.0 

4390 Use `reindex` instead. 

4391 

4392 By default, places NaN in locations having no value in the 

4393 previous index. A new object is produced unless the new index 

4394 is equivalent to the current one and copy=False. 

4395 

4396 Parameters 

4397 ---------- 

4398 labels : array-like 

4399 New labels / index to conform to. Preferably an Index object to 

4400 avoid duplicating data. 

4401 axis : %(axes_single_arg)s 

4402 Indicate whether to use rows or columns. 

4403 method : {None, 'backfill'/'bfill', 'pad'/'ffill', 'nearest'}, optional 

4404 Method to use for filling holes in reindexed DataFrame: 

4405 

4406 * default: don't fill gaps. 

4407 * pad / ffill: propagate last valid observation forward to next 

4408 valid. 

4409 * backfill / bfill: use next valid observation to fill gap. 

4410 * nearest: use nearest valid observations to fill gap. 

4411 

4412 level : int or str 

4413 Broadcast across a level, matching Index values on the 

4414 passed MultiIndex level. 

4415 copy : bool, default True 

4416 Return a new object, even if the passed indexes are the same. 

4417 limit : int, optional 

4418 Maximum number of consecutive elements to forward or backward fill. 

4419 fill_value : float, default NaN 

4420 Value used to fill in locations having no value in the previous 

4421 index. 

4422 

4423 .. versionadded:: 0.21.0 (list-like tolerance) 

4424 

4425 Returns 

4426 ------- 

4427 %(klass)s 

4428 Returns a new DataFrame object with new indices, unless the new 

4429 index is equivalent to the current one and copy=False. 

4430 

4431 See Also 

4432 -------- 

4433 DataFrame.set_index : Set row labels. 

4434 DataFrame.reset_index : Remove row labels or move them to new columns. 

4435 DataFrame.reindex : Change to new indices or expand indices. 

4436 DataFrame.reindex_like : Change to same indices as other DataFrame. 

4437 

4438 Examples 

4439 -------- 

4440 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'num_legs': [4, 2], 'num_wings': [0, 2]}, 

4441 ... index=['dog', 'hawk']) 

4442 >>> df 

4443 num_legs num_wings 

4444 dog 4 0 

4445 hawk 2 2 

4446 >>> df.reindex(['num_wings', 'num_legs', 'num_heads'], 

4447 ... axis='columns') 

4448 num_wings num_legs num_heads 

4449 dog 0 4 NaN 

4450 hawk 2 2 NaN 

4451 """) 

4452 

4453 @Appender(_shared_docs['reindex_axis'] % _shared_doc_kwargs) 

4454 def reindex_axis(self, labels, axis=0, method=None, level=None, copy=True, 

4455 limit=None, fill_value=None): 

4456 msg = ("'.reindex_axis' is deprecated and will be removed in a future " 

4457 "version. Use '.reindex' instead.") 

4458 self._consolidate_inplace() 

4459 

4460 axis_name = self._get_axis_name(axis) 

4461 axis_values = self._get_axis(axis_name) 

4462 method = missing.clean_reindex_fill_method(method) 

4463 warnings.warn(msg, FutureWarning, stacklevel=3) 

4464 new_index, indexer = axis_values.reindex(labels, method, level, 

4465 limit=limit) 

4466 return self._reindex_with_indexers({axis: [new_index, indexer]}, 

4467 fill_value=fill_value, copy=copy) 

4468 

4469 def _reindex_with_indexers(self, reindexers, fill_value=None, copy=False, 

4470 allow_dups=False): 

4471 """allow_dups indicates an internal call here """ 

4472 

4473 # reindex doing multiple operations on different axes if indicated 

4474 new_data = self._data 

4475 for axis in sorted(reindexers.keys()): 

4476 index, indexer = reindexers[axis] 

4477 baxis = self._get_block_manager_axis(axis) 

4478 

4479 if index is None: 

4480 continue 

4481 

4482 index = ensure_index(index) 

4483 if indexer is not None: 

4484 indexer = ensure_int64(indexer) 

4485 

4486 # TODO: speed up on homogeneous DataFrame objects 

4487 new_data = new_data.reindex_indexer(index, indexer, axis=baxis, 

4488 fill_value=fill_value, 

4489 allow_dups=allow_dups, 

4490 copy=copy) 

4491 

4492 if copy and new_data is self._data: 

4493 new_data = new_data.copy() 

4494 

4495 return self._constructor(new_data).__finalize__(self)

4497 def filter(self, items=None, like=None, regex=None, axis=None): 

4498 """ 

4499 Subset rows or columns of dataframe according to labels in 

4500 the specified index. 

4501 

4502 Note that this routine does not filter a dataframe on its 

4503 contents. The filter is applied to the labels of the index. 

4504 

4505 Parameters 

4506 ---------- 

4507 items : list-like 

4508 List of axis to restrict to (must not all be present). 

4509 like : string 

4510 Keep axis where "arg in col == True". 

4511 regex : string (regular expression) 

4512 Keep axis with re.search(regex, col) == True. 

4513 axis : int or string axis name 

4514 The axis to filter on. By default this is the info axis, 

4515 'index' for Series, 'columns' for DataFrame. 

4516 

4517 Returns 

4518 ------- 

4519 same type as input object 

4520 

4521 See Also 

4522 -------- 

4523 DataFrame.loc 

4524 

4525 Notes 

4526 ----- 

4527 The ``items``, ``like``, and ``regex`` parameters are 

4528 enforced to be mutually exclusive. 

4529 

4530 ``axis`` defaults to the info axis that is used when indexing 

4531 with ``[]``. 

4532 

4533 Examples 

4534 -------- 

4535 >>> df = pd.DataFrame(np.array(([1,2,3], [4,5,6])), 

4536 ... index=['mouse', 'rabbit'], 

4537 ... columns=['one', 'two', 'three']) 

4538 

4539 >>> # select columns by name 

4540 >>> df.filter(items=['one', 'three']) 

4541 one three 

4542 mouse 1 3 

4543 rabbit 4 6 

4544 

4545 >>> # select columns by regular expression 

4546 >>> df.filter(regex='e$', axis=1) 

4547 one three 

4548 mouse 1 3 

4549 rabbit 4 6 

4550 

4551 >>> # select rows containing 'bbi' 

4552 >>> df.filter(like='bbi', axis=0) 

4553 one two three 

4554 rabbit 4 5 6 

4555 """ 

4556 import re 

4557 

4558 nkw = com.count_not_none(items, like, regex) 

4559 if nkw > 1: 

4560 raise TypeError('Keyword arguments `items`, `like`, or `regex` ' 

4561 'are mutually exclusive') 

4562 

4563 if axis is None: 

4564 axis = self._info_axis_name 

4565 labels = self._get_axis(axis) 

4566 

4567 if items is not None: 

4568 name = self._get_axis_name(axis) 

4569 return self.reindex( 

4570 **{name: [r for r in items if r in labels]}) 

4571 elif like: 

4572 def f(x): 

4573 return like in to_str(x) 

4574 values = labels.map(f) 

4575 return self.loc(axis=axis)[values] 

4576 elif regex: 

4577 def f(x): 

4578 return matcher.search(to_str(x)) is not None 

4579 matcher = re.compile(regex) 

4580 values = labels.map(f) 

4581 return self.loc(axis=axis)[values] 

4582 else: 

4583 raise TypeError('Must pass either `items`, `like`, or `regex`') 

4584 

4585 def head(self, n=5): 

4586 """ 

4587 Return the first `n` rows. 

4588 

4589 This function returns the first `n` rows for the object based 

4590 on position. It is useful for quickly testing if your object 

4591 has the right type of data in it. 

4592 

4593 Parameters 

4594 ---------- 

4595 n : int, default 5 

4596 Number of rows to select. 

4597 

4598 Returns 

4599 ------- 

4600 obj_head : same type as caller 

4601 The first `n` rows of the caller object. 

4602 

4603 See Also 

4604 -------- 

4605 DataFrame.tail: Returns the last `n` rows. 

4606 

4607 Examples 

4608 -------- 

4609 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'animal':['alligator', 'bee', 'falcon', 'lion', 

4610 ... 'monkey', 'parrot', 'shark', 'whale', 'zebra']}) 

4611 >>> df 

4612 animal 

4613 0 alligator 

4614 1 bee 

4615 2 falcon 

4616 3 lion 

4617 4 monkey 

4618 5 parrot 

4619 6 shark 

4620 7 whale 

4621 8 zebra 

4622 

4623 Viewing the first 5 lines 

4624 

4625 >>> df.head() 

4626 animal 

4627 0 alligator 

4628 1 bee 

4629 2 falcon 

4630 3 lion 

4631 4 monkey 

4632 

4633 Viewing the first `n` lines (three in this case) 

4634 

4635 >>> df.head(3) 

4636 animal 

4637 0 alligator 

4638 1 bee 

4639 2 falcon 

4640 """ 

4641 

4642 return self.iloc[:n] 

4643 

4644 def tail(self, n=5): 

4645 """ 

4646 Return the last `n` rows. 

4647 

4648 This function returns last `n` rows from the object based on 

4649 position. It is useful for quickly verifying data, for example, 

4650 after sorting or appending rows. 

4651 

4652 Parameters 

4653 ---------- 

4654 n : int, default 5 

4655 Number of rows to select. 

4656 

4657 Returns 

4658 ------- 

4659 type of caller 

4660 The last `n` rows of the caller object. 

4661 

4662 See Also 

4663 -------- 

4664 DataFrame.head : The first `n` rows of the caller object. 

4665 

4666 Examples 

4667 -------- 

4668 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'animal':['alligator', 'bee', 'falcon', 'lion', 

4669 ... 'monkey', 'parrot', 'shark', 'whale', 'zebra']}) 

4670 >>> df 

4671 animal 

4672 0 alligator 

4673 1 bee 

4674 2 falcon 

4675 3 lion 

4676 4 monkey 

4677 5 parrot 

4678 6 shark 

4679 7 whale 

4680 8 zebra 

4681 

4682 Viewing the last 5 lines 

4683 

4684 >>> df.tail() 

4685 animal 

4686 4 monkey 

4687 5 parrot 

4688 6 shark 

4689 7 whale 

4690 8 zebra 

4691 

4692 Viewing the last `n` lines (three in this case) 

4693 

4694 >>> df.tail(3) 

4695 animal 

4696 6 shark 

4697 7 whale 

4698 8 zebra 

4699 """ 

4700 

4701 if n == 0: 

4702 return self.iloc[0:0] 

4703 return self.iloc[-n:] 

4704 

4705 def sample(self, n=None, frac=None, replace=False, weights=None, 

4706 random_state=None, axis=None): 

4707 """ 

4708 Return a random sample of items from an axis of object. 

4709 

4710 You can use `random_state` for reproducibility. 

4711 

4712 Parameters 

4713 ---------- 

4714 n : int, optional 

4715 Number of items from axis to return. Cannot be used with `frac`. 

4716 Default = 1 if `frac` = None. 

4717 frac : float, optional 

4718 Fraction of axis items to return. Cannot be used with `n`. 

4719 replace : bool, default False 

4720 Sample with or without replacement. 

4721 weights : str or ndarray-like, optional 

4722 Default 'None' results in equal probability weighting. 

4723 If passed a Series, will align with target object on index. Index 

4724 values in weights not found in sampled object will be ignored and 

4725 index values in sampled object not in weights will be assigned 

4726 weights of zero. 

4727 If called on a DataFrame, will accept the name of a column 

4728 when axis = 0. 

4729 Unless weights are a Series, weights must be same length as axis 

4730 being sampled. 

4731 If weights do not sum to 1, they will be normalized to sum to 1. 

4732 Missing values in the weights column will be treated as zero. 

4733 Infinite values not allowed. 

4734 random_state : int or numpy.random.RandomState, optional 

4735 Seed for the random number generator (if int), or numpy RandomState 

4736 object. 

4737 axis : int or string, optional 

4738 Axis to sample. Accepts axis number or name. Default is stat axis 

4739 for given data type (0 for Series and DataFrames, 1 for Panels). 

4740 

4741 Returns 

4742 ------- 

4743 Series or DataFrame 

4744 A new object of same type as caller containing `n` items randomly 

4745 sampled from the caller object. 

4746 

4747 See Also 

4748 -------- 

4749 numpy.random.choice: Generates a random sample from a given 1-D numpy 

4750 array. 

4751 

4752 Examples 

4753 -------- 

4754 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'num_legs': [2, 4, 8, 0], 

4755 ... 'num_wings': [2, 0, 0, 0], 

4756 ... 'num_specimen_seen': [10, 2, 1, 8]}, 

4757 ... index=['falcon', 'dog', 'spider', 'fish']) 

4758 >>> df 

4759 num_legs num_wings num_specimen_seen 

4760 falcon 2 2 10 

4761 dog 4 0 2 

4762 spider 8 0 1 

4763 fish 0 0 8 

4764 

4765 Extract 3 random elements from the ``Series`` ``df['num_legs']``: 

4766 Note that we use `random_state` to ensure the reproducibility of 

4767 the examples. 

4768 

4769 >>> df['num_legs'].sample(n=3, random_state=1) 

4770 fish 0 

4771 spider 8 

4772 falcon 2 

4773 Name: num_legs, dtype: int64 

4774 

4775 A random 50% sample of the ``DataFrame`` with replacement: 

4776 

4777 >>> df.sample(frac=0.5, replace=True, random_state=1) 

4778 num_legs num_wings num_specimen_seen 

4779 dog 4 0 2 

4780 fish 0 0 8 

4781 

4782 Using a DataFrame column as weights. Rows with larger value in the 

4783 `num_specimen_seen` column are more likely to be sampled. 

4784 

4785 >>> df.sample(n=2, weights='num_specimen_seen', random_state=1) 

4786 num_legs num_wings num_specimen_seen 

4787 falcon 2 2 10 

4788 fish 0 0 8 

4789 """ 

4790 

4791 if axis is None: 

4792 axis = self._stat_axis_number 

4793 

4794 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

4795 axis_length = self.shape[axis] 

4796 

4797 # Process random_state argument 

4798 rs = com.random_state(random_state) 

4799 

4800 # Check weights for compliance 

4801 if weights is not None: 

4802 

4803 # If a series, align with frame 

4804 if isinstance(weights, pd.Series): 

4805 weights = weights.reindex(self.axes[axis]) 

4806 

4807 # Strings acceptable if a dataframe and axis = 0 

4808 if isinstance(weights, string_types): 

4809 if isinstance(self, pd.DataFrame): 

4810 if axis == 0: 

4811 try: 

4812 weights = self[weights] 

4813 except KeyError: 

4814 raise KeyError("String passed to weights not a " 

4815 "valid column") 

4816 else: 

4817 raise ValueError("Strings can only be passed to " 

4818 "weights when sampling from rows on " 

4819 "a DataFrame") 

4820 else: 

4821 raise ValueError("Strings cannot be passed as weights " 

4822 "when sampling from a Series or Panel.") 

4823 

4824 weights = pd.Series(weights, dtype='float64') 

4825 

4826 if len(weights) != axis_length: 

4827 raise ValueError("Weights and axis to be sampled must be of " 

4828 "same length") 

4829 

4830 if (weights == np.inf).any() or (weights == -np.inf).any(): 

4831 raise ValueError("weight vector may not include `inf` values") 

4832 

4833 if (weights < 0).any(): 

4834 raise ValueError("weight vector many not include negative " 

4835 "values") 

4836 

4837 # If has nan, set to zero. 

4838 weights = weights.fillna(0) 

4839 

4840 # Renormalize if don't sum to 1 

4841 if weights.sum() != 1: 

4842 if weights.sum() != 0: 

4843 weights = weights / weights.sum() 

4844 else: 

4845 raise ValueError("Invalid weights: weights sum to zero") 

4846 

4847 weights = weights.values 

4848 

4849 # If no frac or n, default to n=1. 

4850 if n is None and frac is None: 

4851 n = 1 

4852 elif n is not None and frac is None and n % 1 != 0: 

4853 raise ValueError("Only integers accepted as `n` values") 

4854 elif n is None and frac is not None: 

4855 n = int(round(frac * axis_length)) 

4856 elif n is not None and frac is not None: 

4857 raise ValueError('Please enter a value for `frac` OR `n`, not ' 

4858 'both') 

4859 

4860 # Check for negative sizes 

4861 if n < 0: 

4862 raise ValueError("A negative number of rows requested. Please " 

4863 "provide positive value.") 

4864 

4865 locs = rs.choice(axis_length, size=n, replace=replace, p=weights) 

4866 return self.take(locs, axis=axis, is_copy=False)

4912

4914 ... .pipe(g, arg1=a)

4916 ... ) 

4917 """)

5033 # ---------------------------------------------------------------------- 

5034 # Attribute access 

5035 

5036 def __finalize__(self, other, method=None, **kwargs): 

5037 """ 

5038 Propagate metadata from other to self. 

5039 

5040 Parameters 

5041 ---------- 

5042 other : the object from which to get the attributes that we are going 

5043 to propagate 

5044 method : optional, a passed method name ; possibly to take different 

5045 types of propagation actions based on this 

5046 

5047 """ 

5048 if isinstance(other, NDFrame): 

5049 for name in self._metadata: 

5050 object.__setattr__(self, name, getattr(other, name, None)) 

5051 return self 

5052 

5053 def __getattr__(self, name): 

5054 """After regular attribute access, try looking up the name 

5055 This allows simpler access to columns for interactive use. 

5056 """ 

5057 

5058 # Note: obj.x will always call obj.__getattribute__('x') prior to 

5059 # calling obj.__getattr__('x'). 

5060 

5061 if (name in self._internal_names_set or name in self._metadata or 

5062 name in self._accessors): 

5063 return object.__getattribute__(self, name) 

5064 else: 

5065 if self._info_axis._can_hold_identifiers_and_holds_name(name): 

5066 return self[name] 

5067 return object.__getattribute__(self, name) 

5068 

5069 def __setattr__(self, name, value): 

5070 """After regular attribute access, try setting the name 

5071 This allows simpler access to columns for interactive use. 

5072 """ 

5073 

5074 # first try regular attribute access via __getattribute__, so that 

5075 # e.g. ``obj.x`` and ``obj.x = 4`` will always reference/modify 

5076 # the same attribute. 

5077 

5078 try: 

5079 object.__getattribute__(self, name) 

5080 return object.__setattr__(self, name, value) 

5081 except AttributeError: 

5082 pass 

5083 

5084 # if this fails, go on to more involved attribute setting 

5085 # (note that this matches __getattr__, above). 

5086 if name in self._internal_names_set: 

5087 object.__setattr__(self, name, value) 

5088 elif name in self._metadata: 

5089 object.__setattr__(self, name, value) 

5090 else: 

5091 try: 

5092 existing = getattr(self, name) 

5093 if isinstance(existing, Index): 

5094 object.__setattr__(self, name, value) 

5095 elif name in self._info_axis: 

5096 self[name] = value 

5097 else: 

5098 object.__setattr__(self, name, value) 

5099 except (AttributeError, TypeError): 

5100 if isinstance(self, ABCDataFrame) and (is_list_like(value)): 

5101 warnings.warn("Pandas doesn't allow columns to be " 

5102 "created via a new attribute name - see " 

5103 "https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/" 

5104 "stable/indexing.html#attribute-access", 

5105 stacklevel=2) 

5106 object.__setattr__(self, name, value) 

5107 

5108 def _dir_additions(self): 

5109 """ add the string-like attributes from the info_axis. 

5110 If info_axis is a MultiIndex, it's first level values are used. 

5111 """ 

5112 additions = {c for c in self._info_axis.unique(level=0)[:100] 

5113 if isinstance(c, string_types) and isidentifier(c)} 

5114 return super(NDFrame, self)._dir_additions().union(additions) 

5115

5119 # ---------------------------------------------------------------------- 

5120 # Consolidation of internals 

5121 

5122 def _protect_consolidate(self, f): 

5123 """Consolidate _data -- if the blocks have changed, then clear the 

5124 cache 

5125 """ 

5126 blocks_before = len(self._data.blocks) 

5127 result = f() 

5128 if len(self._data.blocks) != blocks_before: 

5129 self._clear_item_cache() 

5130 return result 

5131 

5132 def _consolidate_inplace(self): 

5133 """Consolidate data in place and return None""" 

5134 

5135 def f(): 

5136 self._data = self._data.consolidate() 

5137 

5138 self._protect_consolidate(f) 

5139 

5140 def _consolidate(self, inplace=False): 

5141 """ 

5142 Compute NDFrame with "consolidated" internals (data of each dtype 

5143 grouped together in a single ndarray). 

5144 

5145 Parameters 

5146 ---------- 

5147 inplace : boolean, default False 

5148 If False return new object, otherwise modify existing object 

5149 

5150 Returns 

5151 ------- 

5152 consolidated : same type as caller 

5153 """ 

5154 inplace = validate_bool_kwarg(inplace, 'inplace') 

5155 if inplace: 

5156 self._consolidate_inplace() 

5157 else: 

5158 f = lambda: self._data.consolidate() 

5159 cons_data = self._protect_consolidate(f) 

5160 return self._constructor(cons_data).__finalize__(self) 

5161 

5162 @property 

5163 def _is_mixed_type(self): 

5164 f = lambda: self._data.is_mixed_type 

5165 return self._protect_consolidate(f) 

5166 

5167 @property 

5168 def _is_numeric_mixed_type(self): 

5169 f = lambda: self._data.is_numeric_mixed_type 

5170 return self._protect_consolidate(f) 

5171 

5172 @property 

5173 def _is_datelike_mixed_type(self): 

5174 f = lambda: self._data.is_datelike_mixed_type 

5175 return self._protect_consolidate(f) 

5176 

5177 def _check_inplace_setting(self, value): 

5178 """ check whether we allow in-place setting with this type of value """ 

5179 

5180 if self._is_mixed_type: 

5181 if not self._is_numeric_mixed_type: 

5182 

5183 # allow an actual np.nan thru 

5184 try: 

5185 if np.isnan(value): 

5186 return True 

5187 except Exception: 

5188 pass 

5189 

5190 raise TypeError('Cannot do inplace boolean setting on ' 

5191 'mixed-types with a non np.nan value') 

5192 

5193 return True 

5194 

5195 def _get_numeric_data(self): 

5196 return self._constructor( 

5197 self._data.get_numeric_data()).__finalize__(self) 

5198 

5199 def _get_bool_data(self): 

5200 return self._constructor(self._data.get_bool_data()).__finalize__(self)

5204 

5205 def as_matrix(self, columns=None): 

5206 """ 

5207 Convert the frame to its Numpy-array representation. 

5208 

5209 .. deprecated:: 0.23.0 

5210 Use :meth:`DataFrame.values` instead. 

5211 

5212 Parameters 

5213 ---------- 

5214 columns : list, optional, default:None 

5215 If None, return all columns, otherwise, returns specified columns. 

5216 

5217 Returns 

5218 ------- 

5219 values : ndarray 

5220 If the caller is heterogeneous and contains booleans or objects, 

5221 the result will be of dtype=object. See Notes. 

5222 

5223 See Also 

5224 -------- 

5225 DataFrame.values 

5226 

5227 Notes 

5228 ----- 

5229 Return is NOT a Numpy-matrix, rather, a Numpy-array. 

5230 

5231 The dtype will be a lower-common-denominator dtype (implicit 

5232 upcasting); that is to say if the dtypes (even of numeric types) 

5233 are mixed, the one that accommodates all will be chosen. Use this 

5234 with care if you are not dealing with the blocks. 

5235 

5236 e.g. If the dtypes are float16 and float32, dtype will be upcast to 

5237 float32. If dtypes are int32 and uint8, dtype will be upcase to 

5238 int32. By numpy.find_common_type convention, mixing int64 and uint64 

5239 will result in a float64 dtype. 

5240 

5241 This method is provided for backwards compatibility. Generally, 

5242 it is recommended to use '.values'. 

5243 """ 

5244 warnings.warn("Method .as_matrix will be removed in a future version. " 

5245 "Use .values instead.", FutureWarning, stacklevel=2) 

5246 self._consolidate_inplace() 

5247 return self._data.as_array(transpose=self._AXIS_REVERSED, 

5248 items=columns) 

5249 

5250 @property 

5251 def values(self): 

5252 """ 

5253 Return a Numpy representation of the DataFrame. 

5254 

5255 .. warning:: 

5256 

5257 We recommend using :meth:`DataFrame.to_numpy` instead. 

5258 

5259 Only the values in the DataFrame will be returned, the axes labels 

5260 will be removed. 

5261 

5262 Returns 

5263 ------- 

5264 numpy.ndarray 

5265 The values of the DataFrame. 

5266 

5267 See Also 

5268 -------- 

5269 DataFrame.to_numpy : Recommended alternative to this method. 

5270 pandas.DataFrame.index : Retrieve the index labels. 

5271 pandas.DataFrame.columns : Retrieving the column names. 

5272 

5273 Notes 

5274 ----- 

5275 The dtype will be a lower-common-denominator dtype (implicit 

5276 upcasting); that is to say if the dtypes (even of numeric types) 

5277 are mixed, the one that accommodates all will be chosen. Use this 

5278 with care if you are not dealing with the blocks. 

5279 

5280 e.g. If the dtypes are float16 and float32, dtype will be upcast to 

5281 float32. If dtypes are int32 and uint8, dtype will be upcast to 

5282 int32. By :func:`numpy.find_common_type` convention, mixing int64 

5283 and uint64 will result in a float64 dtype. 

5284 

5285 Examples 

5286 -------- 

5287 A DataFrame where all columns are the same type (e.g., int64) results 

5288 in an array of the same type. 

5289 

5290 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'age': [ 3, 29], 

5291 ... 'height': [94, 170], 

5292 ... 'weight': [31, 115]}) 

5293 >>> df 

5294 age height weight 

5295 0 3 94 31 

5296 1 29 170 115 

5297 >>> df.dtypes 

5298 age int64 

5299 height int64 

5300 weight int64 

5301 dtype: object 

5302 >>> df.values 

5303 array([[ 3, 94, 31], 

5304 [ 29, 170, 115]], dtype=int64) 

5305 

5306 A DataFrame with mixed type columns(e.g., str/object, int64, float32) 

5307 results in an ndarray of the broadest type that accommodates these 

5308 mixed types (e.g., object). 

5309 

5310 >>> df2 = pd.DataFrame([('parrot', 24.0, 'second'), 

5311 ... ('lion', 80.5, 1), 

5312 ... ('monkey', np.nan, None)], 

5313 ... columns=('name', 'max_speed', 'rank')) 

5314 >>> df2.dtypes 

5315 name object 

5316 max_speed float64 

5317 rank object 

5318 dtype: object 

5319 >>> df2.values 

5320 array([['parrot', 24.0, 'second'], 

5321 ['lion', 80.5, 1], 

5322 ['monkey', nan, None]], dtype=object) 

5323 """ 

5324 self._consolidate_inplace() 

5325 return self._data.as_array(transpose=self._AXIS_REVERSED) 

5326 

5327 @property 

5328 def _values(self): 

5329 """internal implementation""" 

5330 return self.values 

5331 

5332 @property 

5333 def _get_values(self): 

5334 # compat 

5335 return self.values 

5336 

5337 def get_values(self): 

5338 """ 

5339 Return an ndarray after converting sparse values to dense. 

5340 

5341 This is the same as ``.values`` for non-sparse data. For sparse 

5342 data contained in a `pandas.SparseArray`, the data are first 

5343 converted to a dense representation. 

5344 

5345 Returns 

5346 ------- 

5347 numpy.ndarray 

5348 Numpy representation of DataFrame 

5349 

5350 See Also 

5351 -------- 

5352 values : Numpy representation of DataFrame. 

5353 pandas.SparseArray : Container for sparse data. 

5354 

5355 Examples 

5356 -------- 

5357 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'a': [1, 2], 'b': [True, False], 

5358 ... 'c': [1.0, 2.0]}) 

5359 >>> df 

5360 a b c 

5361 0 1 True 1.0 

5362 1 2 False 2.0 

5363 

5364 >>> df.get_values()

5366 

5367 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({"a": pd.SparseArray([1, None, None]), 

5368 ... "c": [1.0, 2.0, 3.0]})

5371 0 1.0 1.0 

5372 1 NaN 2.0 

5373 2 NaN 3.0 

5374 

5375 >>> df.get_values()
