5377 [nan, 2.], 

5378 [nan, 3.]]) 

5379 """ 

5380 return self.values 

5381 

5382 def get_dtype_counts(self): 

5383 """ 

5384 Return counts of unique dtypes in this object. 

5385 

5386 Returns 

5387 ------- 

5388 dtype : Series 

5389 Series with the count of columns with each dtype. 

5390 

5391 See Also 

5392 -------- 

5393 dtypes : Return the dtypes in this object. 

5394 

5395 Examples 

5396 -------- 

5397 >>> a = [['a', 1, 1.0], ['b', 2, 2.0], ['c', 3, 3.0]] 

5398 >>> df = pd.DataFrame(a, columns=['str', 'int', 'float']) 

5399 >>> df 

5400 str int float 

5401 0 a 1 1.0 

5402 1 b 2 2.0 

5403 2 c 3 3.0 

5404 

5405 >>> df.get_dtype_counts() 

5406 float64 1 

5407 int64 1 

5408 object 1 

5409 dtype: int64 

5410 """ 

5411 from pandas import Series 

5412 return Series(self._data.get_dtype_counts())

5542 a homogeneous dtype.

5545

5547 as_matrix) 

5548

5551 copy : boolean, default True 

5552 

5553 Returns 

5554 ------- 

5555 values : a dict of dtype -> Constructor Types 

5556 """ 

5557 warnings.warn("as_blocks is deprecated and will " 

5558 "be removed in a future version", 

5559 FutureWarning, stacklevel=2)

5572 """ 

5573 Return a dict of dtype -> Constructor Types that 

5574 each is a homogeneous dtype. 

5575 

5576 Internal ONLY 

5577 """ 

5578 return {k: self._constructor(v).__finalize__(self) 

5579 for k, v, in self._data.to_dict(copy=copy).items()} 

5580 

5581 def astype(self, dtype, copy=True, errors='raise', **kwargs): 

5582 """ 

5583 Cast a pandas object to a specified dtype ``dtype``. 

5584 

5585 Parameters 

5586 ---------- 

5587 dtype : data type, or dict of column name -> data type 

5588 Use a numpy.dtype or Python type to cast entire pandas object to 

5589 the same type. Alternatively, use {col: dtype, ...}, where col is a 

5590 column label and dtype is a numpy.dtype or Python type to cast one 

5591 or more of the DataFrame's columns to column-specific types. 

5592 copy : bool, default True 

5593 Return a copy when ``copy=True`` (be very careful setting 

5594 ``copy=False`` as changes to values then may propagate to other 

5595 pandas objects). 

5596 errors : {'raise', 'ignore'}, default 'raise' 

5597 Control raising of exceptions on invalid data for provided dtype. 

5598 

5599 - ``raise`` : allow exceptions to be raised 

5600 - ``ignore`` : suppress exceptions. On error return original object 

5601 

5602 .. versionadded:: 0.20.0 

5603 

5604 kwargs : keyword arguments to pass on to the constructor 

5605 

5606 Returns 

5607 ------- 

5608 casted : same type as caller 

5609 

5610 See Also 

5611 -------- 

5612 to_datetime : Convert argument to datetime. 

5613 to_timedelta : Convert argument to timedelta. 

5614 to_numeric : Convert argument to a numeric type. 

5615 numpy.ndarray.astype : Cast a numpy array to a specified type. 

5616 

5617 Examples 

5618 -------- 

5619 >>> ser = pd.Series([1, 2], dtype='int32') 

5620 >>> ser 

5621 0 1 

5622 1 2 

5623 dtype: int32 

5624 >>> ser.astype('int64') 

5625 0 1 

5626 1 2 

5627 dtype: int64 

5628 

5629 Convert to categorical type: 

5630 

5631 >>> ser.astype('category') 

5632 0 1 

5633 1 2 

5634 dtype: category 

5635 Categories (2, int64): [1, 2] 

5636 

5637 Convert to ordered categorical type with custom ordering: 

5638 

5639 >>> cat_dtype = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype( 

5640 ... categories=[2, 1], ordered=True) 

5641 >>> ser.astype(cat_dtype) 

5642 0 1 

5643 1 2 

5644 dtype: category 

5645 Categories (2, int64): [2 < 1] 

5646 

5647 Note that using ``copy=False`` and changing data on a new 

5648 pandas object may propagate changes: 

5649 

5650 >>> s1 = pd.Series([1,2]) 

5651 >>> s2 = s1.astype('int64', copy=False) 

5652 >>> s2[0] = 10 

5653 >>> s1 # note that s1[0] has changed too 

5654 0 10 

5655 1 2 

5656 dtype: int64 

5657 """ 

5658 if is_dict_like(dtype): 

5659 if self.ndim == 1: # i.e. Series 

5660 if len(dtype) > 1 or self.name not in dtype: 

5661 raise KeyError('Only the Series name can be used for ' 

5662 'the key in Series dtype mappings.') 

5663 new_type = dtype[self.name] 

5664 return self.astype(new_type, copy, errors, **kwargs) 

5665 elif self.ndim > 2: 

5666 raise NotImplementedError( 

5667 'astype() only accepts a dtype arg of type dict when ' 

5668 'invoked on Series and DataFrames. A single dtype must be ' 

5669 'specified when invoked on a Panel.' 

5670 ) 

5671 for col_name in dtype.keys(): 

5672 if col_name not in self: 

5673 raise KeyError('Only a column name can be used for the ' 

5674 'key in a dtype mappings argument.') 

5675 results = [] 

5676 for col_name, col in self.iteritems(): 

5677 if col_name in dtype: 

5678 results.append(col.astype(dtype[col_name], copy=copy)) 

5679 else: 

5680 results.append(results.append(col.copy() if copy else col)) 

5681 

5682 elif is_extension_array_dtype(dtype) and self.ndim > 1: 

5683 # GH 18099/22869: columnwise conversion to extension dtype 

5684 # GH 24704: use iloc to handle duplicate column names 

5685 results = (self.iloc[:, i].astype(dtype, copy=copy) 

5686 for i in range(len(self.columns))) 

5687 

5688 else: 

5689 # else, only a single dtype is given 

5690 new_data = self._data.astype(dtype=dtype, copy=copy, errors=errors, 

5691 **kwargs) 

5692 return self._constructor(new_data).__finalize__(self) 

5693 

5694 # GH 19920: retain column metadata after concat 

5695 result = pd.concat(results, axis=1, copy=False) 

5696 result.columns = self.columns 

5697 return result 

5698 

5699 def copy(self, deep=True): 

5700 """ 

5701 Make a copy of this object's indices and data. 

5702 

5703 When ``deep=True`` (default), a new object will be created with a 

5704 copy of the calling object's data and indices. Modifications to 

5705 the data or indices of the copy will not be reflected in the 

5706 original object (see notes below). 

5707 

5708 When ``deep=False``, a new object will be created without copying 

5709 the calling object's data or index (only references to the data 

5710 and index are copied). Any changes to the data of the original 

5711 will be reflected in the shallow copy (and vice versa). 

5712 

5713 Parameters 

5714 ---------- 

5715 deep : bool, default True 

5716 Make a deep copy, including a copy of the data and the indices. 

5717 With ``deep=False`` neither the indices nor the data are copied. 

5718 

5719 Returns 

5720 ------- 

5721 copy : Series, DataFrame or Panel 

5722 Object type matches caller. 

5723 

5724 Notes 

5725 ----- 

5726 When ``deep=True``, data is copied but actual Python objects 

5727 will not be copied recursively, only the reference to the object. 

5728 This is in contrast to `copy.deepcopy` in the Standard Library, 

5729 which recursively copies object data (see examples below). 

5730 

5731 While ``Index`` objects are copied when ``deep=True``, the underlying 

5732 numpy array is not copied for performance reasons. Since ``Index`` is 

5733 immutable, the underlying data can be safely shared and a copy 

5734 is not needed. 

5735 

5736 Examples 

5737 -------- 

5738 >>> s = pd.Series([1, 2], index=["a", "b"]) 

5739 >>> s 

5740 a 1 

5741 b 2 

5742 dtype: int64 

5743 

5744 >>> s_copy = s.copy() 

5745 >>> s_copy 

5746 a 1 

5747 b 2 

5748 dtype: int64 

5749 

5750 **Shallow copy versus default (deep) copy:** 

5751 

5752 >>> s = pd.Series([1, 2], index=["a", "b"]) 

5753 >>> deep = s.copy() 

5754 >>> shallow = s.copy(deep=False) 

5755 

5756 Shallow copy shares data and index with original. 

5757 

5758 >>> s is shallow 

5759 False 

5760 >>> s.values is shallow.values and s.index is shallow.index 

5761 True 

5762 

5763 Deep copy has own copy of data and index. 

5764 

5765 >>> s is deep 

5766 False 

5767 >>> s.values is deep.values or s.index is deep.index 

5768 False 

5769 

5770 Updates to the data shared by shallow copy and original is reflected 

5771 in both; deep copy remains unchanged. 

5772 

5773 >>> s[0] = 3 

5774 >>> shallow[1] = 4 

5775 >>> s 

5776 a 3 

5777 b 4 

5778 dtype: int64 

5779 >>> shallow 

5780 a 3 

5781 b 4 

5782 dtype: int64 

5783 >>> deep 

5784 a 1 

5785 b 2 

5786 dtype: int64 

5787 

5788 Note that when copying an object containing Python objects, a deep copy 

5789 will copy the data, but will not do so recursively. Updating a nested 

5790 data object will be reflected in the deep copy. 

5791 

5792 >>> s = pd.Series([[1, 2], [3, 4]]) 

5793 >>> deep = s.copy() 

5794 >>> s[0][0] = 10 

5795 >>> s 

5796 0 [10, 2] 

5797 1 [3, 4] 

5798 dtype: object 

5799 >>> deep 

5800 0 [10, 2] 

5801 1 [3, 4] 

5802 dtype: object 

5803 """ 

5804 data = self._data.copy(deep=deep) 

5805 return self._constructor(data).__finalize__(self) 

5806 

5807 def __copy__(self, deep=True): 

5808 return self.copy(deep=deep) 

5809 

5810 def __deepcopy__(self, memo=None): 

5811 """ 

5812 Parameters 

5813 ---------- 

5814 memo, default None 

5815 Standard signature. Unused 

5816 """ 

5817 if memo is None: 

5818 memo = {} 

5819 return self.copy(deep=True)

5821 def _convert(self, datetime=False, numeric=False, timedelta=False, 

5822 coerce=False, copy=True): 

5823 """ 

5824 Attempt to infer better dtype for object columns 

5825 

5826 Parameters 

5827 ---------- 

5828 datetime : boolean, default False 

5829 If True, convert to date where possible. 

5830 numeric : boolean, default False 

5831 If True, attempt to convert to numbers (including strings), with 

5832 unconvertible values becoming NaN. 

5833 timedelta : boolean, default False 

5834 If True, convert to timedelta where possible. 

5835 coerce : boolean, default False 

5836 If True, force conversion with unconvertible values converted to 

5837 nulls (NaN or NaT) 

5838 copy : boolean, default True 

5839 If True, return a copy even if no copy is necessary (e.g. no 

5840 conversion was done). Note: This is meant for internal use, and 

5841 should not be confused with inplace. 

5842 

5843 Returns 

5844 ------- 

5845 converted : same as input object 

5846 """ 

5847 return self._constructor( 

5848 self._data.convert(datetime=datetime, numeric=numeric, 

5849 timedelta=timedelta, coerce=coerce, 

5850 copy=copy)).__finalize__(self)

5885 msg = ("convert_objects is deprecated. To re-infer data dtypes for " 

5886 "object columns, use {klass}.infer_objects()\nFor all " 

5887 "other conversions use the data-type specific converters " 

5888 "pd.to_datetime, pd.to_timedelta and pd.to_numeric."

5894 convert_numeric=convert_numeric,

5898 def infer_objects(self): 

5899 """ 

5900 Attempt to infer better dtypes for object columns. 

5901 

5902 Attempts soft conversion of object-dtyped 

5903 columns, leaving non-object and unconvertible 

5904 columns unchanged. The inference rules are the 

5905 same as during normal Series/DataFrame construction. 

5906 

5907 .. versionadded:: 0.21.0 

5908 

5909 Returns 

5910 ------- 

5911 converted : same type as input object 

5912 

5913 See Also 

5914 -------- 

5915 to_datetime : Convert argument to datetime. 

5916 to_timedelta : Convert argument to timedelta. 

5917 to_numeric : Convert argument to numeric type. 

5918 

5919 Examples 

5920 -------- 

5921 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({"A": ["a", 1, 2, 3]}) 

5922 >>> df = df.iloc[1:] 

5923 >>> df 

5924 A 

5925 1 1 

5926 2 2 

5927 3 3 

5928 

5929 >>> df.dtypes 

5930 A object 

5931 dtype: object 

5932 

5933 >>> df.infer_objects().dtypes 

5934 A int64 

5935 dtype: object 

5936 """ 

5937 # numeric=False necessary to only soft convert; 

5938 # python objects will still be converted to 

5939 # native numpy numeric types 

5940 return self._constructor( 

5941 self._data.convert(datetime=True, numeric=False, 

5942 timedelta=True, coerce=False, 

5943 copy=True)).__finalize__(self)

5945 # ---------------------------------------------------------------------- 

5946 # Filling NA's 

5947 

5948 def fillna(self, value=None, method=None, axis=None, inplace=False, 

5949 limit=None, downcast=None): 

5950 """ 

5951 Fill NA/NaN values using the specified method. 

5952 

5953 Parameters 

5954 ---------- 

5955 value : scalar, dict, Series, or DataFrame 

5956 Value to use to fill holes (e.g. 0), alternately a 

5957 dict/Series/DataFrame of values specifying which value to use for 

5958 each index (for a Series) or column (for a DataFrame). (values not 

5959 in the dict/Series/DataFrame will not be filled). This value cannot 

5960 be a list. 

5961 method : {'backfill', 'bfill', 'pad', 'ffill', None}, default None 

5962 Method to use for filling holes in reindexed Series 

5963 pad / ffill: propagate last valid observation forward to next valid 

5964 backfill / bfill: use NEXT valid observation to fill gap 

5965 axis : %(axes_single_arg)s 

5966 inplace : boolean, default False 

5967 If True, fill in place. Note: this will modify any 

5968 other views on this object, (e.g. a no-copy slice for a column in a 

5969 DataFrame). 

5970 limit : int, default None 

5971 If method is specified, this is the maximum number of consecutive 

5972 NaN values to forward/backward fill. In other words, if there is 

5973 a gap with more than this number of consecutive NaNs, it will only 

5974 be partially filled. If method is not specified, this is the 

5975 maximum number of entries along the entire axis where NaNs will be 

5976 filled. Must be greater than 0 if not None. 

5977 downcast : dict, default is None 

5978 a dict of item->dtype of what to downcast if possible, 

5979 or the string 'infer' which will try to downcast to an appropriate 

5980 equal type (e.g. float64 to int64 if possible) 

5981 

5982 Returns 

5983 ------- 

5984 filled : %(klass)s 

5985 

5986 See Also 

5987 -------- 

5988 interpolate : Fill NaN values using interpolation. 

5989 reindex, asfreq 

5990 

5991 Examples 

5992 -------- 

5993 >>> df = pd.DataFrame([[np.nan, 2, np.nan, 0], 

5994 ... [3, 4, np.nan, 1], 

5995 ... [np.nan, np.nan, np.nan, 5], 

5996 ... [np.nan, 3, np.nan, 4]], 

5997 ... columns=list('ABCD')) 

5998 >>> df 

5999 A B C D 

6000 0 NaN 2.0 NaN 0 

6001 1 3.0 4.0 NaN 1 

6002 2 NaN NaN NaN 5 

6003 3 NaN 3.0 NaN 4 

6004 

6005 Replace all NaN elements with 0s. 

6006 

6007 >>> df.fillna(0) 

6008 A B C D 

6009 0 0.0 2.0 0.0 0 

6010 1 3.0 4.0 0.0 1 

6011 2 0.0 0.0 0.0 5 

6012 3 0.0 3.0 0.0 4 

6013 

6014 We can also propagate non-null values forward or backward. 

6015 

6016 >>> df.fillna(method='ffill') 

6017 A B C D 

6018 0 NaN 2.0 NaN 0 

6019 1 3.0 4.0 NaN 1 

6020 2 3.0 4.0 NaN 5 

6021 3 3.0 3.0 NaN 4 

6022 

6023 Replace all NaN elements in column 'A', 'B', 'C', and 'D', with 0, 1, 

6024 2, and 3 respectively. 

6025 

6026 >>> values = {'A': 0, 'B': 1, 'C': 2, 'D': 3} 

6027 >>> df.fillna(value=values) 

6028 A B C D 

6029 0 0.0 2.0 2.0 0 

6030 1 3.0 4.0 2.0 1 

6031 2 0.0 1.0 2.0 5 

6032 3 0.0 3.0 2.0 4 

6033 

6034 Only replace the first NaN element. 

6035 

6036 >>> df.fillna(value=values, limit=1) 

6037 A B C D 

6038 0 0.0 2.0 2.0 0 

6039 1 3.0 4.0 NaN 1 

6040 2 NaN 1.0 NaN 5 

6041 3 NaN 3.0 NaN 4 

6042 """ 

6043 inplace = validate_bool_kwarg(inplace, 'inplace') 

6044 value, method = validate_fillna_kwargs(value, method) 

6045 

6046 self._consolidate_inplace() 

6047 

6048 # set the default here, so functions examining the signaure 

6049 # can detect if something was set (e.g. in groupby) (GH9221) 

6050 if axis is None: 

6051 axis = 0 

6052 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

6053 

6054 from pandas import DataFrame 

6055 if value is None: 

6056 

6057 if self._is_mixed_type and axis == 1: 

6058 if inplace: 

6059 raise NotImplementedError() 

6060 result = self.T.fillna(method=method, limit=limit).T 

6061 

6062 # need to downcast here because of all of the transposes 

6063 result._data = result._data.downcast() 

6064 

6065 return result 

6066 

6067 # > 3d 

6068 if self.ndim > 3: 

6069 raise NotImplementedError('Cannot fillna with a method for > ' 

6070 '3dims') 

6071 

6072 # 3d 

6073 elif self.ndim == 3: 

6074 # fill in 2d chunks 

6075 result = {col: s.fillna(method=method, value=value) 

6076 for col, s in self.iteritems()} 

6077 prelim_obj = self._constructor.from_dict(result) 

6078 new_obj = prelim_obj.__finalize__(self) 

6079 new_data = new_obj._data 

6080 

6081 else: 

6082 # 2d or less 

6083 new_data = self._data.interpolate(method=method, axis=axis, 

6084 limit=limit, inplace=inplace, 

6085 coerce=True, 

6086 downcast=downcast) 

6087 else: 

6088 if len(self._get_axis(axis)) == 0: 

6089 return self 

6090 

6091 if self.ndim == 1: 

6092 if isinstance(value, (dict, ABCSeries)): 

6093 from pandas import Series 

6094 value = Series(value) 

6095 elif not is_list_like(value): 

6096 pass 

6097 else: 

6098 raise TypeError('"value" parameter must be a scalar, dict ' 

6099 'or Series, but you passed a ' 

6100 '"{0}"'.format(type(value).__name__)) 

6101 

6102 new_data = self._data.fillna(value=value, limit=limit, 

6103 inplace=inplace, 

6104 downcast=downcast) 

6105 

6106 elif isinstance(value, (dict, ABCSeries)): 

6107 if axis == 1: 

6108 raise NotImplementedError('Currently only can fill ' 

6109 'with dict/Series column ' 

6110 'by column') 

6111 

6112 result = self if inplace else self.copy() 

6113 for k, v in compat.iteritems(value): 

6114 if k not in result: 

6115 continue 

6116 obj = result[k] 

6117 obj.fillna(v, limit=limit, inplace=True, downcast=downcast) 

6118 return result if not inplace else None 

6119 

6120 elif not is_list_like(value): 

6121 new_data = self._data.fillna(value=value, limit=limit, 

6122 inplace=inplace, 

6123 downcast=downcast) 

6124 elif isinstance(value, DataFrame) and self.ndim == 2: 

6125 new_data = self.where(self.notna(), value) 

6126 else: 

6127 raise ValueError("invalid fill value with a %s" % type(value)) 

6128 

6129 if inplace: 

6130 self._update_inplace(new_data) 

6131 else: 

6132 return self._constructor(new_data).__finalize__(self) 

6133 

6134 def ffill(self, axis=None, inplace=False, limit=None, downcast=None): 

6135 """ 

6136 Synonym for :meth:`DataFrame.fillna` with ``method='ffill'``. 

6137 """ 

6138 return self.fillna(method='ffill', axis=axis, inplace=inplace, 

6139 limit=limit, downcast=downcast) 

6140 

6141 def bfill(self, axis=None, inplace=False, limit=None, downcast=None): 

6142 """ 

6143 Synonym for :meth:`DataFrame.fillna` with ``method='bfill'``. 

6144 """ 

6145 return self.fillna(method='bfill', axis=axis, inplace=inplace, 

6146 limit=limit, downcast=downcast)

6148 _shared_docs['replace'] = (""" 

6149 Replace values given in `to_replace` with `value`. 

6150 

6151 Values of the %(klass)s are replaced with other values dynamically. 

6152 This differs from updating with ``.loc`` or ``.iloc``, which require 

6153 you to specify a location to update with some value. 

6154 

6155 Parameters 

6156 ---------- 

6157 to_replace : str, regex, list, dict, Series, int, float, or None 

6158 How to find the values that will be replaced. 

6159 

6160 * numeric, str or regex: 

6161 

6162 - numeric: numeric values equal to `to_replace` will be 

6163 replaced with `value` 

6164 - str: string exactly matching `to_replace` will be replaced 

6165 with `value` 

6166 - regex: regexs matching `to_replace` will be replaced with 

6167 `value` 

6168 

6169 * list of str, regex, or numeric: 

6170 

6171 - First, if `to_replace` and `value` are both lists, they 

6172 **must** be the same length. 

6173 - Second, if ``regex=True`` then all of the strings in **both** 

6174 lists will be interpreted as regexs otherwise they will match 

6175 directly. This doesn't matter much for `value` since there 

6176 are only a few possible substitution regexes you can use. 

6177 - str, regex and numeric rules apply as above. 

6178 

6179 * dict: 

6180 

6181 - Dicts can be used to specify different replacement values 

6182 for different existing values. For example, 

6183 ``{'a': 'b', 'y': 'z'}`` replaces the value 'a' with 'b' and 

6184 'y' with 'z'. To use a dict in this way the `value` 

6185 parameter should be `None`. 

6186 - For a DataFrame a dict can specify that different values 

6187 should be replaced in different columns. For example, 

6188 ``{'a': 1, 'b': 'z'}`` looks for the value 1 in column 'a' 

6189 and the value 'z' in column 'b' and replaces these values 

6190 with whatever is specified in `value`. The `value` parameter 

6191 should not be ``None`` in this case. You can treat this as a 

6192 special case of passing two lists except that you are 

6193 specifying the column to search in. 

6194 - For a DataFrame nested dictionaries, e.g., 

6195 ``{'a': {'b': np.nan}}``, are read as follows: look in column 

6196 'a' for the value 'b' and replace it with NaN. The `value` 

6197 parameter should be ``None`` to use a nested dict in this 

6198 way. You can nest regular expressions as well. Note that 

6199 column names (the top-level dictionary keys in a nested 

6200 dictionary) **cannot** be regular expressions. 

6201 

6202 * None: 

6203 

6204 - This means that the `regex` argument must be a string, 

6205 compiled regular expression, or list, dict, ndarray or 

6206 Series of such elements. If `value` is also ``None`` then 

6207 this **must** be a nested dictionary or Series. 

6208 

6209 See the examples section for examples of each of these. 

6210 value : scalar, dict, list, str, regex, default None 

6211 Value to replace any values matching `to_replace` with. 

6212 For a DataFrame a dict of values can be used to specify which 

6213 value to use for each column (columns not in the dict will not be 

6214 filled). Regular expressions, strings and lists or dicts of such 

6215 objects are also allowed. 

6216 inplace : bool, default False 

6217 If True, in place. Note: this will modify any 

6218 other views on this object (e.g. a column from a DataFrame). 

6219 Returns the caller if this is True. 

6220 limit : int, default None 

6221 Maximum size gap to forward or backward fill. 

6222 regex : bool or same types as `to_replace`, default False 

6223 Whether to interpret `to_replace` and/or `value` as regular 

6224 expressions. If this is ``True`` then `to_replace` *must* be a 

6225 string. Alternatively, this could be a regular expression or a 

6226 list, dict, or array of regular expressions in which case 

6227 `to_replace` must be ``None``. 

6228 method : {'pad', 'ffill', 'bfill', `None`} 

6229 The method to use when for replacement, when `to_replace` is a 

6230 scalar, list or tuple and `value` is ``None``. 

6231 

6232 .. versionchanged:: 0.23.0 

6233 Added to DataFrame. 

6234 

6235 Returns 

6236 ------- 

6237 %(klass)s 

6238 Object after replacement. 

6239 

6240 Raises 

6241 ------ 

6242 AssertionError 

6243 * If `regex` is not a ``bool`` and `to_replace` is not 

6244 ``None``. 

6245 TypeError 

6246 * If `to_replace` is a ``dict`` and `value` is not a ``list``, 

6247 ``dict``, ``ndarray``, or ``Series`` 

6248 * If `to_replace` is ``None`` and `regex` is not compilable 

6249 into a regular expression or is a list, dict, ndarray, or 

6250 Series. 

6251 * When replacing multiple ``bool`` or ``datetime64`` objects and 

6252 the arguments to `to_replace` does not match the type of the 

6253 value being replaced 

6254 ValueError 

6255 * If a ``list`` or an ``ndarray`` is passed to `to_replace` and 

6256 `value` but they are not the same length. 

6257 

6258 See Also 

6259 -------- 

6260 %(klass)s.fillna : Fill NA values. 

6261 %(klass)s.where : Replace values based on boolean condition. 

6262 Series.str.replace : Simple string replacement. 

6263 

6264 Notes 

6265 ----- 

6266 * Regex substitution is performed under the hood with ``re.sub``. The 

6267 rules for substitution for ``re.sub`` are the same. 

6268 * Regular expressions will only substitute on strings, meaning you 

6269 cannot provide, for example, a regular expression matching floating 

6270 point numbers and expect the columns in your frame that have a 

6271 numeric dtype to be matched. However, if those floating point 

6272 numbers *are* strings, then you can do this. 

6273 * This method has *a lot* of options. You are encouraged to experiment 

6274 and play with this method to gain intuition about how it works. 

6275 * When dict is used as the `to_replace` value, it is like 

6276 key(s) in the dict are the to_replace part and 

6277 value(s) in the dict are the value parameter. 

6278 

6279 Examples 

6280 -------- 

6281 

6282 **Scalar `to_replace` and `value`** 

6283 

6284 >>> s = pd.Series([0, 1, 2, 3, 4]) 

6285 >>> s.replace(0, 5) 

6286 0 5 

6287 1 1 

6288 2 2 

6289 3 3 

6290 4 4 

6291 dtype: int64 

6292 

6293 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'A': [0, 1, 2, 3, 4], 

6294 ... 'B': [5, 6, 7, 8, 9], 

6295 ... 'C': ['a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 'e']}) 

6296 >>> df.replace(0, 5) 

6297 A B C 

6298 0 5 5 a 

6299 1 1 6 b 

6300 2 2 7 c 

6301 3 3 8 d 

6302 4 4 9 e 

6303 

6304 **List-like `to_replace`** 

6305 

6306 >>> df.replace([0, 1, 2, 3], 4) 

6307 A B C 

6308 0 4 5 a 

6309 1 4 6 b 

6310 2 4 7 c 

6311 3 4 8 d 

6312 4 4 9 e 

6313 

6314 >>> df.replace([0, 1, 2, 3], [4, 3, 2, 1]) 

6315 A B C 

6316 0 4 5 a 

6317 1 3 6 b 

6318 2 2 7 c 

6319 3 1 8 d 

6320 4 4 9 e 

6321 

6322 >>> s.replace([1, 2], method='bfill')

6324 1 3 

6325 2 3

6327 4 4

6329 

6330 **dict-like `to_replace`** 

6331 

6332 >>> df.replace({0: 10, 1: 100}) 

6333 A B C 

6334 0 10 5 a 

6335 1 100 6 b 

6336 2 2 7 c 

6337 3 3 8 d 

6338 4 4 9 e 

6339 

6340 >>> df.replace({'A': 0, 'B': 5}, 100) 

6341 A B C 

6342 0 100 100 a 

6343 1 1 6 b 

6344 2 2 7 c 

6345 3 3 8 d 

6346 4 4 9 e 

6347

6350 0 100 5 a 

6351 1 1 6 b

6356 **Regular expression `to_replace`** 

6357 

6358 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'A': ['bat', 'foo', 'bait'], 

6359 ... 'B': ['abc', 'bar', 'xyz']}) 

6360 >>> df.replace(to_replace=r'^ba.$', value='new', regex=True) 

6361 A B 

6362 0 new abc 

6363 1 foo new 

6364 2 bait xyz 

6365 

6366 >>> df.replace({'A': r'^ba.$'}, {'A': 'new'}, regex=True) 

6367 A B 

6368 0 new abc 

6369 1 foo bar 

6370 2 bait xyz 

6371 

6372 >>> df.replace(regex=r'^ba.$', value='new') 

6373 A B 

6374 0 new abc 

6375 1 foo new 

6376 2 bait xyz 

6377 

6378 >>> df.replace(regex={r'^ba.$': 'new', 'foo': 'xyz'}) 

6379 A B 

6380 0 new abc 

6381 1 xyz new 

6382 2 bait xyz 

6383 

6384 >>> df.replace(regex=[r'^ba.$', 'foo'], value='new')

6386 0 new abc 

6387 1 new new 

6388 2 bait xyz 

6389 

6390 Note that when replacing multiple ``bool`` or ``datetime64`` objects, 

6391 the data types in the `to_replace` parameter must match the data 

6392 type of the value being replaced: 

6393 

6394 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'A': [True, False, True], 

6395 ... 'B': [False, True, False]}) 

6396 >>> df.replace({'a string': 'new value', True: False}) # raises 

6397 Traceback (most recent call last): 

6398 ... 

6399 TypeError: Cannot compare types 'ndarray(dtype=bool)' and 'str' 

6400 

6401 This raises a ``TypeError`` because one of the ``dict`` keys is not of 

6402 the correct type for replacement. 

6403 

6404 Compare the behavior of ``s.replace({'a': None})`` and 

6405 ``s.replace('a', None)`` to understand the peculiarities 

6406 of the `to_replace` parameter: 

6407 

6408 >>> s = pd.Series([10, 'a', 'a', 'b', 'a']) 

6409 

6410 When one uses a dict as the `to_replace` value, it is like the 

6411 value(s) in the dict are equal to the `value` parameter. 

6412 ``s.replace({'a': None})`` is equivalent to 

6413 ``s.replace(to_replace={'a': None}, value=None, method=None)``: 

6414 

6415 >>> s.replace({'a': None}) 

6416 0 10 

6417 1 None 

6418 2 None 

6419 3 b 

6420 4 None 

6421 dtype: object 

6422 

6423 When ``value=None`` and `to_replace` is a scalar, list or 

6424 tuple, `replace` uses the method parameter (default 'pad') to do the 

6425 replacement. So this is why the 'a' values are being replaced by 10 

6426 in rows 1 and 2 and 'b' in row 4 in this case. 

6427 The command ``s.replace('a', None)`` is actually equivalent to 

6428 ``s.replace(to_replace='a', value=None, method='pad')``: 

6429 

6430 >>> s.replace('a', None) 

6431 0 10 

6432 1 10 

6433 2 10 

6434 3 b 

6435 4 b 

6436 dtype: object 

6437 """)

6439 @Appender(_shared_docs['replace'] % _shared_doc_kwargs) 

6440 def replace(self, to_replace=None, value=None, inplace=False, limit=None, 

6441 regex=False, method='pad'): 

6442 inplace = validate_bool_kwarg(inplace, 'inplace') 

6443 if not is_bool(regex) and to_replace is not None: 

6444 raise AssertionError("'to_replace' must be 'None' if 'regex' is " 

6445 "not a bool") 

6446 

6447 self._consolidate_inplace() 

6448 

6449 if value is None: 

6450 # passing a single value that is scalar like 

6451 # when value is None (GH5319), for compat 

6452 if not is_dict_like(to_replace) and not is_dict_like(regex): 

6453 to_replace = [to_replace] 

6454 

6455 if isinstance(to_replace, (tuple, list)): 

6456 if isinstance(self, pd.DataFrame): 

6457 return self.apply(_single_replace, 

6458 args=(to_replace, method, inplace, 

6459 limit)) 

6460 return _single_replace(self, to_replace, method, inplace, 

6461 limit) 

6462 

6463 if not is_dict_like(to_replace): 

6464 if not is_dict_like(regex): 

6465 raise TypeError('If "to_replace" and "value" are both None' 

6466 ' and "to_replace" is not a list, then ' 

6467 'regex must be a mapping') 

6468 to_replace = regex 

6469 regex = True 

6470 

6471 items = list(compat.iteritems(to_replace)) 

6472 keys, values = lzip(*items) or ([], []) 

6473 

6474 are_mappings = [is_dict_like(v) for v in values] 

6475 

6476 if any(are_mappings): 

6477 if not all(are_mappings): 

6478 raise TypeError("If a nested mapping is passed, all values" 

6479 " of the top level mapping must be " 

6480 "mappings") 

6481 # passed a nested dict/Series 

6482 to_rep_dict = {} 

6483 value_dict = {} 

6484 

6485 for k, v in items: 

6486 keys, values = lzip(*v.items()) or ([], []) 

6487 if set(keys) & set(values): 

6488 raise ValueError("Replacement not allowed with " 

6489 "overlapping keys and values") 

6490 to_rep_dict[k] = list(keys) 

6491 value_dict[k] = list(values) 

6492 

6493 to_replace, value = to_rep_dict, value_dict 

6494 else: 

6495 to_replace, value = keys, values 

6496 

6497 return self.replace(to_replace, value, inplace=inplace, 

6498 limit=limit, regex=regex) 

6499 else: 

6500 

6501 # need a non-zero len on all axes 

6502 for a in self._AXIS_ORDERS: 

6503 if not len(self._get_axis(a)): 

6504 return self 

6505 

6506 new_data = self._data 

6507 if is_dict_like(to_replace): 

6508 if is_dict_like(value): # {'A' : NA} -> {'A' : 0} 

6509 res = self if inplace else self.copy() 

6510 for c, src in compat.iteritems(to_replace): 

6511 if c in value and c in self: 

6512 # object conversion is handled in 

6513 # series.replace which is called recursivelly 

6514 res[c] = res[c].replace(to_replace=src, 

6515 value=value[c], 

6516 inplace=False, 

6517 regex=regex) 

6518 return None if inplace else res 

6519 

6520 # {'A': NA} -> 0 

6521 elif not is_list_like(value): 

6522 keys = [(k, src) for k, src in compat.iteritems(to_replace) 

6523 if k in self] 

6524 keys_len = len(keys) - 1 

6525 for i, (k, src) in enumerate(keys): 

6526 convert = i == keys_len 

6527 new_data = new_data.replace(to_replace=src, 

6528 value=value, 

6529 filter=[k], 

6530 inplace=inplace, 

6531 regex=regex, 

6532 convert=convert) 

6533 else: 

6534 raise TypeError('value argument must be scalar, dict, or ' 

6535 'Series') 

6536 

6537 elif is_list_like(to_replace): # [NA, ''] -> [0, 'missing'] 

6538 if is_list_like(value): 

6539 if len(to_replace) != len(value): 

6540 raise ValueError('Replacement lists must match ' 

6541 'in length. Expecting %d got %d ' % 

6542 (len(to_replace), len(value))) 

6543 

6544 new_data = self._data.replace_list(src_list=to_replace, 

6545 dest_list=value, 

6546 inplace=inplace, 

6547 regex=regex) 

6548 

6549 else: # [NA, ''] -> 0 

6550 new_data = self._data.replace(to_replace=to_replace, 

6551 value=value, inplace=inplace, 

6552 regex=regex) 

6553 elif to_replace is None: 

6554 if not (is_re_compilable(regex) or 

6555 is_list_like(regex) or is_dict_like(regex)): 

6556 raise TypeError("'regex' must be a string or a compiled " 

6557 "regular expression or a list or dict of " 

6558 "strings or regular expressions, you " 

6559 "passed a" 

6560 " {0!r}".format(type(regex).__name__)) 

6561 return self.replace(regex, value, inplace=inplace, limit=limit, 

6562 regex=True) 

6563 else: 

6564 

6565 # dest iterable dict-like 

6566 if is_dict_like(value): # NA -> {'A' : 0, 'B' : -1} 

6567 new_data = self._data 

6568 

6569 for k, v in compat.iteritems(value): 

6570 if k in self: 

6571 new_data = new_data.replace(to_replace=to_replace, 

6572 value=v, filter=[k], 

6573 inplace=inplace, 

6574 regex=regex) 

6575 

6576 elif not is_list_like(value): # NA -> 0 

6577 new_data = self._data.replace(to_replace=to_replace, 

6578 value=value, inplace=inplace, 

6579 regex=regex) 

6580 else: 

6581 msg = ('Invalid "to_replace" type: ' 

6582 '{0!r}').format(type(to_replace).__name__) 

6583 raise TypeError(msg) # pragma: no cover 

6584 

6585 if inplace: 

6586 self._update_inplace(new_data) 

6587 else: 

6588 return self._constructor(new_data).__finalize__(self) 

6589 

6590 _shared_docs['interpolate'] = """ 

6591 Please note that only ``method='linear'`` is supported for 

6592 DataFrame/Series with a MultiIndex. 

6593 

6594 Parameters 

6595 ---------- 

6596 method : str, default 'linear' 

6597 Interpolation technique to use. One of: 

6598 

6599 * 'linear': Ignore the index and treat the values as equally 

6600 spaced. This is the only method supported on MultiIndexes. 

6601 * 'time': Works on daily and higher resolution data to interpolate 

6602 given length of interval. 

6603 * 'index', 'values': use the actual numerical values of the index. 

6604 * 'pad': Fill in NaNs using existing values. 

6605 * 'nearest', 'zero', 'slinear', 'quadratic', 'cubic', 'spline', 

6606 'barycentric', 'polynomial': Passed to 

6607 `scipy.interpolate.interp1d`. Both 'polynomial' and 'spline' 

6608 require that you also specify an `order` (int), 

6609 e.g. ``df.interpolate(method='polynomial', order=4)``. 

6610 These use the numerical values of the index. 

6611 * 'krogh', 'piecewise_polynomial', 'spline', 'pchip', 'akima': 

6612 Wrappers around the SciPy interpolation methods of similar 

6613 names. See `Notes`. 

6614 * 'from_derivatives': Refers to 

6615 `scipy.interpolate.BPoly.from_derivatives` which 

6616 replaces 'piecewise_polynomial' interpolation method in 

6617 scipy 0.18. 

6618 

6619 .. versionadded:: 0.18.1 

6620 

6621 Added support for the 'akima' method. 

6622 Added interpolate method 'from_derivatives' which replaces 

6623 'piecewise_polynomial' in SciPy 0.18; backwards-compatible with 

6624 SciPy < 0.18 

6625 

6626 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns', None}, default None 

6627 Axis to interpolate along. 

6628 limit : int, optional 

6629 Maximum number of consecutive NaNs to fill. Must be greater than 

6630 0. 

6631 inplace : bool, default False 

6632 Update the data in place if possible. 

6633 limit_direction : {'forward', 'backward', 'both'}, default 'forward' 

6634 If limit is specified, consecutive NaNs will be filled in this 

6635 direction. 

6636 limit_area : {`None`, 'inside', 'outside'}, default None 

6637 If limit is specified, consecutive NaNs will be filled with this 

6638 restriction. 

6639 

6640 * ``None``: No fill restriction. 

6641 * 'inside': Only fill NaNs surrounded by valid values 

6642 (interpolate). 

6643 * 'outside': Only fill NaNs outside valid values (extrapolate). 

6644 

6645 .. versionadded:: 0.21.0 

6646 

6647 downcast : optional, 'infer' or None, defaults to None 

6648 Downcast dtypes if possible. 

6649 **kwargs 

6650 Keyword arguments to pass on to the interpolating function. 

6651 

6652 Returns 

6653 ------- 

6654 Series or DataFrame 

6655 Returns the same object type as the caller, interpolated at 

6656 some or all ``NaN`` values 

6657 

6658 See Also 

6659 -------- 

6660 fillna : Fill missing values using different methods. 

6661 scipy.interpolate.Akima1DInterpolator : Piecewise cubic polynomials 

6662 (Akima interpolator). 

6663 scipy.interpolate.BPoly.from_derivatives : Piecewise polynomial in the 

6664 Bernstein basis. 

6665 scipy.interpolate.interp1d : Interpolate a 1-D function. 

6666 scipy.interpolate.KroghInterpolator : Interpolate polynomial (Krogh 

6667 interpolator). 

6668 scipy.interpolate.PchipInterpolator : PCHIP 1-d monotonic cubic 

6669 interpolation. 

6670 scipy.interpolate.CubicSpline : Cubic spline data interpolator. 

6671 

6672 Notes 

6673 ----- 

6674 The 'krogh', 'piecewise_polynomial', 'spline', 'pchip' and 'akima' 

6675 methods are wrappers around the respective SciPy implementations of 

6676 similar names. These use the actual numerical values of the index. 

6677 For more information on their behavior, see the 

6678 `SciPy documentation 

6679 <http://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy/reference/interpolate.html#univariate-interpolation>`__ 

6680 and `SciPy tutorial 

6681 <http://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy/reference/tutorial/interpolate.html>`__. 

6682 

6683 Examples 

6684 -------- 

6685 Filling in ``NaN`` in a :class:`~pandas.Series` via linear 

6686 interpolation. 

6687 

6688 >>> s = pd.Series([0, 1, np.nan, 3]) 

6689 >>> s 

6690 0 0.0 

6691 1 1.0 

6692 2 NaN 

6693 3 3.0 

6694 dtype: float64 

6695 >>> s.interpolate() 

6696 0 0.0 

6697 1 1.0 

6698 2 2.0 

6699 3 3.0 

6700 dtype: float64 

6701 

6702 Filling in ``NaN`` in a Series by padding, but filling at most two 

6703 consecutive ``NaN`` at a time. 

6704 

6705 >>> s = pd.Series([np.nan, "single_one", np.nan, 

6706 ... "fill_two_more", np.nan, np.nan, np.nan, 

6707 ... 4.71, np.nan]) 

6708 >>> s 

6709 0 NaN 

6710 1 single_one 

6711 2 NaN 

6712 3 fill_two_more 

6713 4 NaN 

6714 5 NaN 

6715 6 NaN 

6716 7 4.71 

6717 8 NaN 

6718 dtype: object 

6719 >>> s.interpolate(method='pad', limit=2) 

6720 0 NaN 

6721 1 single_one 

6722 2 single_one 

6723 3 fill_two_more 

6724 4 fill_two_more 

6725 5 fill_two_more 

6726 6 NaN 

6727 7 4.71 

6728 8 4.71 

6729 dtype: object 

6730 

6731 Filling in ``NaN`` in a Series via polynomial interpolation or splines: 

6732 Both 'polynomial' and 'spline' methods require that you also specify 

6733 an ``order`` (int). 

6734 

6735 >>> s = pd.Series([0, 2, np.nan, 8]) 

6736 >>> s.interpolate(method='polynomial', order=2) 

6737 0 0.000000 

6738 1 2.000000 

6739 2 4.666667 

6740 3 8.000000 

6741 dtype: float64 

6742 

6743 Fill the DataFrame forward (that is, going down) along each column 

6744 using linear interpolation. 

6745 

6746 Note how the last entry in column 'a' is interpolated differently, 

6747 because there is no entry after it to use for interpolation. 

6748 Note how the first entry in column 'b' remains ``NaN``, because there 

6749 is no entry befofe it to use for interpolation. 

6750 

6751 >>> df = pd.DataFrame([(0.0, np.nan, -1.0, 1.0), 

6752 ... (np.nan, 2.0, np.nan, np.nan), 

6753 ... (2.0, 3.0, np.nan, 9.0), 

6754 ... (np.nan, 4.0, -4.0, 16.0)], 

6755 ... columns=list('abcd')) 

6756 >>> df 

6757 a b c d 

6758 0 0.0 NaN -1.0 1.0 

6759 1 NaN 2.0 NaN NaN 

6760 2 2.0 3.0 NaN 9.0 

6761 3 NaN 4.0 -4.0 16.0 

6762 >>> df.interpolate(method='linear', limit_direction='forward', axis=0) 

6763 a b c d 

6764 0 0.0 NaN -1.0 1.0 

6765 1 1.0 2.0 -2.0 5.0 

6766 2 2.0 3.0 -3.0 9.0 

6767 3 2.0 4.0 -4.0 16.0 

6768 

6769 Using polynomial interpolation. 

6770 

6771 >>> df['d'].interpolate(method='polynomial', order=2) 

6772 0 1.0 

6773 1 4.0 

6774 2 9.0 

6775 3 16.0 

6776 Name: d, dtype: float64 

6777 """ 

6778 

6779 @Appender(_shared_docs['interpolate'] % _shared_doc_kwargs) 

6780 def interpolate(self, method='linear', axis=0, limit=None, inplace=False, 

6781 limit_direction='forward', limit_area=None, 

6782 downcast=None, **kwargs): 

6783 """ 

6784 Interpolate values according to different methods. 

6785 """ 

6786 inplace = validate_bool_kwarg(inplace, 'inplace') 

6787 

6788 if self.ndim > 2: 

6789 raise NotImplementedError("Interpolate has not been implemented " 

6790 "on Panel and Panel 4D objects.") 

6791 

6792 if axis == 0: 

6793 ax = self._info_axis_name 

6794 _maybe_transposed_self = self 

6795 elif axis == 1: 

6796 _maybe_transposed_self = self.T 

6797 ax = 1 

6798 else: 

6799 _maybe_transposed_self = self 

6800 ax = _maybe_transposed_self._get_axis_number(ax) 

6801 

6802 if _maybe_transposed_self.ndim == 2: 

6803 alt_ax = 1 - ax 

6804 else: 

6805 alt_ax = ax 

6806 

6807 if (isinstance(_maybe_transposed_self.index, MultiIndex) and 

6808 method != 'linear'): 

6809 raise ValueError("Only `method=linear` interpolation is supported " 

6810 "on MultiIndexes.") 

6811 

6812 if _maybe_transposed_self._data.get_dtype_counts().get( 

6813 'object') == len(_maybe_transposed_self.T): 

6814 raise TypeError("Cannot interpolate with all object-dtype columns " 

6815 "in the DataFrame. Try setting at least one " 

6816 "column to a numeric dtype.") 

6817 

6818 # create/use the index 

6819 if method == 'linear': 

6820 # prior default 

6821 index = np.arange(len(_maybe_transposed_self._get_axis(alt_ax))) 

6822 else: 

6823 index = _maybe_transposed_self._get_axis(alt_ax) 

6824 

6825 if isna(index).any(): 

6826 raise NotImplementedError("Interpolation with NaNs in the index " 

6827 "has not been implemented. Try filling " 

6828 "those NaNs before interpolating.") 

6829 data = _maybe_transposed_self._data 

6830 new_data = data.interpolate(method=method, axis=ax, index=index, 

6831 values=_maybe_transposed_self, limit=limit, 

6832 limit_direction=limit_direction, 

6833 limit_area=limit_area, 

6834 inplace=inplace, downcast=downcast, 

6835 **kwargs) 

6836 

6837 if inplace: 

6838 if axis == 1: 

6839 new_data = self._constructor(new_data).T._data 

6840 self._update_inplace(new_data) 

6841 else: 

6842 res = self._constructor(new_data).__finalize__(self) 

6843 if axis == 1: 

6844 res = res.T 

6845 return res 

6846 

6847 # ---------------------------------------------------------------------- 

6848 # Timeseries methods Methods 

6849 

6850 def asof(self, where, subset=None): 

6851 """ 

6852 Return the last row(s) without any NaNs before `where`. 

6853 

6854 The last row (for each element in `where`, if list) without any 

6855 NaN is taken. 

6856 In case of a :class:`~pandas.DataFrame`, the last row without NaN 

6857 considering only the subset of columns (if not `None`) 

6858 

6859 .. versionadded:: 0.19.0 For DataFrame 

6860 

6861 If there is no good value, NaN is returned for a Series or 

6862 a Series of NaN values for a DataFrame 

6863 

6864 Parameters 

6865 ---------- 

6866 where : date or array-like of dates 

6867 Date(s) before which the last row(s) are returned. 

6868 subset : str or array-like of str, default `None` 

6869 For DataFrame, if not `None`, only use these columns to 

6870 check for NaNs. 

6871 

6872 Returns 

6873 ------- 

6874 scalar, Series, or DataFrame 

6875 

6876 * scalar : when `self` is a Series and `where` is a scalar 

6877 * Series: when `self` is a Series and `where` is an array-like, 

6878 or when `self` is a DataFrame and `where` is a scalar 

6879 * DataFrame : when `self` is a DataFrame and `where` is an 

6880 array-like 

6881 

6882 See Also 

6883 -------- 

6884 merge_asof : Perform an asof merge. Similar to left join. 

6885 

6886 Notes 

6887 ----- 

6888 Dates are assumed to be sorted. Raises if this is not the case. 

6889 

6890 Examples 

6891 -------- 

6892 A Series and a scalar `where`. 

6893 

6894 >>> s = pd.Series([1, 2, np.nan, 4], index=[10, 20, 30, 40]) 

6895 >>> s 

6896 10 1.0 

6897 20 2.0 

6898 30 NaN 

6899 40 4.0 

6900 dtype: float64 

6901 

6902 >>> s.asof(20) 

6903 2.0 

6904 

6905 For a sequence `where`, a Series is returned. The first value is 

6906 NaN, because the first element of `where` is before the first 

6907 index value. 

6908 

6909 >>> s.asof([5, 20]) 

6910 5 NaN 

6911 20 2.0 

6912 dtype: float64 

6913 

6914 Missing values are not considered. The following is ``2.0``, not 

6915 NaN, even though NaN is at the index location for ``30``. 

6916 

6917 >>> s.asof(30) 

6918 2.0 

6919 

6920 Take all columns into consideration 

6921 

6922 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'a': [10, 20, 30, 40, 50], 

6923 ... 'b': [None, None, None, None, 500]}, 

6924 ... index=pd.DatetimeIndex(['2018-02-27 09:01:00', 

6925 ... '2018-02-27 09:02:00', 

6926 ... '2018-02-27 09:03:00', 

6927 ... '2018-02-27 09:04:00', 

6928 ... '2018-02-27 09:05:00'])) 

6929 >>> df.asof(pd.DatetimeIndex(['2018-02-27 09:03:30', 

6930 ... '2018-02-27 09:04:30'])) 

6931 a b 

6932 2018-02-27 09:03:30 NaN NaN 

6933 2018-02-27 09:04:30 NaN NaN 

6934 

6935 Take a single column into consideration 

6936 

6937 >>> df.asof(pd.DatetimeIndex(['2018-02-27 09:03:30', 

6938 ... '2018-02-27 09:04:30']), 

6939 ... subset=['a']) 

6940 a b 

6941 2018-02-27 09:03:30 30.0 NaN 

6942 2018-02-27 09:04:30 40.0 NaN 

6943 """ 

6944 if isinstance(where, compat.string_types): 

6945 from pandas import to_datetime 

6946 where = to_datetime(where) 

6947 

6948 if not self.index.is_monotonic: 

6949 raise ValueError("asof requires a sorted index") 

6950 

6951 is_series = isinstance(self, ABCSeries) 

6952 if is_series: 

6953 if subset is not None: 

6954 raise ValueError("subset is not valid for Series") 

6955 elif self.ndim > 2: 

6956 raise NotImplementedError("asof is not implemented " 

6957 "for {type}".format(type=type(self))) 

6958 else: 

6959 if subset is None: 

6960 subset = self.columns 

6961 if not is_list_like(subset): 

6962 subset = [subset] 

6963 

6964 is_list = is_list_like(where) 

6965 if not is_list: 

6966 start = self.index[0] 

6967 if isinstance(self.index, PeriodIndex): 

6968 where = Period(where, freq=self.index.freq).ordinal 

6969 start = start.ordinal 

6970 

6971 if where < start: 

6972 if not is_series: 

6973 from pandas import Series 

6974 return Series(index=self.columns, name=where) 

6975 return np.nan 

6976 

6977 # It's always much faster to use a *while* loop here for 

6978 # Series than pre-computing all the NAs. However a 

6979 # *while* loop is extremely expensive for DataFrame 

6980 # so we later pre-compute all the NAs and use the same 

6981 # code path whether *where* is a scalar or list. 

6982 # See PR: https://github.com/pandas-dev/pandas/pull/14476 

6983 if is_series: 

6984 loc = self.index.searchsorted(where, side='right') 

6985 if loc > 0: 

6986 loc -= 1 

6987 

6988 values = self._values 

6989 while loc > 0 and isna(values[loc]): 

6990 loc -= 1 

6991 return values[loc] 

6992 

6993 if not isinstance(where, Index): 

6994 where = Index(where) if is_list else Index([where]) 

6995 

6996 nulls = self.isna() if is_series else self[subset].isna().any(1) 

6997 if nulls.all(): 

6998 if is_series: 

6999 return self._constructor(np.nan, index=where, name=self.name) 

7000 elif is_list: 

7001 from pandas import DataFrame 

7002 return DataFrame(np.nan, index=where, columns=self.columns) 

7003 else: 

7004 from pandas import Series 

7005 return Series(np.nan, index=self.columns, name=where[0]) 

7006 

7007 locs = self.index.asof_locs(where, ~(nulls.values)) 

7008 

7009 # mask the missing 

7010 missing = locs == -1 

7011 data = self.take(locs, is_copy=False) 

7012 data.index = where 

7013 data.loc[missing] = np.nan 

7014 return data if is_list else data.iloc[-1] 

7015 

7016 # ---------------------------------------------------------------------- 

7017 # Action Methods
