7019 _shared_docs['isna'] = """ 

7020 Detect missing values. 

7021 

7022 Return a boolean same-sized object indicating if the values are NA. 

7023 NA values, such as None or :attr:`numpy.NaN`, gets mapped to True 

7024 values. 

7025 Everything else gets mapped to False values. Characters such as empty 

7026 strings ``''`` or :attr:`numpy.inf` are not considered NA values 

7027 (unless you set ``pandas.options.mode.use_inf_as_na = True``). 

7028 

7029 Returns 

7030 ------- 

7031 %(klass)s 

7032 Mask of bool values for each element in %(klass)s that 

7033 indicates whether an element is not an NA value. 

7034 

7035 See Also 

7036 -------- 

7037 %(klass)s.isnull : Alias of isna. 

7038 %(klass)s.notna : Boolean inverse of isna. 

7039 %(klass)s.dropna : Omit axes labels with missing values. 

7040 isna : Top-level isna. 

7041 

7042 Examples 

7043 -------- 

7044 Show which entries in a DataFrame are NA. 

7045 

7046 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'age': [5, 6, np.NaN], 

7047 ... 'born': [pd.NaT, pd.Timestamp('1939-05-27'), 

7048 ... pd.Timestamp('1940-04-25')], 

7049 ... 'name': ['Alfred', 'Batman', ''], 

7050 ... 'toy': [None, 'Batmobile', 'Joker']}) 

7051 >>> df 

7052 age born name toy 

7053 0 5.0 NaT Alfred None 

7054 1 6.0 1939-05-27 Batman Batmobile 

7055 2 NaN 1940-04-25 Joker 

7056 

7057 >>> df.isna() 

7058 age born name toy 

7059 0 False True False True 

7060 1 False False False False 

7061 2 True False False False 

7062 

7063 Show which entries in a Series are NA. 

7064 

7065 >>> ser = pd.Series([5, 6, np.NaN]) 

7066 >>> ser 

7067 0 5.0 

7068 1 6.0 

7069 2 NaN 

7070 dtype: float64 

7071 

7072 >>> ser.isna() 

7073 0 False 

7074 1 False 

7075 2 True 

7076 dtype: bool 

7077 """ 

7078 

7079 @Appender(_shared_docs['isna'] % _shared_doc_kwargs) 

7080 def isna(self): 

7081 return isna(self).__finalize__(self) 

7082 

7083 @Appender(_shared_docs['isna'] % _shared_doc_kwargs) 

7084 def isnull(self): 

7085 return isna(self).__finalize__(self) 

7086 

7087 _shared_docs['notna'] = """ 

7088 Detect existing (non-missing) values. 

7089 

7090 Return a boolean same-sized object indicating if the values are not NA. 

7091 Non-missing values get mapped to True. Characters such as empty 

7092 strings ``''`` or :attr:`numpy.inf` are not considered NA values 

7093 (unless you set ``pandas.options.mode.use_inf_as_na = True``). 

7094 NA values, such as None or :attr:`numpy.NaN`, get mapped to False 

7095 values. 

7096 

7097 Returns 

7098 ------- 

7099 %(klass)s 

7100 Mask of bool values for each element in %(klass)s that 

7101 indicates whether an element is not an NA value. 

7102 

7103 See Also 

7104 -------- 

7105 %(klass)s.notnull : Alias of notna. 

7106 %(klass)s.isna : Boolean inverse of notna. 

7107 %(klass)s.dropna : Omit axes labels with missing values. 

7108 notna : Top-level notna. 

7109 

7110 Examples 

7111 -------- 

7112 Show which entries in a DataFrame are not NA. 

7113 

7114 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'age': [5, 6, np.NaN], 

7115 ... 'born': [pd.NaT, pd.Timestamp('1939-05-27'), 

7116 ... pd.Timestamp('1940-04-25')], 

7117 ... 'name': ['Alfred', 'Batman', ''], 

7118 ... 'toy': [None, 'Batmobile', 'Joker']}) 

7119 >>> df 

7120 age born name toy 

7121 0 5.0 NaT Alfred None 

7122 1 6.0 1939-05-27 Batman Batmobile 

7123 2 NaN 1940-04-25 Joker 

7124 

7125 >>> df.notna() 

7126 age born name toy 

7127 0 True False True False 

7128 1 True True True True 

7129 2 False True True True 

7130 

7131 Show which entries in a Series are not NA. 

7132 

7133 >>> ser = pd.Series([5, 6, np.NaN]) 

7134 >>> ser 

7135 0 5.0 

7136 1 6.0 

7137 2 NaN 

7138 dtype: float64 

7139 

7140 >>> ser.notna() 

7141 0 True 

7142 1 True 

7143 2 False 

7144 dtype: bool 

7145 """ 

7146 

7147 @Appender(_shared_docs['notna'] % _shared_doc_kwargs) 

7148 def notna(self): 

7149 return notna(self).__finalize__(self) 

7150 

7151 @Appender(_shared_docs['notna'] % _shared_doc_kwargs) 

7152 def notnull(self): 

7153 return notna(self).__finalize__(self) 

7154 

7155 def _clip_with_scalar(self, lower, upper, inplace=False): 

7156 if ((lower is not None and np.any(isna(lower))) or 

7157 (upper is not None and np.any(isna(upper)))): 

7158 raise ValueError("Cannot use an NA value as a clip threshold") 

7159 

7160 result = self 

7161 mask = isna(self.values) 

7162 

7163 with np.errstate(all='ignore'): 

7164 if upper is not None: 

7165 subset = self.to_numpy() <= upper 

7166 result = result.where(subset, upper, axis=None, inplace=False) 

7167 if lower is not None: 

7168 subset = self.to_numpy() >= lower 

7169 result = result.where(subset, lower, axis=None, inplace=False) 

7170 

7171 if np.any(mask): 

7172 result[mask] = np.nan 

7173 

7174 if inplace: 

7175 self._update_inplace(result) 

7176 else: 

7177 return result 

7178 

7179 def _clip_with_one_bound(self, threshold, method, axis, inplace): 

7180 

7181 if axis is not None: 

7182 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

7183 

7184 # method is self.le for upper bound and self.ge for lower bound 

7185 if is_scalar(threshold) and is_number(threshold): 

7186 if method.__name__ == 'le': 

7187 return self._clip_with_scalar(None, threshold, inplace=inplace) 

7188 return self._clip_with_scalar(threshold, None, inplace=inplace) 

7189 

7190 subset = method(threshold, axis=axis) | isna(self) 

7191 

7192 # GH #15390 

7193 # In order for where method to work, the threshold must 

7194 # be transformed to NDFrame from other array like structure. 

7195 if (not isinstance(threshold, ABCSeries)) and is_list_like(threshold): 

7196 if isinstance(self, ABCSeries): 

7197 threshold = pd.Series(threshold, index=self.index) 

7198 else: 

7199 threshold = _align_method_FRAME(self, threshold, 

7200 axis) 

7201 return self.where(subset, threshold, axis=axis, inplace=inplace) 

7202 

7203 def clip(self, lower=None, upper=None, axis=None, inplace=False, 

7204 *args, **kwargs): 

7205 """ 

7206 Trim values at input threshold(s). 

7207 

7208 Assigns values outside boundary to boundary values. Thresholds 

7209 can be singular values or array like, and in the latter case 

7210 the clipping is performed element-wise in the specified axis. 

7211 

7212 Parameters 

7213 ---------- 

7214 lower : float or array_like, default None 

7215 Minimum threshold value. All values below this 

7216 threshold will be set to it. 

7217 upper : float or array_like, default None 

7218 Maximum threshold value. All values above this 

7219 threshold will be set to it. 

7220 axis : int or string axis name, optional 

7221 Align object with lower and upper along the given axis. 

7222 inplace : boolean, default False 

7223 Whether to perform the operation in place on the data. 

7224 

7225 .. versionadded:: 0.21.0 

7226 *args, **kwargs 

7227 Additional keywords have no effect but might be accepted 

7228 for compatibility with numpy. 

7229 

7230 Returns 

7231 ------- 

7232 Series or DataFrame 

7233 Same type as calling object with the values outside the 

7234 clip boundaries replaced 

7235 

7236 Examples 

7237 -------- 

7238 >>> data = {'col_0': [9, -3, 0, -1, 5], 'col_1': [-2, -7, 6, 8, -5]} 

7239 >>> df = pd.DataFrame(data) 

7240 >>> df 

7241 col_0 col_1 

7242 0 9 -2 

7243 1 -3 -7 

7244 2 0 6 

7245 3 -1 8 

7246 4 5 -5 

7247 

7248 Clips per column using lower and upper thresholds: 

7249 

7250 >>> df.clip(-4, 6) 

7251 col_0 col_1 

7252 0 6 -2 

7253 1 -3 -4 

7254 2 0 6 

7255 3 -1 6 

7256 4 5 -4 

7257 

7258 Clips using specific lower and upper thresholds per column element: 

7259 

7260 >>> t = pd.Series([2, -4, -1, 6, 3]) 

7261 >>> t 

7262 0 2 

7263 1 -4 

7264 2 -1 

7265 3 6 

7266 4 3 

7267 dtype: int64 

7268 

7269 >>> df.clip(t, t + 4, axis=0) 

7270 col_0 col_1 

7271 0 6 2 

7272 1 -3 -4 

7273 2 0 3 

7274 3 6 8 

7275 4 5 3 

7276 """ 

7277 if isinstance(self, ABCPanel): 

7278 raise NotImplementedError("clip is not supported yet for panels") 

7279 

7280 inplace = validate_bool_kwarg(inplace, 'inplace') 

7281 

7282 axis = nv.validate_clip_with_axis(axis, args, kwargs) 

7283 if axis is not None: 

7284 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

7285 

7286 # GH 17276 

7287 # numpy doesn't like NaN as a clip value 

7288 # so ignore 

7289 # GH 19992 

7290 # numpy doesn't drop a list-like bound containing NaN 

7291 if not is_list_like(lower) and np.any(pd.isnull(lower)): 

7292 lower = None 

7293 if not is_list_like(upper) and np.any(pd.isnull(upper)): 

7294 upper = None 

7295 

7296 # GH 2747 (arguments were reversed) 

7297 if lower is not None and upper is not None: 

7298 if is_scalar(lower) and is_scalar(upper): 

7299 lower, upper = min(lower, upper), max(lower, upper) 

7300 

7301 # fast-path for scalars 

7302 if ((lower is None or (is_scalar(lower) and is_number(lower))) and 

7303 (upper is None or (is_scalar(upper) and is_number(upper)))): 

7304 return self._clip_with_scalar(lower, upper, inplace=inplace) 

7305 

7306 result = self 

7307 if lower is not None: 

7308 result = result._clip_with_one_bound(lower, method=self.ge, 

7309 axis=axis, inplace=inplace) 

7310 if upper is not None: 

7311 if inplace: 

7312 result = self 

7313 result = result._clip_with_one_bound(upper, method=self.le, 

7314 axis=axis, inplace=inplace) 

7315 

7316 return result 

7317 

7318 def clip_upper(self, threshold, axis=None, inplace=False): 

7319 """ 

7320 Trim values above a given threshold. 

7321 

7322 .. deprecated:: 0.24.0 

7323 Use clip(upper=threshold) instead. 

7324 

7325 Elements above the `threshold` will be changed to match the 

7326 `threshold` value(s). Threshold can be a single value or an array, 

7327 in the latter case it performs the truncation element-wise. 

7328 

7329 Parameters 

7330 ---------- 

7331 threshold : numeric or array-like 

7332 Maximum value allowed. All values above threshold will be set to 

7333 this value. 

7334 

7335 * float : every value is compared to `threshold`. 

7336 * array-like : The shape of `threshold` should match the object 

7337 it's compared to. When `self` is a Series, `threshold` should be 

7338 the length. When `self` is a DataFrame, `threshold` should 2-D 

7339 and the same shape as `self` for ``axis=None``, or 1-D and the 

7340 same length as the axis being compared. 

7341 

7342 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0 

7343 Align object with `threshold` along the given axis. 

7344 inplace : boolean, default False 

7345 Whether to perform the operation in place on the data. 

7346 

7347 .. versionadded:: 0.21.0 

7348 

7349 Returns 

7350 ------- 

7351 Series or DataFrame 

7352 Original data with values trimmed. 

7353 

7354 See Also 

7355 -------- 

7356 Series.clip : General purpose method to trim Series values to given 

7357 threshold(s). 

7358 DataFrame.clip : General purpose method to trim DataFrame values to 

7359 given threshold(s). 

7360 

7361 Examples 

7362 -------- 

7363 >>> s = pd.Series([1, 2, 3, 4, 5]) 

7364 >>> s 

7365 0 1 

7366 1 2 

7367 2 3 

7368 3 4 

7369 4 5 

7370 dtype: int64 

7371 

7372 >>> s.clip(upper=3) 

7373 0 1 

7374 1 2 

7375 2 3 

7376 3 3 

7377 4 3 

7378 dtype: int64 

7379 

7380 >>> elemwise_thresholds = [5, 4, 3, 2, 1] 

7381 >>> elemwise_thresholds 

7382 [5, 4, 3, 2, 1] 

7383 

7384 >>> s.clip(upper=elemwise_thresholds) 

7385 0 1 

7386 1 2 

7387 2 3 

7388 3 2 

7389 4 1 

7390 dtype: int64 

7391 """ 

7392 warnings.warn('clip_upper(threshold) is deprecated, ' 

7393 'use clip(upper=threshold) instead', 

7394 FutureWarning, stacklevel=2) 

7395 return self._clip_with_one_bound(threshold, method=self.le, 

7396 axis=axis, inplace=inplace) 

7397 

7398 def clip_lower(self, threshold, axis=None, inplace=False): 

7399 """ 

7400 Trim values below a given threshold. 

7401 

7402 .. deprecated:: 0.24.0 

7403 Use clip(lower=threshold) instead. 

7404 

7405 Elements below the `threshold` will be changed to match the 

7406 `threshold` value(s). Threshold can be a single value or an array, 

7407 in the latter case it performs the truncation element-wise. 

7408 

7409 Parameters 

7410 ---------- 

7411 threshold : numeric or array-like 

7412 Minimum value allowed. All values below threshold will be set to 

7413 this value. 

7414 

7415 * float : every value is compared to `threshold`. 

7416 * array-like : The shape of `threshold` should match the object 

7417 it's compared to. When `self` is a Series, `threshold` should be 

7418 the length. When `self` is a DataFrame, `threshold` should 2-D 

7419 and the same shape as `self` for ``axis=None``, or 1-D and the 

7420 same length as the axis being compared. 

7421 

7422 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0 

7423 Align `self` with `threshold` along the given axis. 

7424 

7425 inplace : boolean, default False 

7426 Whether to perform the operation in place on the data. 

7427 

7428 .. versionadded:: 0.21.0 

7429 

7430 Returns 

7431 ------- 

7432 Series or DataFrame 

7433 Original data with values trimmed. 

7434 

7435 See Also 

7436 -------- 

7437 Series.clip : General purpose method to trim Series values to given 

7438 threshold(s). 

7439 DataFrame.clip : General purpose method to trim DataFrame values to 

7440 given threshold(s). 

7441 

7442 Examples 

7443 -------- 

7444 

7445 Series single threshold clipping: 

7446 

7447 >>> s = pd.Series([5, 6, 7, 8, 9]) 

7448 >>> s.clip(lower=8) 

7449 0 8 

7450 1 8 

7451 2 8 

7452 3 8 

7453 4 9 

7454 dtype: int64 

7455 

7456 Series clipping element-wise using an array of thresholds. `threshold` 

7457 should be the same length as the Series. 

7458 

7459 >>> elemwise_thresholds = [4, 8, 7, 2, 5] 

7460 >>> s.clip(lower=elemwise_thresholds) 

7461 0 5 

7462 1 8 

7463 2 7 

7464 3 8 

7465 4 9 

7466 dtype: int64 

7467 

7468 DataFrames can be compared to a scalar. 

7469 

7470 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({"A": [1, 3, 5], "B": [2, 4, 6]}) 

7471 >>> df 

7472 A B 

7473 0 1 2 

7474 1 3 4 

7475 2 5 6 

7476 

7477 >>> df.clip(lower=3) 

7478 A B 

7479 0 3 3 

7480 1 3 4 

7481 2 5 6 

7482 

7483 Or to an array of values. By default, `threshold` should be the same 

7484 shape as the DataFrame. 

7485 

7486 >>> df.clip(lower=np.array([[3, 4], [2, 2], [6, 2]])) 

7487 A B 

7488 0 3 4 

7489 1 3 4 

7490 2 6 6 

7491 

7492 Control how `threshold` is broadcast with `axis`. In this case 

7493 `threshold` should be the same length as the axis specified by 

7494 `axis`. 

7495 

7496 >>> df.clip(lower=[3, 3, 5], axis='index') 

7497 A B 

7498 0 3 3 

7499 1 3 4 

7500 2 5 6 

7501 

7502 >>> df.clip(lower=[4, 5], axis='columns') 

7503 A B 

7504 0 4 5 

7505 1 4 5 

7506 2 5 6 

7507 """ 

7508 warnings.warn('clip_lower(threshold) is deprecated, ' 

7509 'use clip(lower=threshold) instead', 

7510 FutureWarning, stacklevel=2) 

7511 return self._clip_with_one_bound(threshold, method=self.ge, 

7512 axis=axis, inplace=inplace) 

7513 

7514 def groupby(self, by=None, axis=0, level=None, as_index=True, sort=True, 

7515 group_keys=True, squeeze=False, observed=False, **kwargs): 

7516 """ 

7517 Group DataFrame or Series using a mapper or by a Series of columns. 

7518 

7519 A groupby operation involves some combination of splitting the 

7520 object, applying a function, and combining the results. This can be 

7521 used to group large amounts of data and compute operations on these 

7522 groups. 

7523 

7524 Parameters 

7525 ---------- 

7526 by : mapping, function, label, or list of labels 

7527 Used to determine the groups for the groupby. 

7528 If ``by`` is a function, it's called on each value of the object's 

7529 index. If a dict or Series is passed, the Series or dict VALUES 

7530 will be used to determine the groups (the Series' values are first 

7531 aligned; see ``.align()`` method). If an ndarray is passed, the 

7532 values are used as-is determine the groups. A label or list of 

7533 labels may be passed to group by the columns in ``self``. Notice 

7534 that a tuple is interpreted a (single) key. 

7535 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0 

7536 Split along rows (0) or columns (1). 

7537 level : int, level name, or sequence of such, default None 

7538 If the axis is a MultiIndex (hierarchical), group by a particular 

7539 level or levels. 

7540 as_index : bool, default True 

7541 For aggregated output, return object with group labels as the 

7542 index. Only relevant for DataFrame input. as_index=False is 

7543 effectively "SQL-style" grouped output. 

7544 sort : bool, default True 

7545 Sort group keys. Get better performance by turning this off. 

7546 Note this does not influence the order of observations within each 

7547 group. Groupby preserves the order of rows within each group. 

7548 group_keys : bool, default True 

7549 When calling apply, add group keys to index to identify pieces. 

7550 squeeze : bool, default False 

7551 Reduce the dimensionality of the return type if possible, 

7552 otherwise return a consistent type. 

7553 observed : bool, default False 

7554 This only applies if any of the groupers are Categoricals. 

7555 If True: only show observed values for categorical groupers. 

7556 If False: show all values for categorical groupers. 

7557 

7558 .. versionadded:: 0.23.0 

7559 

7560 **kwargs 

7561 Optional, only accepts keyword argument 'mutated' and is passed 

7562 to groupby. 

7563 

7564 Returns 

7565 ------- 

7566 DataFrameGroupBy or SeriesGroupBy 

7567 Depends on the calling object and returns groupby object that 

7568 contains information about the groups. 

7569 

7570 See Also 

7571 -------- 

7572 resample : Convenience method for frequency conversion and resampling 

7573 of time series. 

7574 

7575 Notes 

7576 ----- 

7577 See the `user guide 

7578 <http://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/groupby.html>`_ for more. 

7579 

7580 Examples 

7581 -------- 

7582 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'Animal' : ['Falcon', 'Falcon', 

7583 ... 'Parrot', 'Parrot'], 

7584 ... 'Max Speed' : [380., 370., 24., 26.]}) 

7585 >>> df 

7586 Animal Max Speed 

7587 0 Falcon 380.0 

7588 1 Falcon 370.0 

7589 2 Parrot 24.0 

7590 3 Parrot 26.0 

7591 >>> df.groupby(['Animal']).mean() 

7592 Max Speed 

7593 Animal 

7594 Falcon 375.0 

7595 Parrot 25.0 

7596 

7597 **Hierarchical Indexes** 

7598 

7599 We can groupby different levels of a hierarchical index 

7600 using the `level` parameter: 

7601 

7602 >>> arrays = [['Falcon', 'Falcon', 'Parrot', 'Parrot'], 

7603 ... ['Capitve', 'Wild', 'Capitve', 'Wild']] 

7604 >>> index = pd.MultiIndex.from_arrays(arrays, names=('Animal', 'Type')) 

7605 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'Max Speed' : [390., 350., 30., 20.]}, 

7606 ... index=index) 

7607 >>> df 

7608 Max Speed 

7609 Animal Type 

7610 Falcon Capitve 390.0 

7611 Wild 350.0 

7612 Parrot Capitve 30.0 

7613 Wild 20.0 

7614 >>> df.groupby(level=0).mean() 

7615 Max Speed 

7616 Animal 

7617 Falcon 370.0 

7618 Parrot 25.0 

7619 >>> df.groupby(level=1).mean() 

7620 Max Speed 

7621 Type 

7622 Capitve 210.0 

7623 Wild 185.0 

7624 """ 

7625 from pandas.core.groupby.groupby import groupby 

7626 

7627 if level is None and by is None: 

7628 raise TypeError("You have to supply one of 'by' and 'level'") 

7629 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

7630 return groupby(self, by=by, axis=axis, level=level, as_index=as_index, 

7631 sort=sort, group_keys=group_keys, squeeze=squeeze, 

7632 observed=observed, **kwargs) 

7633 

7634 def asfreq(self, freq, method=None, how=None, normalize=False, 

7635 fill_value=None): 

7636 """ 

7637 Convert TimeSeries to specified frequency. 

7638 

7639 Optionally provide filling method to pad/backfill missing values. 

7640 

7641 Returns the original data conformed to a new index with the specified 

7642 frequency. ``resample`` is more appropriate if an operation, such as 

7643 summarization, is necessary to represent the data at the new frequency. 

7644 

7645 Parameters 

7646 ---------- 

7647 freq : DateOffset object, or string 

7648 method : {'backfill'/'bfill', 'pad'/'ffill'}, default None 

7649 Method to use for filling holes in reindexed Series (note this 

7650 does not fill NaNs that already were present): 

7651 

7652 * 'pad' / 'ffill': propagate last valid observation forward to next 

7653 valid 

7654 * 'backfill' / 'bfill': use NEXT valid observation to fill 

7655 how : {'start', 'end'}, default end 

7656 For PeriodIndex only, see PeriodIndex.asfreq 

7657 normalize : bool, default False 

7658 Whether to reset output index to midnight 

7659 fill_value : scalar, optional 

7660 Value to use for missing values, applied during upsampling (note 

7661 this does not fill NaNs that already were present). 

7662 

7663 .. versionadded:: 0.20.0 

7664 

7665 Returns 

7666 ------- 

7667 converted : same type as caller 

7668 

7669 See Also 

7670 -------- 

7671 reindex 

7672 

7673 Notes 

7674 ----- 

7675 To learn more about the frequency strings, please see `this link 

7676 <http://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/timeseries.html#offset-aliases>`__. 

7677 

7678 Examples 

7679 -------- 

7680 

7681 Start by creating a series with 4 one minute timestamps. 

7682 

7683 >>> index = pd.date_range('1/1/2000', periods=4, freq='T') 

7684 >>> series = pd.Series([0.0, None, 2.0, 3.0], index=index) 

7685 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'s':series}) 

7686 >>> df 

7687 s 

7688 2000-01-01 00:00:00 0.0 

7689 2000-01-01 00:01:00 NaN 

7690 2000-01-01 00:02:00 2.0 

7691 2000-01-01 00:03:00 3.0 

7692 

7693 Upsample the series into 30 second bins. 

7694 

7695 >>> df.asfreq(freq='30S') 

7696 s 

7697 2000-01-01 00:00:00 0.0 

7698 2000-01-01 00:00:30 NaN 

7699 2000-01-01 00:01:00 NaN 

7700 2000-01-01 00:01:30 NaN 

7701 2000-01-01 00:02:00 2.0 

7702 2000-01-01 00:02:30 NaN 

7703 2000-01-01 00:03:00 3.0 

7704 

7705 Upsample again, providing a ``fill value``. 

7706 

7707 >>> df.asfreq(freq='30S', fill_value=9.0) 

7708 s 

7709 2000-01-01 00:00:00 0.0 

7710 2000-01-01 00:00:30 9.0 

7711 2000-01-01 00:01:00 NaN 

7712 2000-01-01 00:01:30 9.0 

7713 2000-01-01 00:02:00 2.0 

7714 2000-01-01 00:02:30 9.0 

7715 2000-01-01 00:03:00 3.0 

7716 

7717 Upsample again, providing a ``method``. 

7718 

7719 >>> df.asfreq(freq='30S', method='bfill') 

7720 s 

7721 2000-01-01 00:00:00 0.0 

7722 2000-01-01 00:00:30 NaN 

7723 2000-01-01 00:01:00 NaN 

7724 2000-01-01 00:01:30 2.0 

7725 2000-01-01 00:02:00 2.0 

7726 2000-01-01 00:02:30 3.0 

7727 2000-01-01 00:03:00 3.0 

7728 """ 

7729 from pandas.core.resample import asfreq 

7730 return asfreq(self, freq, method=method, how=how, normalize=normalize, 

7731 fill_value=fill_value) 

7732 

7733 def at_time(self, time, asof=False, axis=None): 

7734 """ 

7735 Select values at particular time of day (e.g. 9:30AM). 

7736 

7737 Parameters 

7738 ---------- 

7739 time : datetime.time or string 

7740 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0 

7741 

7742 .. versionadded:: 0.24.0 

7743 

7744 Returns 

7745 ------- 

7746 values_at_time : same type as caller 

7747 

7748 Raises 

7749 ------ 

7750 TypeError 

7751 If the index is not a :class:`DatetimeIndex` 

7752 

7753 See Also 

7754 -------- 

7755 between_time : Select values between particular times of the day. 

7756 first : Select initial periods of time series based on a date offset. 

7757 last : Select final periods of time series based on a date offset. 

7758 DatetimeIndex.indexer_at_time : Get just the index locations for 

7759 values at particular time of the day. 

7760 

7761 Examples 

7762 -------- 

7763 >>> i = pd.date_range('2018-04-09', periods=4, freq='12H') 

7764 >>> ts = pd.DataFrame({'A': [1,2,3,4]}, index=i) 

7765 >>> ts 

7766 A 

7767 2018-04-09 00:00:00 1 

7768 2018-04-09 12:00:00 2 

7769 2018-04-10 00:00:00 3 

7770 2018-04-10 12:00:00 4 

7771 

7772 >>> ts.at_time('12:00') 

7773 A 

7774 2018-04-09 12:00:00 2 

7775 2018-04-10 12:00:00 4 

7776 """ 

7777 if axis is None: 

7778 axis = self._stat_axis_number 

7779 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

7780 

7781 index = self._get_axis(axis) 

7782 try: 

7783 indexer = index.indexer_at_time(time, asof=asof) 

7784 except AttributeError: 

7785 raise TypeError('Index must be DatetimeIndex') 

7786 

7787 return self._take(indexer, axis=axis) 

7788 

7789 def between_time(self, start_time, end_time, include_start=True, 

7790 include_end=True, axis=None): 

7791 """ 

7792 Select values between particular times of the day (e.g., 9:00-9:30 AM). 

7793 

7794 By setting ``start_time`` to be later than ``end_time``, 

7795 you can get the times that are *not* between the two times. 

7796 

7797 Parameters 

7798 ---------- 

7799 start_time : datetime.time or string 

7800 end_time : datetime.time or string 

7801 include_start : boolean, default True 

7802 include_end : boolean, default True 

7803 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0 

7804 

7805 .. versionadded:: 0.24.0 

7806 

7807 Returns 

7808 ------- 

7809 values_between_time : same type as caller 

7810 

7811 Raises 

7812 ------ 

7813 TypeError 

7814 If the index is not a :class:`DatetimeIndex` 

7815 

7816 See Also 

7817 -------- 

7818 at_time : Select values at a particular time of the day. 

7819 first : Select initial periods of time series based on a date offset. 

7820 last : Select final periods of time series based on a date offset. 

7821 DatetimeIndex.indexer_between_time : Get just the index locations for 

7822 values between particular times of the day. 

7823 

7824 Examples 

7825 -------- 

7826 >>> i = pd.date_range('2018-04-09', periods=4, freq='1D20min') 

7827 >>> ts = pd.DataFrame({'A': [1,2,3,4]}, index=i) 

7828 >>> ts 

7829 A 

7830 2018-04-09 00:00:00 1 

7831 2018-04-10 00:20:00 2 

7832 2018-04-11 00:40:00 3 

7833 2018-04-12 01:00:00 4 

7834 

7835 >>> ts.between_time('0:15', '0:45') 

7836 A 

7837 2018-04-10 00:20:00 2 

7838 2018-04-11 00:40:00 3 

7839 

7840 You get the times that are *not* between two times by setting 

7841 ``start_time`` later than ``end_time``: 

7842 

7843 >>> ts.between_time('0:45', '0:15') 

7844 A 

7845 2018-04-09 00:00:00 1 

7846 2018-04-12 01:00:00 4 

7847 """ 

7848 if axis is None: 

7849 axis = self._stat_axis_number 

7850 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

7851 

7852 index = self._get_axis(axis) 

7853 try: 

7854 indexer = index.indexer_between_time( 

7855 start_time, end_time, include_start=include_start, 

7856 include_end=include_end) 

7857 except AttributeError: 

7858 raise TypeError('Index must be DatetimeIndex') 

7859 

7860 return self._take(indexer, axis=axis) 

7861 

7862 def resample(self, rule, how=None, axis=0, fill_method=None, closed=None, 

7863 label=None, convention='start', kind=None, loffset=None, 

7864 limit=None, base=0, on=None, level=None): 

7865 """ 

7866 Resample time-series data. 

7867 

7868 Convenience method for frequency conversion and resampling of time 

7869 series. Object must have a datetime-like index (`DatetimeIndex`, 

7870 `PeriodIndex`, or `TimedeltaIndex`), or pass datetime-like values 

7871 to the `on` or `level` keyword. 

7872 

7873 Parameters 

7874 ---------- 

7875 rule : str 

7876 The offset string or object representing target conversion. 

7877 how : str 

7878 Method for down/re-sampling, default to 'mean' for downsampling. 

7879 

7880 .. deprecated:: 0.18.0 

7881 The new syntax is ``.resample(...).mean()``, or 

7882 ``.resample(...).apply(<func>)`` 

7883 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0 

7884 Which axis to use for up- or down-sampling. For `Series` this 

7885 will default to 0, i.e. along the rows. Must be 

7886 `DatetimeIndex`, `TimedeltaIndex` or `PeriodIndex`. 

7887 fill_method : str, default None 

7888 Filling method for upsampling. 

7889 

7890 .. deprecated:: 0.18.0 

7891 The new syntax is ``.resample(...).<func>()``, 

7892 e.g. ``.resample(...).pad()`` 

7893 closed : {'right', 'left'}, default None 

7894 Which side of bin interval is closed. The default is 'left' 

7895 for all frequency offsets except for 'M', 'A', 'Q', 'BM', 

7896 'BA', 'BQ', and 'W' which all have a default of 'right'. 

7897 label : {'right', 'left'}, default None 

7898 Which bin edge label to label bucket with. The default is 'left' 

7899 for all frequency offsets except for 'M', 'A', 'Q', 'BM', 

7900 'BA', 'BQ', and 'W' which all have a default of 'right'. 

7901 convention : {'start', 'end', 's', 'e'}, default 'start' 

7902 For `PeriodIndex` only, controls whether to use the start or 

7903 end of `rule`. 

7904 kind : {'timestamp', 'period'}, optional, default None 

7905 Pass 'timestamp' to convert the resulting index to a 

7906 `DateTimeIndex` or 'period' to convert it to a `PeriodIndex`. 

7907 By default the input representation is retained. 

7908 loffset : timedelta, default None 

7909 Adjust the resampled time labels. 

7910 limit : int, default None 

7911 Maximum size gap when reindexing with `fill_method`. 

7912 

7913 .. deprecated:: 0.18.0 

7914 base : int, default 0 

7915 For frequencies that evenly subdivide 1 day, the "origin" of the 

7916 aggregated intervals. For example, for '5min' frequency, base could 

7917 range from 0 through 4. Defaults to 0. 

7918 on : str, optional 

7919 For a DataFrame, column to use instead of index for resampling. 

7920 Column must be datetime-like. 

7921 

7922 .. versionadded:: 0.19.0 

7923 

7924 level : str or int, optional 

7925 For a MultiIndex, level (name or number) to use for 

7926 resampling. `level` must be datetime-like. 

7927 

7928 .. versionadded:: 0.19.0 

7929 

7930 Returns 

7931 ------- 

7932 Resampler object 

7933 

7934 See Also 

7935 -------- 

7936 groupby : Group by mapping, function, label, or list of labels. 

7937 Series.resample : Resample a Series. 

7938 DataFrame.resample: Resample a DataFrame. 

7939 

7940 Notes 

7941 ----- 

7942 See the `user guide 

7943 <http://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/timeseries.html#resampling>`_ 

7944 for more. 

7945 

7946 To learn more about the offset strings, please see `this link 

7947 <http://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/timeseries.html#offset-aliases>`__. 

7948 

7949 Examples 

7950 -------- 

7951 

7952 Start by creating a series with 9 one minute timestamps. 

7953 

7954 >>> index = pd.date_range('1/1/2000', periods=9, freq='T') 

7955 >>> series = pd.Series(range(9), index=index) 

7956 >>> series 

7957 2000-01-01 00:00:00 0 

7958 2000-01-01 00:01:00 1 

7959 2000-01-01 00:02:00 2 

7960 2000-01-01 00:03:00 3 

7961 2000-01-01 00:04:00 4 

7962 2000-01-01 00:05:00 5 

7963 2000-01-01 00:06:00 6 

7964 2000-01-01 00:07:00 7 

7965 2000-01-01 00:08:00 8 

7966 Freq: T, dtype: int64 

7967 

7968 Downsample the series into 3 minute bins and sum the values 

7969 of the timestamps falling into a bin. 

7970 

7971 >>> series.resample('3T').sum() 

7972 2000-01-01 00:00:00 3 

7973 2000-01-01 00:03:00 12 

7974 2000-01-01 00:06:00 21 

7975 Freq: 3T, dtype: int64 

7976 

7977 Downsample the series into 3 minute bins as above, but label each 

7978 bin using the right edge instead of the left. Please note that the 

7979 value in the bucket used as the label is not included in the bucket, 

7980 which it labels. For example, in the original series the 

7981 bucket ``2000-01-01 00:03:00`` contains the value 3, but the summed 

7982 value in the resampled bucket with the label ``2000-01-01 00:03:00`` 

7983 does not include 3 (if it did, the summed value would be 6, not 3). 

7984 To include this value close the right side of the bin interval as 

7985 illustrated in the example below this one. 

7986 

7987 >>> series.resample('3T', label='right').sum() 

7988 2000-01-01 00:03:00 3 

7989 2000-01-01 00:06:00 12 

7990 2000-01-01 00:09:00 21 

7991 Freq: 3T, dtype: int64 

7992 

7993 Downsample the series into 3 minute bins as above, but close the right 

7994 side of the bin interval. 

7995 

7996 >>> series.resample('3T', label='right', closed='right').sum() 

7997 2000-01-01 00:00:00 0 

7998 2000-01-01 00:03:00 6 

7999 2000-01-01 00:06:00 15 

8000 2000-01-01 00:09:00 15 

8001 Freq: 3T, dtype: int64 

8002 

8003 Upsample the series into 30 second bins. 

8004 

8005 >>> series.resample('30S').asfreq()[0:5] # Select first 5 rows 

8006 2000-01-01 00:00:00 0.0 

8007 2000-01-01 00:00:30 NaN 

8008 2000-01-01 00:01:00 1.0 

8009 2000-01-01 00:01:30 NaN 

8010 2000-01-01 00:02:00 2.0 

8011 Freq: 30S, dtype: float64 

8012 

8013 Upsample the series into 30 second bins and fill the ``NaN`` 

8014 values using the ``pad`` method. 

8015 

8016 >>> series.resample('30S').pad()[0:5] 

8017 2000-01-01 00:00:00 0 

8018 2000-01-01 00:00:30 0 

8019 2000-01-01 00:01:00 1 

8020 2000-01-01 00:01:30 1 

8021 2000-01-01 00:02:00 2 

8022 Freq: 30S, dtype: int64 

8023 

8024 Upsample the series into 30 second bins and fill the 

8025 ``NaN`` values using the ``bfill`` method. 

8026 

8027 >>> series.resample('30S').bfill()[0:5] 

8028 2000-01-01 00:00:00 0 

8029 2000-01-01 00:00:30 1 

8030 2000-01-01 00:01:00 1 

8031 2000-01-01 00:01:30 2 

8032 2000-01-01 00:02:00 2 

8033 Freq: 30S, dtype: int64 

8034 

8035 Pass a custom function via ``apply`` 

8036 

8037 >>> def custom_resampler(array_like): 

8038 ... return np.sum(array_like) + 5 

8039 ... 

8040 >>> series.resample('3T').apply(custom_resampler) 

8041 2000-01-01 00:00:00 8 

8042 2000-01-01 00:03:00 17 

8043 2000-01-01 00:06:00 26 

8044 Freq: 3T, dtype: int64 

8045 

8046 For a Series with a PeriodIndex, the keyword `convention` can be 

8047 used to control whether to use the start or end of `rule`. 

8048 

8049 Resample a year by quarter using 'start' `convention`. Values are 

8050 assigned to the first quarter of the period. 

8051 

8052 >>> s = pd.Series([1, 2], index=pd.period_range('2012-01-01', 

8053 ... freq='A', 

8054 ... periods=2)) 

8055 >>> s 

8056 2012 1 

8057 2013 2 

8058 Freq: A-DEC, dtype: int64 

8059 >>> s.resample('Q', convention='start').asfreq() 

8060 2012Q1 1.0 

8061 2012Q2 NaN 

8062 2012Q3 NaN 

8063 2012Q4 NaN 

8064 2013Q1 2.0 

8065 2013Q2 NaN 

8066 2013Q3 NaN 

8067 2013Q4 NaN 

8068 Freq: Q-DEC, dtype: float64 

8069 

8070 Resample quarters by month using 'end' `convention`. Values are 

8071 assigned to the last month of the period. 

8072 

8073 >>> q = pd.Series([1, 2, 3, 4], index=pd.period_range('2018-01-01', 

8074 ... freq='Q', 

8075 ... periods=4)) 

8076 >>> q 

8077 2018Q1 1 

8078 2018Q2 2 

8079 2018Q3 3 

8080 2018Q4 4 

8081 Freq: Q-DEC, dtype: int64 

8082 >>> q.resample('M', convention='end').asfreq() 

8083 2018-03 1.0 

8084 2018-04 NaN 

8085 2018-05 NaN 

8086 2018-06 2.0 

8087 2018-07 NaN 

8088 2018-08 NaN 

8089 2018-09 3.0 

8090 2018-10 NaN 

8091 2018-11 NaN 

8092 2018-12 4.0 

8093 Freq: M, dtype: float64 

8094 

8095 For DataFrame objects, the keyword `on` can be used to specify the 

8096 column instead of the index for resampling. 

8097 

8098 >>> d = dict({'price': [10, 11, 9, 13, 14, 18, 17, 19], 

8099 ... 'volume': [50, 60, 40, 100, 50, 100, 40, 50]}) 

8100 >>> df = pd.DataFrame(d) 

8101 >>> df['week_starting'] = pd.date_range('01/01/2018', 

8102 ... periods=8, 

8103 ... freq='W') 

8104 >>> df 

8105 price volume week_starting 

8106 0 10 50 2018-01-07 

8107 1 11 60 2018-01-14 

8108 2 9 40 2018-01-21 

8109 3 13 100 2018-01-28 

8110 4 14 50 2018-02-04 

8111 5 18 100 2018-02-11 

8112 6 17 40 2018-02-18 

8113 7 19 50 2018-02-25 

8114 >>> df.resample('M', on='week_starting').mean() 

8115 price volume 

8116 week_starting 

8117 2018-01-31 10.75 62.5 

8118 2018-02-28 17.00 60.0 

8119 

8120 For a DataFrame with MultiIndex, the keyword `level` can be used to 

8121 specify on which level the resampling needs to take place. 

8122 

8123 >>> days = pd.date_range('1/1/2000', periods=4, freq='D') 

8124 >>> d2 = dict({'price': [10, 11, 9, 13, 14, 18, 17, 19], 

8125 ... 'volume': [50, 60, 40, 100, 50, 100, 40, 50]}) 

8126 >>> df2 = pd.DataFrame(d2, 

8127 ... index=pd.MultiIndex.from_product([days, 

8128 ... ['morning', 

8129 ... 'afternoon']] 

8130 ... )) 

8131 >>> df2 

8132 price volume 

8133 2000-01-01 morning 10 50 

8134 afternoon 11 60 

8135 2000-01-02 morning 9 40 

8136 afternoon 13 100 

8137 2000-01-03 morning 14 50 

8138 afternoon 18 100 

8139 2000-01-04 morning 17 40 

8140 afternoon 19 50 

8141 >>> df2.resample('D', level=0).sum() 

8142 price volume 

8143 2000-01-01 21 110 

8144 2000-01-02 22 140 

8145 2000-01-03 32 150 

8146 2000-01-04 36 90 

8147 """ 

8148 

8149 from pandas.core.resample import (resample, 

8150 _maybe_process_deprecations) 

8151 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

8152 r = resample(self, freq=rule, label=label, closed=closed, 

8153 axis=axis, kind=kind, loffset=loffset, 

8154 convention=convention, 

8155 base=base, key=on, level=level) 

8156 return _maybe_process_deprecations(r, 

8157 how=how, 

8158 fill_method=fill_method, 

8159 limit=limit) 

8160 

8161 def first(self, offset): 

8162 """ 

8163 Convenience method for subsetting initial periods of time series data 

8164 based on a date offset. 

8165 

8166 Parameters 

8167 ---------- 

8168 offset : string, DateOffset, dateutil.relativedelta 

8169 

8170 Returns 

8171 ------- 

8172 subset : same type as caller 

8173 

8174 Raises 

8175 ------ 

8176 TypeError 

8177 If the index is not a :class:`DatetimeIndex` 

8178 

8179 See Also 

8180 -------- 

8181 last : Select final periods of time series based on a date offset. 

8182 at_time : Select values at a particular time of the day. 

8183 between_time : Select values between particular times of the day. 

8184 

8185 Examples 

8186 -------- 

8187 >>> i = pd.date_range('2018-04-09', periods=4, freq='2D') 

8188 >>> ts = pd.DataFrame({'A': [1,2,3,4]}, index=i) 

8189 >>> ts 

8190 A 

8191 2018-04-09 1 

8192 2018-04-11 2 

8193 2018-04-13 3 

8194 2018-04-15 4 

8195 

8196 Get the rows for the first 3 days: 

8197 

8198 >>> ts.first('3D') 

8199 A 

8200 2018-04-09 1 

8201 2018-04-11 2 

8202 

8203 Notice the data for 3 first calender days were returned, not the first 

8204 3 days observed in the dataset, and therefore data for 2018-04-13 was 

8205 not returned. 

8206 """ 

8207 if not isinstance(self.index, DatetimeIndex): 

8208 raise TypeError("'first' only supports a DatetimeIndex index") 

8209 

8210 if len(self.index) == 0: 

8211 return self 

8212 

8213 offset = to_offset(offset) 

8214 end_date = end = self.index[0] + offset 

8215 

8216 # Tick-like, e.g. 3 weeks 

8217 if not offset.isAnchored() and hasattr(offset, '_inc'): 

8218 if end_date in self.index: 

8219 end = self.index.searchsorted(end_date, side='left') 

8220 return self.iloc[:end] 

8221 

8222 return self.loc[:end] 

8223 

8224 def last(self, offset): 

8225 """ 

8226 Convenience method for subsetting final periods of time series data 

8227 based on a date offset. 

8228 

8229 Parameters 

8230 ---------- 

8231 offset : string, DateOffset, dateutil.relativedelta 

8232 

8233 Returns 

8234 ------- 

8235 subset : same type as caller 

8236 

8237 Raises 

8238 ------ 

8239 TypeError 

8240 If the index is not a :class:`DatetimeIndex` 

8241 

8242 See Also 

8243 -------- 

8244 first : Select initial periods of time series based on a date offset. 

8245 at_time : Select values at a particular time of the day. 

8246 between_time : Select values between particular times of the day. 

8247 

8248 Examples 

8249 -------- 

8250 >>> i = pd.date_range('2018-04-09', periods=4, freq='2D') 

8251 >>> ts = pd.DataFrame({'A': [1,2,3,4]}, index=i) 

8252 >>> ts 

8253 A 

8254 2018-04-09 1 

8255 2018-04-11 2 

8256 2018-04-13 3 

8257 2018-04-15 4 

8258 

8259 Get the rows for the last 3 days: 

8260 

8261 >>> ts.last('3D') 

8262 A 

8263 2018-04-13 3 

8264 2018-04-15 4 

8265 

8266 Notice the data for 3 last calender days were returned, not the last 

8267 3 observed days in the dataset, and therefore data for 2018-04-11 was 

8268 not returned. 

8269 """ 

8270 if not isinstance(self.index, DatetimeIndex): 

8271 raise TypeError("'last' only supports a DatetimeIndex index") 

8272 

8273 if len(self.index) == 0: 

8274 return self 

8275 

8276 offset = to_offset(offset) 

8277 

8278 start_date = self.index[-1] - offset 

8279 start = self.index.searchsorted(start_date, side='right') 

8280 return self.iloc[start:] 

8281 

8282 def rank(self, axis=0, method='average', numeric_only=None, 

8283 na_option='keep', ascending=True, pct=False): 

8284 """ 

8285 Compute numerical data ranks (1 through n) along axis. Equal values are 

8286 assigned a rank that is the average of the ranks of those values. 

8287 

8288 Parameters 

8289 ---------- 

8290 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0 

8291 index to direct ranking 

8292 method : {'average', 'min', 'max', 'first', 'dense'} 

8293 * average: average rank of group 

8294 * min: lowest rank in group 

8295 * max: highest rank in group 

8296 * first: ranks assigned in order they appear in the array 

8297 * dense: like 'min', but rank always increases by 1 between groups 

8298 numeric_only : boolean, default None 

8299 Include only float, int, boolean data. Valid only for DataFrame or 

8300 Panel objects 

8301 na_option : {'keep', 'top', 'bottom'} 

8302 * keep: leave NA values where they are 

8303 * top: smallest rank if ascending 

8304 * bottom: smallest rank if descending 

8305 ascending : boolean, default True 

8306 False for ranks by high (1) to low (N) 

8307 pct : boolean, default False 

8308 Computes percentage rank of data 

8309 

8310 Returns 

8311 ------- 

8312 ranks : same type as caller 

8313 """ 

8314 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

8315 

8316 if self.ndim > 2: 

8317 msg = "rank does not make sense when ndim > 2" 

8318 raise NotImplementedError(msg) 

8319 

8320 if na_option not in {'keep', 'top', 'bottom'}: 

8321 msg = "na_option must be one of 'keep', 'top', or 'bottom'" 

8322 raise ValueError(msg) 

8323 

8324 def ranker(data): 

8325 ranks = algos.rank(data.values, axis=axis, method=method, 

8326 ascending=ascending, na_option=na_option, 

8327 pct=pct) 

8328 ranks = self._constructor(ranks, **data._construct_axes_dict()) 

8329 return ranks.__finalize__(self) 

8330 

8331 # if numeric_only is None, and we can't get anything, we try with 

8332 # numeric_only=True 

8333 if numeric_only is None: 

8334 try: 

8335 return ranker(self) 

8336 except TypeError: 

8337 numeric_only = True 

8338 

8339 if numeric_only: 

8340 data = self._get_numeric_data() 

8341 else: 

8342 data = self 

8343 

8344 return ranker(data) 

8345 

8346 _shared_docs['align'] = (""" 

8347 Align two objects on their axes with the 

8348 specified join method for each axis Index. 

8349 

8350 Parameters 

8351 ---------- 

8352 other : DataFrame or Series 

8353 join : {'outer', 'inner', 'left', 'right'}, default 'outer' 

8354 axis : allowed axis of the other object, default None 

8355 Align on index (0), columns (1), or both (None) 

8356 level : int or level name, default None 

8357 Broadcast across a level, matching Index values on the 

8358 passed MultiIndex level 

8359 copy : boolean, default True 

8360 Always returns new objects. If copy=False and no reindexing is 

8361 required then original objects are returned. 

8362 fill_value : scalar, default np.NaN 

8363 Value to use for missing values. Defaults to NaN, but can be any 

8364 "compatible" value 

8365 method : {'backfill', 'bfill', 'pad', 'ffill', None}, default None 

8366 Method to use for filling holes in reindexed Series 

8367 pad / ffill: propagate last valid observation forward to next valid 

8368 backfill / bfill: use NEXT valid observation to fill gap 

8369 limit : int, default None 

8370 If method is specified, this is the maximum number of consecutive 

8371 NaN values to forward/backward fill. In other words, if there is 

8372 a gap with more than this number of consecutive NaNs, it will only 

8373 be partially filled. If method is not specified, this is the 

8374 maximum number of entries along the entire axis where NaNs will be 

8375 filled. Must be greater than 0 if not None. 

8376 fill_axis : %(axes_single_arg)s, default 0 

8377 Filling axis, method and limit 

8378 broadcast_axis : %(axes_single_arg)s, default None 

8379 Broadcast values along this axis, if aligning two objects of 

8380 different dimensions 

8381 

8382 Returns 

8383 ------- 

8384 (left, right) : (%(klass)s, type of other) 

8385 Aligned objects 

8386 """) 

8387 

8388 @Appender(_shared_docs['align'] % _shared_doc_kwargs) 

8389 def align(self, other, join='outer', axis=None, level=None, copy=True, 

8390 fill_value=None, method=None, limit=None, fill_axis=0, 

8391 broadcast_axis=None): 

8392 from pandas import DataFrame, Series 

8393 method = missing.clean_fill_method(method) 

8394 

8395 if broadcast_axis == 1 and self.ndim != other.ndim: 

8396 if isinstance(self, Series): 

8397 # this means other is a DataFrame, and we need to broadcast 

8398 # self 

8399 cons = self._constructor_expanddim 

8400 df = cons({c: self for c in other.columns}, 

8401 **other._construct_axes_dict()) 

8402 return df._align_frame(other, join=join, axis=axis, 

8403 level=level, copy=copy, 

8404 fill_value=fill_value, method=method, 

8405 limit=limit, fill_axis=fill_axis) 

8406 elif isinstance(other, Series): 

8407 # this means self is a DataFrame, and we need to broadcast 

8408 # other 

8409 cons = other._constructor_expanddim 

8410 df = cons({c: other for c in self.columns}, 

8411 **self._construct_axes_dict()) 

8412 return self._align_frame(df, join=join, axis=axis, level=level, 

8413 copy=copy, fill_value=fill_value, 

8414 method=method, limit=limit, 

8415 fill_axis=fill_axis) 

8416 

8417 if axis is not None: 

8418 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

8419 if isinstance(other, DataFrame): 

8420 return self._align_frame(other, join=join, axis=axis, level=level, 

8421 copy=copy, fill_value=fill_value, 

8422 method=method, limit=limit, 

8423 fill_axis=fill_axis) 

8424 elif isinstance(other, Series): 

8425 return self._align_series(other, join=join, axis=axis, level=level, 

8426 copy=copy, fill_value=fill_value, 

8427 method=method, limit=limit, 

8428 fill_axis=fill_axis) 

8429 else: # pragma: no cover 

8430 raise TypeError('unsupported type: %s' % type(other)) 

8431 

8432 def _align_frame(self, other, join='outer', axis=None, level=None, 

8433 copy=True, fill_value=None, method=None, limit=None, 

8434 fill_axis=0): 

8435 # defaults 

8436 join_index, join_columns = None, None 

8437 ilidx, iridx = None, None 

8438 clidx, cridx = None, None 

8439 

8440 is_series = isinstance(self, ABCSeries) 

8441 

8442 if axis is None or axis == 0: 

8443 if not self.index.equals(other.index): 

8444 join_index, ilidx, iridx = self.index.join( 

8445 other.index, how=join, level=level, return_indexers=True) 

8446 

8447 if axis is None or axis == 1: 

8448 if not is_series and not self.columns.equals(other.columns): 

8449 join_columns, clidx, cridx = self.columns.join( 

8450 other.columns, how=join, level=level, return_indexers=True) 

8451 

8452 if is_series: 

8453 reindexers = {0: [join_index, ilidx]} 

8454 else: 

8455 reindexers = {0: [join_index, ilidx], 1: [join_columns, clidx]} 

8456 

8457 left = self._reindex_with_indexers(reindexers, copy=copy, 

8458 fill_value=fill_value, 

8459 allow_dups=True) 

8460 # other must be always DataFrame 

8461 right = other._reindex_with_indexers({0: [join_index, iridx], 

8462 1: [join_columns, cridx]}, 

8463 copy=copy, fill_value=fill_value, 

8464 allow_dups=True) 

8465 

8466 if method is not None: 

8467 left = left.fillna(axis=fill_axis, method=method, limit=limit) 

8468 right = right.fillna(axis=fill_axis, method=method, limit=limit) 

8469 

8470 # if DatetimeIndex have different tz, convert to UTC 

8471 if is_datetime64tz_dtype(left.index): 

8472 if left.index.tz != right.index.tz: 

8473 if join_index is not None: 

8474 left.index = join_index 

8475 right.index = join_index 

8476 

8477 return left.__finalize__(self), right.__finalize__(other) 

8478 

8479 def _align_series(self, other, join='outer', axis=None, level=None, 

8480 copy=True, fill_value=None, method=None, limit=None, 

8481 fill_axis=0): 

8482 

8483 is_series = isinstance(self, ABCSeries) 

8484 

8485 # series/series compat, other must always be a Series 

8486 if is_series: 

8487 if axis: 

8488 raise ValueError('cannot align series to a series other than ' 

8489 'axis 0') 

8490 

8491 # equal 

8492 if self.index.equals(other.index): 

8493 join_index, lidx, ridx = None, None, None 

8494 else: 

8495 join_index, lidx, ridx = self.index.join(other.index, how=join, 

8496 level=level, 

8497 return_indexers=True) 

8498 

8499 left = self._reindex_indexer(join_index, lidx, copy) 

8500 right = other._reindex_indexer(join_index, ridx, copy) 

8501 

8502 else: 

8503 # one has > 1 ndim 

8504 fdata = self._data 

8505 if axis == 0: 

8506 join_index = self.index 

8507 lidx, ridx = None, None 

8508 if not self.index.equals(other.index): 

8509 join_index, lidx, ridx = self.index.join( 

8510 other.index, how=join, level=level, 

8511 return_indexers=True) 

8512 

8513 if lidx is not None: 

8514 fdata = fdata.reindex_indexer(join_index, lidx, axis=1) 

8515 

8516 elif axis == 1: 

8517 join_index = self.columns 

8518 lidx, ridx = None, None 

8519 if not self.columns.equals(other.index): 

8520 join_index, lidx, ridx = self.columns.join( 

8521 other.index, how=join, level=level, 

8522 return_indexers=True) 

8523 

8524 if lidx is not None: 

8525 fdata = fdata.reindex_indexer(join_index, lidx, axis=0) 

8526 else: 

8527 raise ValueError('Must specify axis=0 or 1') 

8528 

8529 if copy and fdata is self._data: 

8530 fdata = fdata.copy() 

8531 

8532 left = self._constructor(fdata) 

8533 

8534 if ridx is None: 

8535 right = other 

8536 else: 

8537 right = other.reindex(join_index, level=level) 

8538 

8539 # fill 

8540 fill_na = notna(fill_value) or (method is not None) 

8541 if fill_na: 

8542 left = left.fillna(fill_value, method=method, limit=limit, 

8543 axis=fill_axis) 

8544 right = right.fillna(fill_value, method=method, limit=limit) 

8545 

8546 # if DatetimeIndex have different tz, convert to UTC 

8547 if is_series or (not is_series and axis == 0): 

8548 if is_datetime64tz_dtype(left.index): 

8549 if left.index.tz != right.index.tz: 

8550 if join_index is not None: 

8551 left.index = join_index 

8552 right.index = join_index 

8553 

8554 return left.__finalize__(self), right.__finalize__(other) 

8555 

8556 def _where(self, cond, other=np.nan, inplace=False, axis=None, level=None, 

8557 errors='raise', try_cast=False): 

8558 """ 

8559 Equivalent to public method `where`, except that `other` is not 

8560 applied as a function even if callable. Used in __setitem__. 

8561 """ 

8562 inplace = validate_bool_kwarg(inplace, 'inplace') 

8563 

8564 # align the cond to same shape as myself 

8565 cond = com.apply_if_callable(cond, self) 

8566 if isinstance(cond, NDFrame): 

8567 cond, _ = cond.align(self, join='right', broadcast_axis=1) 

8568 else: 

8569 if not hasattr(cond, 'shape'): 

8570 cond = np.asanyarray(cond) 

8571 if cond.shape != self.shape: 

8572 raise ValueError('Array conditional must be same shape as ' 

8573 'self') 

8574 cond = self._constructor(cond, **self._construct_axes_dict()) 

8575 

8576 # make sure we are boolean 

8577 fill_value = True if inplace else False 

8578 cond = cond.fillna(fill_value) 

8579 

8580 msg = "Boolean array expected for the condition, not {dtype}" 

8581 

8582 if not isinstance(cond, pd.DataFrame): 

8583 # This is a single-dimensional object. 

8584 if not is_bool_dtype(cond): 

8585 raise ValueError(msg.format(dtype=cond.dtype)) 

8586 elif not cond.empty: 

8587 for dt in cond.dtypes: 

8588 if not is_bool_dtype(dt): 

8589 raise ValueError(msg.format(dtype=dt)) 

8590 

8591 cond = -cond if inplace else cond 

8592 

8593 # try to align with other 

8594 try_quick = True 

8595 if hasattr(other, 'align'): 

8596 

8597 # align with me 

8598 if other.ndim <= self.ndim: 

8599 

8600 _, other = self.align(other, join='left', axis=axis, 

8601 level=level, fill_value=np.nan) 

8602 

8603 # if we are NOT aligned, raise as we cannot where index 

8604 if (axis is None and 

8605 not all(other._get_axis(i).equals(ax) 

8606 for i, ax in enumerate(self.axes))): 

8607 raise InvalidIndexError 

8608 

8609 # slice me out of the other 

8610 else: 

8611 raise NotImplementedError("cannot align with a higher " 

8612 "dimensional NDFrame") 

8613 

8614 if isinstance(other, np.ndarray): 

8615 

8616 if other.shape != self.shape: 

8617 

8618 if self.ndim == 1: 

8619 

8620 icond = cond.values 

8621 

8622 # GH 2745 / GH 4192 

8623 # treat like a scalar 

8624 if len(other) == 1: 

8625 other = np.array(other[0]) 

8626 

8627 # GH 3235 

8628 # match True cond to other 

8629 elif len(cond[icond]) == len(other): 

8630 

8631 # try to not change dtype at first (if try_quick) 

8632 if try_quick: 

8633 

8634 try: 

8635 new_other = com.values_from_object(self) 

8636 new_other = new_other.copy() 

8637 new_other[icond] = other 

8638 other = new_other 

8639 except Exception: 

8640 try_quick = False 

8641 

8642 # let's create a new (if we failed at the above 

8643 # or not try_quick 

8644 if not try_quick: 

8645 

8646 dtype, fill_value = maybe_promote(other.dtype) 

8647 new_other = np.empty(len(icond), dtype=dtype) 

8648 new_other.fill(fill_value) 

8649 maybe_upcast_putmask(new_other, icond, other) 

8650 other = new_other 

8651 

8652 else: 

8653 raise ValueError('Length of replacements must equal ' 

8654 'series length') 

8655 

8656 else: 

8657 raise ValueError('other must be the same shape as self ' 

8658 'when an ndarray') 

8659 

8660 # we are the same shape, so create an actual object for alignment 

8661 else: 

8662 other = self._constructor(other, **self._construct_axes_dict()) 

8663 

8664 if axis is None: 

8665 axis = 0 

8666 

8667 if self.ndim == getattr(other, 'ndim', 0): 

8668 align = True 

8669 else: 

8670 align = (self._get_axis_number(axis) == 1) 

8671 

8672 block_axis = self._get_block_manager_axis(axis) 

8673 

8674 if inplace: 

8675 # we may have different type blocks come out of putmask, so 

8676 # reconstruct the block manager 

8677 

8678 self._check_inplace_setting(other) 

8679 new_data = self._data.putmask(mask=cond, new=other, align=align, 

8680 inplace=True, axis=block_axis, 

8681 transpose=self._AXIS_REVERSED) 

8682 self._update_inplace(new_data) 

8683 

8684 else: 

8685 new_data = self._data.where(other=other, cond=cond, align=align, 

8686 errors=errors, 

8687 try_cast=try_cast, axis=block_axis, 

8688 transpose=self._AXIS_REVERSED) 

8689 

8690 return self._constructor(new_data).__finalize__(self)

8692 _shared_docs['where'] = ("""

8864 _shared_docs['shift'] = (""" 

8865 Shift index by desired number of periods with an optional time `freq`. 

8866 

8867 When `freq` is not passed, shift the index without realigning the data. 

8868 If `freq` is passed (in this case, the index must be date or datetime, 

8869 or it will raise a `NotImplementedError`), the index will be 

8870 increased using the periods and the `freq`. 

8871 

8872 Parameters 

8873 ---------- 

8874 periods : int 

8875 Number of periods to shift. Can be positive or negative. 

8876 freq : DateOffset, tseries.offsets, timedelta, or str, optional 

8877 Offset to use from the tseries module or time rule (e.g. 'EOM'). 

8878 If `freq` is specified then the index values are shifted but the 

8879 data is not realigned. That is, use `freq` if you would like to 

8880 extend the index when shifting and preserve the original data. 

8881 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns', None}, default None 

8882 Shift direction. 

8883 fill_value : object, optional 

8884 The scalar value to use for newly introduced missing values. 

8885 the default depends on the dtype of `self`. 

8886 For numeric data, ``np.nan`` is used. 

8887 For datetime, timedelta, or period data, etc. :attr:`NaT` is used. 

8888 For extension dtypes, ``self.dtype.na_value`` is used.

8892 Returns

8896

8903 available. 

8904

8908 ... 'Col2': [13, 23, 18, 33, 48],

8937 def shift(self, periods=1, freq=None, axis=0, fill_value=None): 

8938 if periods == 0: 

8939 return self.copy() 

8940 

8941 block_axis = self._get_block_manager_axis(axis) 

8942 if freq is None: 

8943 new_data = self._data.shift(periods=periods, axis=block_axis, 

8944 fill_value=fill_value) 

8945 else:

8950 def slice_shift(self, periods=1, axis=0): 

8951 """ 

8952 Equivalent to `shift` without copying data. The shifted data will 

8953 not include the dropped periods and the shifted axis will be smaller 

8954 than the original. 

8955 

8956 Parameters 

8957 ---------- 

8958 periods : int 

8959 Number of periods to move, can be positive or negative 

8960 

8961 Returns 

8962 ------- 

8963 shifted : same type as caller 

8964 

8965 Notes 

8966 ----- 

8967 While the `slice_shift` is faster than `shift`, you may pay for it 

8968 later during alignment. 

8969 """ 

8970 if periods == 0: 

8971 return self 

8972 

8973 if periods > 0: 

8974 vslicer = slice(None, -periods) 

8975 islicer = slice(periods, None) 

8976 else: 

8977 vslicer = slice(-periods, None) 

8978 islicer = slice(None, periods) 

8979 

8980 new_obj = self._slice(vslicer, axis=axis) 

8981 shifted_axis = self._get_axis(axis)[islicer] 

8982 new_obj.set_axis(shifted_axis, axis=axis, inplace=True) 

8983 

8984 return new_obj.__finalize__(self)

8986 def tshift(self, periods=1, freq=None, axis=0): 

8987 """ 

8988 Shift the time index, using the index's frequency if available. 

8989 

8990 Parameters 

8991 ---------- 

8992 periods : int 

8993 Number of periods to move, can be positive or negative 

8994 freq : DateOffset, timedelta, or time rule string, default None 

8995 Increment to use from the tseries module or time rule (e.g. 'EOM') 

8996 axis : int or basestring 

8997 Corresponds to the axis that contains the Index 

8998 

8999 Returns 

9000 ------- 

9001 shifted : NDFrame 

9002 

9003 Notes 

9004 ----- 

9005 If freq is not specified then tries to use the freq or inferred_freq 

9006 attributes of the index. If neither of those attributes exist, a 

9007 ValueError is thrown 

9008 """ 

9009 

9010 index = self._get_axis(axis) 

9011 if freq is None: 

9012 freq = getattr(index, 'freq', None) 

9013 

9014 if freq is None: 

9015 freq = getattr(index, 'inferred_freq', None) 

9016 

9017 if freq is None: 

9018 msg = 'Freq was not given and was not set in the index' 

9019 raise ValueError(msg) 

9020 

9021 if periods == 0: 

9022 return self 

9023 

9024 if isinstance(freq, string_types): 

9025 freq = to_offset(freq) 

9026 

9027 block_axis = self._get_block_manager_axis(axis) 

9028 if isinstance(index, PeriodIndex): 

9029 orig_freq = to_offset(index.freq) 

9030 if freq == orig_freq: 

9031 new_data = self._data.copy() 

9032 new_data.axes[block_axis] = index.shift(periods) 

9033 else: 

9034 msg = ('Given freq %s does not match PeriodIndex freq %s' % 

9035 (freq.rule_code, orig_freq.rule_code)) 

9036 raise ValueError(msg) 

9037 else: 

9038 new_data = self._data.copy() 

9039 new_data.axes[block_axis] = index.shift(periods, freq) 

9040 

9041 return self._constructor(new_data).__finalize__(self)

9043 def truncate(self, before=None, after=None, axis=None, copy=True): 

9044 """ 

9045 Truncate a Series or DataFrame before and after some index value. 

9046 

9047 This is a useful shorthand for boolean indexing based on index 

9048 values above or below certain thresholds. 

9049 

9050 Parameters 

9051 ---------- 

9052 before : date, string, int 

9053 Truncate all rows before this index value. 

9054 after : date, string, int 

9055 Truncate all rows after this index value. 

9056 axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, optional 

9057 Axis to truncate. Truncates the index (rows) by default. 

9058 copy : boolean, default is True, 

9059 Return a copy of the truncated section. 

9060 

9061 Returns 

9062 ------- 

9063 type of caller 

9064 The truncated Series or DataFrame. 

9065 

9066 See Also 

9067 -------- 

9068 DataFrame.loc : Select a subset of a DataFrame by label. 

9069 DataFrame.iloc : Select a subset of a DataFrame by position. 

9070 

9071 Notes 

9072 ----- 

9073 If the index being truncated contains only datetime values, 

9074 `before` and `after` may be specified as strings instead of 

9075 Timestamps. 

9076 

9077 Examples 

9078 -------- 

9079 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'A': ['a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 'e'], 

9080 ... 'B': ['f', 'g', 'h', 'i', 'j'], 

9081 ... 'C': ['k', 'l', 'm', 'n', 'o']}, 

9082 ... index=[1, 2, 3, 4, 5]) 

9083 >>> df 

9084 A B C 

9085 1 a f k 

9086 2 b g l 

9087 3 c h m 

9088 4 d i n 

9089 5 e j o 

9090 

9091 >>> df.truncate(before=2, after=4) 

9092 A B C 

9093 2 b g l 

9094 3 c h m 

9095 4 d i n 

9096 

9097 The columns of a DataFrame can be truncated. 

9098 

9099 >>> df.truncate(before="A", after="B", axis="columns") 

9100 A B 

9101 1 a f 

9102 2 b g 

9103 3 c h 

9104 4 d i 

9105 5 e j 

9106 

9107 For Series, only rows can be truncated. 

9108 

9109 >>> df['A'].truncate(before=2, after=4) 

9110 2 b 

9111 3 c 

9112 4 d 

9113 Name: A, dtype: object 

9114 

9115 The index values in ``truncate`` can be datetimes or string 

9116 dates. 

9117 

9118 >>> dates = pd.date_range('2016-01-01', '2016-02-01', freq='s') 

9119 >>> df = pd.DataFrame(index=dates, data={'A': 1}) 

9120 >>> df.tail() 

9121 A 

9122 2016-01-31 23:59:56 1 

9123 2016-01-31 23:59:57 1 

9124 2016-01-31 23:59:58 1 

9125 2016-01-31 23:59:59 1 

9126 2016-02-01 00:00:00 1 

9127 

9128 >>> df.truncate(before=pd.Timestamp('2016-01-05'), 

9129 ... after=pd.Timestamp('2016-01-10')).tail() 

9130 A 

9131 2016-01-09 23:59:56 1 

9132 2016-01-09 23:59:57 1 

9133 2016-01-09 23:59:58 1 

9134 2016-01-09 23:59:59 1 

9135 2016-01-10 00:00:00 1 

9136 

9137 Because the index is a DatetimeIndex containing only dates, we can 

9138 specify `before` and `after` as strings. They will be coerced to 

9139 Timestamps before truncation. 

9140 

9141 >>> df.truncate('2016-01-05', '2016-01-10').tail() 

9142 A 

9143 2016-01-09 23:59:56 1 

9144 2016-01-09 23:59:57 1 

9145 2016-01-09 23:59:58 1 

9146 2016-01-09 23:59:59 1 

9147 2016-01-10 00:00:00 1 

9148 

9149 Note that ``truncate`` assumes a 0 value for any unspecified time 

9150 component (midnight). This differs from partial string slicing, which 

9151 returns any partially matching dates. 

9152 

9153 >>> df.loc['2016-01-05':'2016-01-10', :].tail() 

9154 A 

9155 2016-01-10 23:59:55 1 

9156 2016-01-10 23:59:56 1 

9157 2016-01-10 23:59:57 1 

9158 2016-01-10 23:59:58 1 

9159 2016-01-10 23:59:59 1 

9160 """ 

9161 

9162 if axis is None: 

9163 axis = self._stat_axis_number 

9164 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

9165 ax = self._get_axis(axis) 

9166 

9167 # GH 17935 

9168 # Check that index is sorted 

9169 if not ax.is_monotonic_increasing and not ax.is_monotonic_decreasing: 

9170 raise ValueError("truncate requires a sorted index") 

9171 

9172 # if we have a date index, convert to dates, otherwise 

9173 # treat like a slice 

9174 if ax.is_all_dates: 

9175 from pandas.core.tools.datetimes import to_datetime 

9176 before = to_datetime(before) 

9177 after = to_datetime(after) 

9178 

9179 if before is not None and after is not None: 

9180 if before > after: 

9181 raise ValueError('Truncate: %s must be after %s' % 

9182 (after, before)) 

9183 

9184 slicer = [slice(None, None)] * self._AXIS_LEN 

9185 slicer[axis] = slice(before, after) 

9186 result = self.loc[tuple(slicer)] 

9187 

9188 if isinstance(ax, MultiIndex): 

9189 setattr(result, self._get_axis_name(axis), 

9190 ax.truncate(before, after)) 

9191 

9192 if copy: 

9193 result = result.copy() 

9194 

9195 return result

9197 def tz_convert(self, tz, axis=0, level=None, copy=True): 

9198 """ 

9199 Convert tz-aware axis to target time zone. 

9200 

9201 Parameters 

9202 ---------- 

9203 tz : string or pytz.timezone object 

9204 axis : the axis to convert 

9205 level : int, str, default None 

9206 If axis ia a MultiIndex, convert a specific level. Otherwise 

9207 must be None 

9208 copy : boolean, default True 

9209 Also make a copy of the underlying data 

9210 

9211 Returns 

9212 ------- 

9213 

9214 Raises 

9215 ------ 

9216 TypeError 

9217 If the axis is tz-naive. 

9218 """ 

9219 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

9220 ax = self._get_axis(axis) 

9221 

9222 def _tz_convert(ax, tz): 

9223 if not hasattr(ax, 'tz_convert'): 

9224 if len(ax) > 0: 

9225 ax_name = self._get_axis_name(axis) 

9226 raise TypeError('%s is not a valid DatetimeIndex or ' 

9227 'PeriodIndex' % ax_name) 

9228 else: 

9229 ax = DatetimeIndex([], tz=tz) 

9230 else: 

9231 ax = ax.tz_convert(tz) 

9232 return ax 

9233 

9234 # if a level is given it must be a MultiIndex level or 

9235 # equivalent to the axis name 

9236 if isinstance(ax, MultiIndex): 

9237 level = ax._get_level_number(level) 

9238 new_level = _tz_convert(ax.levels[level], tz) 

9239 ax = ax.set_levels(new_level, level=level) 

9240 else: 

9241 if level not in (None, 0, ax.name): 

9242 raise ValueError("The level {0} is not valid".format(level)) 

9243 ax = _tz_convert(ax, tz) 

9244 

9245 result = self._constructor(self._data, copy=copy) 

9246 result = result.set_axis(ax, axis=axis, inplace=False) 

9247 return result.__finalize__(self)
