9249 def tz_localize(self, tz, axis=0, level=None, copy=True, 

9250 ambiguous='raise', nonexistent='raise'): 

9251 """ 

9252 Localize tz-naive index of a Series or DataFrame to target time zone. 

9253 

9254 This operation localizes the Index. To localize the values in a 

9255 timezone-naive Series, use :meth:`Series.dt.tz_localize`. 

9256 

9257 Parameters 

9258 ---------- 

9259 tz : string or pytz.timezone object 

9260 axis : the axis to localize 

9261 level : int, str, default None 

9262 If axis ia a MultiIndex, localize a specific level. Otherwise 

9263 must be None 

9264 copy : boolean, default True 

9265 Also make a copy of the underlying data 

9266 ambiguous : 'infer', bool-ndarray, 'NaT', default 'raise' 

9267 When clocks moved backward due to DST, ambiguous times may arise. 

9268 For example in Central European Time (UTC+01), when going from 

9269 03:00 DST to 02:00 non-DST, 02:30:00 local time occurs both at 

9270 00:30:00 UTC and at 01:30:00 UTC. In such a situation, the 

9271 `ambiguous` parameter dictates how ambiguous times should be 

9272 handled. 

9273 

9274 - 'infer' will attempt to infer fall dst-transition hours based on 

9275 order 

9276 - bool-ndarray where True signifies a DST time, False designates 

9277 a non-DST time (note that this flag is only applicable for 

9278 ambiguous times) 

9279 - 'NaT' will return NaT where there are ambiguous times 

9280 - 'raise' will raise an AmbiguousTimeError if there are ambiguous 

9281 times 

9282 nonexistent : str, default 'raise' 

9283 A nonexistent time does not exist in a particular timezone 

9284 where clocks moved forward due to DST. Valid valuse are: 

9285 

9286 - 'shift_forward' will shift the nonexistent time forward to the 

9287 closest existing time 

9288 - 'shift_backward' will shift the nonexistent time backward to the 

9289 closest existing time 

9290 - 'NaT' will return NaT where there are nonexistent times 

9291 - timedelta objects will shift nonexistent times by the timedelta 

9292 - 'raise' will raise an NonExistentTimeError if there are 

9293 nonexistent times 

9294 

9295 .. versionadded:: 0.24.0 

9296 

9297 Returns 

9298 ------- 

9299 Series or DataFrame 

9300 Same type as the input. 

9301 

9302 Raises 

9303 ------ 

9304 TypeError 

9305 If the TimeSeries is tz-aware and tz is not None. 

9306 

9307 Examples 

9308 -------- 

9309 

9310 Localize local times: 

9311 

9312 >>> s = pd.Series([1], 

9313 ... index=pd.DatetimeIndex(['2018-09-15 01:30:00'])) 

9314 >>> s.tz_localize('CET') 

9315 2018-09-15 01:30:00+02:00 1 

9316 dtype: int64 

9317 

9318 Be careful with DST changes. When there is sequential data, pandas 

9319 can infer the DST time: 

9320 

9321 >>> s = pd.Series(range(7), index=pd.DatetimeIndex([ 

9322 ... '2018-10-28 01:30:00', 

9323 ... '2018-10-28 02:00:00', 

9324 ... '2018-10-28 02:30:00', 

9325 ... '2018-10-28 02:00:00', 

9326 ... '2018-10-28 02:30:00', 

9327 ... '2018-10-28 03:00:00', 

9328 ... '2018-10-28 03:30:00'])) 

9329 >>> s.tz_localize('CET', ambiguous='infer') 

9330 2018-10-28 01:30:00+02:00 0 

9331 2018-10-28 02:00:00+02:00 1 

9332 2018-10-28 02:30:00+02:00 2 

9333 2018-10-28 02:00:00+01:00 3 

9334 2018-10-28 02:30:00+01:00 4 

9335 2018-10-28 03:00:00+01:00 5 

9336 2018-10-28 03:30:00+01:00 6 

9337 dtype: int64 

9338 

9339 In some cases, inferring the DST is impossible. In such cases, you can 

9340 pass an ndarray to the ambiguous parameter to set the DST explicitly 

9341 

9342 >>> s = pd.Series(range(3), index=pd.DatetimeIndex([ 

9343 ... '2018-10-28 01:20:00', 

9344 ... '2018-10-28 02:36:00', 

9345 ... '2018-10-28 03:46:00'])) 

9346 >>> s.tz_localize('CET', ambiguous=np.array([True, True, False])) 

9347 2018-10-28 01:20:00+02:00 0 

9348 2018-10-28 02:36:00+02:00 1 

9349 2018-10-28 03:46:00+01:00 2 

9350 dtype: int64 

9351 

9352 If the DST transition causes nonexistent times, you can shift these 

9353 dates forward or backwards with a timedelta object or `'shift_forward'` 

9354 or `'shift_backwards'`. 

9355 >>> s = pd.Series(range(2), index=pd.DatetimeIndex([ 

9356 ... '2015-03-29 02:30:00', 

9357 ... '2015-03-29 03:30:00'])) 

9358 >>> s.tz_localize('Europe/Warsaw', nonexistent='shift_forward') 

9359 2015-03-29 03:00:00+02:00 0 

9360 2015-03-29 03:30:00+02:00 1 

9361 dtype: int64 

9362 >>> s.tz_localize('Europe/Warsaw', nonexistent='shift_backward') 

9363 2015-03-29 01:59:59.999999999+01:00 0 

9364 2015-03-29 03:30:00+02:00 1 

9365 dtype: int64 

9366 >>> s.tz_localize('Europe/Warsaw', nonexistent=pd.Timedelta('1H')) 

9367 2015-03-29 03:30:00+02:00 0 

9368 2015-03-29 03:30:00+02:00 1 

9369 dtype: int64 

9370 """ 

9371 nonexistent_options = ('raise', 'NaT', 'shift_forward', 

9372 'shift_backward') 

9373 if nonexistent not in nonexistent_options and not isinstance( 

9374 nonexistent, timedelta): 

9375 raise ValueError("The nonexistent argument must be one of 'raise'," 

9376 " 'NaT', 'shift_forward', 'shift_backward' or" 

9377 " a timedelta object") 

9378 

9379 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

9380 ax = self._get_axis(axis) 

9381 

9382 def _tz_localize(ax, tz, ambiguous, nonexistent): 

9383 if not hasattr(ax, 'tz_localize'): 

9384 if len(ax) > 0: 

9385 ax_name = self._get_axis_name(axis) 

9386 raise TypeError('%s is not a valid DatetimeIndex or ' 

9387 'PeriodIndex' % ax_name) 

9388 else: 

9389 ax = DatetimeIndex([], tz=tz) 

9390 else: 

9391 ax = ax.tz_localize( 

9392 tz, ambiguous=ambiguous, nonexistent=nonexistent 

9393 ) 

9394 return ax 

9395 

9396 # if a level is given it must be a MultiIndex level or 

9397 # equivalent to the axis name 

9398 if isinstance(ax, MultiIndex): 

9399 level = ax._get_level_number(level) 

9400 new_level = _tz_localize( 

9401 ax.levels[level], tz, ambiguous, nonexistent 

9402 ) 

9403 ax = ax.set_levels(new_level, level=level) 

9404 else: 

9405 if level not in (None, 0, ax.name): 

9406 raise ValueError("The level {0} is not valid".format(level)) 

9407 ax = _tz_localize(ax, tz, ambiguous, nonexistent) 

9408 

9409 result = self._constructor(self._data, copy=copy) 

9410 result = result.set_axis(ax, axis=axis, inplace=False) 

9411 return result.__finalize__(self) 

9412 

9413 # ---------------------------------------------------------------------- 

9414 # Numeric Methods 

9415 def abs(self): 

9416 """ 

9417 Return a Series/DataFrame with absolute numeric value of each element. 

9418 

9419 This function only applies to elements that are all numeric. 

9420 

9421 Returns 

9422 ------- 

9423 abs 

9424 Series/DataFrame containing the absolute value of each element. 

9425 

9426 See Also 

9427 -------- 

9428 numpy.absolute : Calculate the absolute value element-wise. 

9429 

9430 Notes 

9431 ----- 

9432 For ``complex`` inputs, ``1.2 + 1j``, the absolute value is 

9433 :math:`\\sqrt{ a^2 + b^2 }`. 

9434 

9435 Examples 

9436 -------- 

9437 Absolute numeric values in a Series. 

9438 

9439 >>> s = pd.Series([-1.10, 2, -3.33, 4]) 

9440 >>> s.abs() 

9441 0 1.10 

9442 1 2.00 

9443 2 3.33 

9444 3 4.00 

9445 dtype: float64 

9446 

9447 Absolute numeric values in a Series with complex numbers. 

9448 

9449 >>> s = pd.Series([1.2 + 1j]) 

9450 >>> s.abs() 

9451 0 1.56205 

9452 dtype: float64 

9453 

9454 Absolute numeric values in a Series with a Timedelta element. 

9455 

9456 >>> s = pd.Series([pd.Timedelta('1 days')]) 

9457 >>> s.abs() 

9458 0 1 days 

9459 dtype: timedelta64[ns] 

9460 

9461 Select rows with data closest to certain value using argsort (from 

9462 `StackOverflow <https://stackoverflow.com/a/17758115>`__). 

9463 

9464 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({ 

9465 ... 'a': [4, 5, 6, 7], 

9466 ... 'b': [10, 20, 30, 40], 

9467 ... 'c': [100, 50, -30, -50] 

9468 ... }) 

9469 >>> df 

9470 a b c 

9471 0 4 10 100 

9472 1 5 20 50 

9473 2 6 30 -30 

9474 3 7 40 -50 

9475 >>> df.loc[(df.c - 43).abs().argsort()] 

9476 a b c 

9477 1 5 20 50 

9478 0 4 10 100 

9479 2 6 30 -30 

9480 3 7 40 -50 

9481 """ 

9482 return np.abs(self) 

9483 

9484 def describe(self, percentiles=None, include=None, exclude=None): 

9485 """ 

9486 Generate descriptive statistics that summarize the central tendency, 

9487 dispersion and shape of a dataset's distribution, excluding 

9488 ``NaN`` values. 

9489 

9490 Analyzes both numeric and object series, as well 

9491 as ``DataFrame`` column sets of mixed data types. The output 

9492 will vary depending on what is provided. Refer to the notes 

9493 below for more detail. 

9494 

9495 Parameters 

9496 ---------- 

9497 percentiles : list-like of numbers, optional 

9498 The percentiles to include in the output. All should 

9499 fall between 0 and 1. The default is 

9500 ``[.25, .5, .75]``, which returns the 25th, 50th, and 

9501 75th percentiles. 

9502 include : 'all', list-like of dtypes or None (default), optional 

9503 A white list of data types to include in the result. Ignored 

9504 for ``Series``. Here are the options: 

9505 

9506 - 'all' : All columns of the input will be included in the output. 

9507 - A list-like of dtypes : Limits the results to the 

9508 provided data types. 

9509 To limit the result to numeric types submit 

9510 ``numpy.number``. To limit it instead to object columns submit 

9511 the ``numpy.object`` data type. Strings 

9512 can also be used in the style of 

9513 ``select_dtypes`` (e.g. ``df.describe(include=['O'])``). To 

9514 select pandas categorical columns, use ``'category'`` 

9515 - None (default) : The result will include all numeric columns. 

9516 exclude : list-like of dtypes or None (default), optional, 

9517 A black list of data types to omit from the result. Ignored 

9518 for ``Series``. Here are the options: 

9519 

9520 - A list-like of dtypes : Excludes the provided data types 

9521 from the result. To exclude numeric types submit 

9522 ``numpy.number``. To exclude object columns submit the data 

9523 type ``numpy.object``. Strings can also be used in the style of 

9524 ``select_dtypes`` (e.g. ``df.describe(include=['O'])``). To 

9525 exclude pandas categorical columns, use ``'category'`` 

9526 - None (default) : The result will exclude nothing. 

9527 

9528 Returns 

9529 ------- 

9530 Series or DataFrame 

9531 Summary statistics of the Series or Dataframe provided. 

9532 

9533 See Also 

9534 -------- 

9535 DataFrame.count: Count number of non-NA/null observations. 

9536 DataFrame.max: Maximum of the values in the object. 

9537 DataFrame.min: Minimum of the values in the object. 

9538 DataFrame.mean: Mean of the values. 

9539 DataFrame.std: Standard deviation of the obersvations. 

9540 DataFrame.select_dtypes: Subset of a DataFrame including/excluding 

9541 columns based on their dtype. 

9542 

9543 Notes 

9544 ----- 

9545 For numeric data, the result's index will include ``count``, 

9546 ``mean``, ``std``, ``min``, ``max`` as well as lower, ``50`` and 

9547 upper percentiles. By default the lower percentile is ``25`` and the 

9548 upper percentile is ``75``. The ``50`` percentile is the 

9549 same as the median. 

9550 

9551 For object data (e.g. strings or timestamps), the result's index 

9552 will include ``count``, ``unique``, ``top``, and ``freq``. The ``top`` 

9553 is the most common value. The ``freq`` is the most common value's 

9554 frequency. Timestamps also include the ``first`` and ``last`` items. 

9555 

9556 If multiple object values have the highest count, then the 

9557 ``count`` and ``top`` results will be arbitrarily chosen from 

9558 among those with the highest count. 

9559 

9560 For mixed data types provided via a ``DataFrame``, the default is to 

9561 return only an analysis of numeric columns. If the dataframe consists 

9562 only of object and categorical data without any numeric columns, the 

9563 default is to return an analysis of both the object and categorical 

9564 columns. If ``include='all'`` is provided as an option, the result 

9565 will include a union of attributes of each type. 

9566 

9567 The `include` and `exclude` parameters can be used to limit 

9568 which columns in a ``DataFrame`` are analyzed for the output. 

9569 The parameters are ignored when analyzing a ``Series``. 

9570 

9571 Examples 

9572 -------- 

9573 Describing a numeric ``Series``. 

9574 

9575 >>> s = pd.Series([1, 2, 3]) 

9576 >>> s.describe() 

9577 count 3.0 

9578 mean 2.0 

9579 std 1.0 

9580 min 1.0 

9581 25% 1.5 

9582 50% 2.0 

9583 75% 2.5 

9584 max 3.0 

9585 dtype: float64 

9586 

9587 Describing a categorical ``Series``. 

9588 

9589 >>> s = pd.Series(['a', 'a', 'b', 'c']) 

9590 >>> s.describe() 

9591 count 4 

9592 unique 3 

9593 top a 

9594 freq 2 

9595 dtype: object 

9596 

9597 Describing a timestamp ``Series``. 

9598 

9599 >>> s = pd.Series([ 

9600 ... np.datetime64("2000-01-01"), 

9601 ... np.datetime64("2010-01-01"), 

9602 ... np.datetime64("2010-01-01") 

9603 ... ]) 

9604 >>> s.describe() 

9605 count 3 

9606 unique 2 

9607 top 2010-01-01 00:00:00 

9608 freq 2 

9609 first 2000-01-01 00:00:00 

9610 last 2010-01-01 00:00:00 

9611 dtype: object 

9612 

9613 Describing a ``DataFrame``. By default only numeric fields 

9614 are returned. 

9615 

9616 >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'categorical': pd.Categorical(['d','e','f']), 

9617 ... 'numeric': [1, 2, 3], 

9618 ... 'object': ['a', 'b', 'c'] 

9619 ... }) 

9620 >>> df.describe() 

9621 numeric 

9622 count 3.0 

9623 mean 2.0 

9624 std 1.0 

9625 min 1.0 

9626 25% 1.5 

9627 50% 2.0 

9628 75% 2.5 

9629 max 3.0 

9630 

9631 Describing all columns of a ``DataFrame`` regardless of data type. 

9632 

9633 >>> df.describe(include='all') 

9634 categorical numeric object 

9635 count 3 3.0 3 

9636 unique 3 NaN 3 

9637 top f NaN c 

9638 freq 1 NaN 1 

9639 mean NaN 2.0 NaN 

9640 std NaN 1.0 NaN 

9641 min NaN 1.0 NaN 

9642 25% NaN 1.5 NaN 

9643 50% NaN 2.0 NaN 

9644 75% NaN 2.5 NaN 

9645 max NaN 3.0 NaN 

9646 

9647 Describing a column from a ``DataFrame`` by accessing it as 

9648 an attribute. 

9649 

9650 >>> df.numeric.describe() 

9651 count 3.0 

9652 mean 2.0 

9653 std 1.0 

9654 min 1.0 

9655 25% 1.5 

9656 50% 2.0 

9657 75% 2.5 

9658 max 3.0 

9659 Name: numeric, dtype: float64 

9660 

9661 Including only numeric columns in a ``DataFrame`` description. 

9662 

9663 >>> df.describe(include=[np.number]) 

9664 numeric 

9665 count 3.0 

9666 mean 2.0 

9667 std 1.0 

9668 min 1.0 

9669 25% 1.5 

9670 50% 2.0 

9671 75% 2.5 

9672 max 3.0 

9673 

9674 Including only string columns in a ``DataFrame`` description. 

9675 

9676 >>> df.describe(include=[np.object]) 

9677 object 

9678 count 3 

9679 unique 3 

9680 top c 

9681 freq 1 

9682 

9683 Including only categorical columns from a ``DataFrame`` description. 

9684 

9685 >>> df.describe(include=['category']) 

9686 categorical 

9687 count 3 

9688 unique 3 

9689 top f 

9690 freq 1 

9691 

9692 Excluding numeric columns from a ``DataFrame`` description. 

9693 

9694 >>> df.describe(exclude=[np.number]) 

9695 categorical object 

9696 count 3 3 

9697 unique 3 3 

9698 top f c 

9699 freq 1 1 

9700 

9701 Excluding object columns from a ``DataFrame`` description. 

9702 

9703 >>> df.describe(exclude=[np.object]) 

9704 categorical numeric 

9705 count 3 3.0 

9706 unique 3 NaN 

9707 top f NaN 

9708 freq 1 NaN 

9709 mean NaN 2.0 

9710 std NaN 1.0 

9711 min NaN 1.0 

9712 25% NaN 1.5 

9713 50% NaN 2.0 

9714 75% NaN 2.5 

9715 max NaN 3.0 

9716 """ 

9717 if self.ndim >= 3: 

9718 msg = "describe is not implemented on Panel objects." 

9719 raise NotImplementedError(msg) 

9720 elif self.ndim == 2 and self.columns.size == 0: 

9721 raise ValueError("Cannot describe a DataFrame without columns") 

9722 

9723 if percentiles is not None: 

9724 # explicit conversion of `percentiles` to list 

9725 percentiles = list(percentiles) 

9726 

9727 # get them all to be in [0, 1] 

9728 self._check_percentile(percentiles) 

9729 

9730 # median should always be included 

9731 if 0.5 not in percentiles: 

9732 percentiles.append(0.5) 

9733 percentiles = np.asarray(percentiles) 

9734 else: 

9735 percentiles = np.array([0.25, 0.5, 0.75]) 

9736 

9737 # sort and check for duplicates 

9738 unique_pcts = np.unique(percentiles) 

9739 if len(unique_pcts) < len(percentiles): 

9740 raise ValueError("percentiles cannot contain duplicates") 

9741 percentiles = unique_pcts 

9742 

9743 formatted_percentiles = format_percentiles(percentiles) 

9744 

9745 def describe_numeric_1d(series): 

9746 stat_index = (['count', 'mean', 'std', 'min'] + 

9747 formatted_percentiles + ['max']) 

9748 d = ([series.count(), series.mean(), series.std(), series.min()] + 

9749 series.quantile(percentiles).tolist() + [series.max()]) 

9750 return pd.Series(d, index=stat_index, name=series.name) 

9751 

9752 def describe_categorical_1d(data): 

9753 names = ['count', 'unique'] 

9754 objcounts = data.value_counts() 

9755 count_unique = len(objcounts[objcounts != 0]) 

9756 result = [data.count(), count_unique] 

9757 if result[1] > 0: 

9758 top, freq = objcounts.index[0], objcounts.iloc[0] 

9759 

9760 if is_datetime64_any_dtype(data): 

9761 tz = data.dt.tz 

9762 asint = data.dropna().values.view('i8') 

9763 top = Timestamp(top) 

9764 if top.tzinfo is not None and tz is not None: 

9765 # Don't tz_localize(None) if key is already tz-aware 

9766 top = top.tz_convert(tz) 

9767 else: 

9768 top = top.tz_localize(tz) 

9769 names += ['top', 'freq', 'first', 'last'] 

9770 result += [top, freq, 

9771 Timestamp(asint.min(), tz=tz), 

9772 Timestamp(asint.max(), tz=tz)] 

9773 else: 

9774 names += ['top', 'freq'] 

9775 result += [top, freq] 

9776 

9777 return pd.Series(result, index=names, name=data.name) 

9778 

9779 def describe_1d(data): 

9780 if is_bool_dtype(data): 

9781 return describe_categorical_1d(data) 

9782 elif is_numeric_dtype(data): 

9783 return describe_numeric_1d(data) 

9784 elif is_timedelta64_dtype(data): 

9785 return describe_numeric_1d(data) 

9786 else: 

9787 return describe_categorical_1d(data) 

9788 

9789 if self.ndim == 1: 

9790 return describe_1d(self) 

9791 elif (include is None) and (exclude is None): 

9792 # when some numerics are found, keep only numerics 

9793 data = self.select_dtypes(include=[np.number]) 

9794 if len(data.columns) == 0: 

9795 data = self 

9796 elif include == 'all': 

9797 if exclude is not None: 

9798 msg = "exclude must be None when include is 'all'" 

9799 raise ValueError(msg) 

9800 data = self 

9801 else: 

9802 data = self.select_dtypes(include=include, exclude=exclude) 

9803 

9804 ldesc = [describe_1d(s) for _, s in data.iteritems()] 

9805 # set a convenient order for rows 

9806 names = [] 

9807 ldesc_indexes = sorted((x.index for x in ldesc), key=len) 

9808 for idxnames in ldesc_indexes: 

9809 for name in idxnames: 

9810 if name not in names: 

9811 names.append(name) 

9812 

9813 d = pd.concat(ldesc, join_axes=pd.Index([names]), axis=1) 

9814 d.columns = data.columns.copy() 

9815 return d 

9816 

9817 def _check_percentile(self, q): 

9818 """ 

9819 Validate percentiles (used by describe and quantile). 

9820 """ 

9821 

9822 msg = ("percentiles should all be in the interval [0, 1]. " 

9823 "Try {0} instead.") 

9824 q = np.asarray(q) 

9825 if q.ndim == 0: 

9826 if not 0 <= q <= 1: 

9827 raise ValueError(msg.format(q / 100.0)) 

9828 else: 

9829 if not all(0 <= qs <= 1 for qs in q): 

9830 raise ValueError(msg.format(q / 100.0)) 

9831 return q 

9832 

9833 _shared_docs['pct_change'] = """ 

9834 Percentage change between the current and a prior element. 

9835 

9836 Computes the percentage change from the immediately previous row by 

9837 default. This is useful in comparing the percentage of change in a time 

9838 series of elements. 

9839 

9840 Parameters 

9841 ---------- 

9842 periods : int, default 1 

9843 Periods to shift for forming percent change. 

9844 fill_method : str, default 'pad' 

9845 How to handle NAs before computing percent changes. 

9846 limit : int, default None 

9847 The number of consecutive NAs to fill before stopping. 

9848 freq : DateOffset, timedelta, or offset alias string, optional 

9849 Increment to use from time series API (e.g. 'M' or BDay()). 

9850 **kwargs 

9851 Additional keyword arguments are passed into 

9852 `DataFrame.shift` or `Series.shift`. 

9853 

9854 Returns 

9855 ------- 

9856 chg : Series or DataFrame 

9857 The same type as the calling object. 

9858 

9859 See Also 

9860 -------- 

9861 Series.diff : Compute the difference of two elements in a Series. 

9862 DataFrame.diff : Compute the difference of two elements in a DataFrame. 

9863 Series.shift : Shift the index by some number of periods. 

9864 DataFrame.shift : Shift the index by some number of periods. 

9865 

9866 Examples 

9867 -------- 

9868 **Series** 

9869 

9870 >>> s = pd.Series([90, 91, 85]) 

9871 >>> s 

9872 0 90 

9873 1 91 

9874 2 85 

9875 dtype: int64 

9876 

9877 >>> s.pct_change() 

9878 0 NaN 

9879 1 0.011111 

9880 2 -0.065934 

9881 dtype: float64 

9882 

9883 >>> s.pct_change(periods=2) 

9884 0 NaN 

9885 1 NaN 

9886 2 -0.055556 

9887 dtype: float64 

9888 

9889 See the percentage change in a Series where filling NAs with last 

9890 valid observation forward to next valid. 

9891 

9892 >>> s = pd.Series([90, 91, None, 85]) 

9893 >>> s 

9894 0 90.0 

9895 1 91.0 

9896 2 NaN 

9897 3 85.0 

9898 dtype: float64 

9899 

9900 >>> s.pct_change(fill_method='ffill') 

9901 0 NaN 

9902 1 0.011111 

9903 2 0.000000 

9904 3 -0.065934 

9905 dtype: float64 

9906 

9907 **DataFrame** 

9908 

9909 Percentage change in French franc, Deutsche Mark, and Italian lira from 

9910 1980-01-01 to 1980-03-01. 

9911

9948 @Appender(_shared_docs['pct_change'] % _shared_doc_kwargs) 

9949 def pct_change(self, periods=1, fill_method='pad', limit=None, freq=None, 

9950 **kwargs): 

9951 # TODO: Not sure if above is correct - need someone to confirm. 

9952 axis = self._get_axis_number(kwargs.pop('axis', self._stat_axis_name)) 

9953 if fill_method is None: 

9954 data = self 

9955 else: 

9956 data = self.fillna(method=fill_method, limit=limit, axis=axis) 

9957 

9958 rs = (data.div(data.shift(periods=periods, freq=freq, axis=axis, 

9959 **kwargs)) - 1) 

9960 rs = rs.reindex_like(data) 

9961 if freq is None: 

9962 mask = isna(com.values_from_object(data)) 

9963 np.putmask(rs.values, mask, np.nan) 

9964 return rs 

9965 

9966 def _agg_by_level(self, name, axis=0, level=0, skipna=True, **kwargs): 

9967 if axis is None: 

9968 raise ValueError("Must specify 'axis' when aggregating by level.") 

9969 grouped = self.groupby(level=level, axis=axis, sort=False) 

9970 if hasattr(grouped, name) and skipna: 

9971 return getattr(grouped, name)(**kwargs) 

9972 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

9973 method = getattr(type(self), name) 

9974 applyf = lambda x: method(x, axis=axis, skipna=skipna, **kwargs) 

9975 return grouped.aggregate(applyf)

9992 @Substitution(outname='mad', 

9993 desc="Return the mean absolute deviation of the values " 

9994 "for the requested axis.", 

9995 name1=name, name2=name2, axis_descr=axis_descr, 

9996 min_count='', see_also='', examples='') 

9997 @Appender(_num_doc) 

9998 def mad(self, axis=None, skipna=None, level=None): 

9999 if skipna is None: 

10000 skipna = True 

10001 if axis is None: 

10002 axis = self._stat_axis_number 

10003 if level is not None: 

10004 return self._agg_by_level('mad', axis=axis, level=level, 

10005 skipna=skipna) 

10006 

10007 data = self._get_numeric_data() 

10008 if axis == 0: 

10009 demeaned = data - data.mean(axis=0) 

10010 else: 

10011 demeaned = data.sub(data.mean(axis=1), axis=0) 

10012 return np.abs(demeaned).mean(axis=axis, skipna=skipna)

10170 @Appender(_shared_docs['transform'] % dict(axis="", **_shared_doc_kwargs)) 

10171 def transform(self, func, *args, **kwargs): 

10172 result = self.agg(func, *args, **kwargs) 

10173 if is_scalar(result) or len(result) != len(self): 

10174 raise ValueError("transforms cannot produce " 

10175 "aggregated results") 

10176 

10177 return result

10182 _shared_docs['valid_index'] = """ 

10183 Return index for %(position)s non-NA/null value. 

10184 

10185 Returns 

10186 -------- 

10187 scalar : type of index 

10188 

10189 Notes 

10190 -------- 

10191 If all elements are non-NA/null, returns None. 

10192 Also returns None for empty %(klass)s. 

10193 """ 

10194 

10195 def _find_valid_index(self, how): 

10196 """ 

10197 Retrieves the index of the first valid value. 

10198 

10199 Parameters 

10200 ---------- 

10201 how : {'first', 'last'} 

10202 Use this parameter to change between the first or last valid index. 

10203 

10204 Returns 

10205 ------- 

10206 idx_first_valid : type of index 

10207 """ 

10208 assert how in ['first', 'last'] 

10209 

10210 if len(self) == 0: # early stop 

10211 return None 

10212 is_valid = ~self.isna() 

10213 

10214 if self.ndim == 2: 

10215 is_valid = is_valid.any(1) # reduce axis 1 

10216 

10217 if how == 'first': 

10218 idxpos = is_valid.values[::].argmax() 

10219 

10220 if how == 'last': 

10221 idxpos = len(self) - 1 - is_valid.values[::-1].argmax() 

10222 

10223 chk_notna = is_valid.iat[idxpos] 

10224 idx = self.index[idxpos] 

10225 

10226 if not chk_notna: 

10227 return None 

10228 return idx 

10229 

10230 @Appender(_shared_docs['valid_index'] % {'position': 'first', 

10231 'klass': 'NDFrame'}) 

10232 def first_valid_index(self): 

10233 return self._find_valid_index('first') 

10234 

10235 @Appender(_shared_docs['valid_index'] % {'position': 'last', 

10236 'klass': 'NDFrame'}) 

10237 def last_valid_index(self): 

10238 return self._find_valid_index('last')

10241def _doc_parms(cls): 

10242 """Return a tuple of the doc parms.""" 

10243 axis_descr = "{%s}" % ', '.join(["{0} ({1})".format(a, i) 

10244 for i, a in enumerate(cls._AXIS_ORDERS)]) 

10245 name = (cls._constructor_sliced.__name__ 

10246 if cls._AXIS_LEN > 1 else 'scalar') 

10247 name2 = cls.__name__ 

10248 return axis_descr, name, name2

10895_min_count_stub = """\ 

10896min_count : int, default 0 

10897 The required number of valid values to perform the operation. If fewer than 

10898 ``min_count`` non-NA values are present the result will be NA. 

10899 

10900 .. versionadded :: 0.22.0 

10901 

10902 Added with the default being 0. This means the sum of an all-NA 

10903 or empty Series is 0, and the product of an all-NA or empty 

10904 Series is 1.

10908def _make_min_count_stat_function(cls, name, name1, name2, axis_descr, desc, 

10909 f, see_also='', examples=''): 

10910 @Substitution(outname=name, desc=desc, name1=name1, name2=name2, 

10911 axis_descr=axis_descr, min_count=_min_count_stub, 

10912 see_also=see_also, examples=examples) 

10913 @Appender(_num_doc) 

10914 def stat_func(self, axis=None, skipna=None, level=None, numeric_only=None, 

10915 min_count=0, 

10916 **kwargs): 

10917 if name == 'sum': 

10918 nv.validate_sum(tuple(), kwargs) 

10919 elif name == 'prod': 

10920 nv.validate_prod(tuple(), kwargs) 

10921 else: 

10922 nv.validate_stat_func(tuple(), kwargs, fname=name) 

10923 if skipna is None: 

10924 skipna = True 

10925 if axis is None: 

10926 axis = self._stat_axis_number 

10927 if level is not None: 

10928 return self._agg_by_level(name, axis=axis, level=level, 

10929 skipna=skipna, min_count=min_count) 

10930 return self._reduce(f, name, axis=axis, skipna=skipna, 

10931 numeric_only=numeric_only, min_count=min_count) 

10932 

10933 return set_function_name(stat_func, name, cls)

10981def _make_cum_function(cls, name, name1, name2, axis_descr, desc, 

10982 accum_func, accum_func_name, mask_a, mask_b, examples): 

10983 @Substitution(outname=name, desc=desc, name1=name1, name2=name2, 

10984 axis_descr=axis_descr, accum_func_name=accum_func_name, 

10985 examples=examples) 

10986 @Appender(_cnum_doc) 

10987 def cum_func(self, axis=None, skipna=True, *args, **kwargs): 

10988 skipna = nv.validate_cum_func_with_skipna(skipna, args, kwargs, name) 

10989 if axis is None: 

10990 axis = self._stat_axis_number 

10991 else: 

10992 axis = self._get_axis_number(axis) 

10993 

10994 y = com.values_from_object(self).copy() 

10995 

10996 if (skipna and 

10997 issubclass(y.dtype.type, (np.datetime64, np.timedelta64))): 

10998 result = accum_func(y, axis) 

10999 mask = isna(self) 

11000 np.putmask(result, mask, iNaT) 

11001 elif skipna and not issubclass(y.dtype.type, (np.integer, np.bool_)): 

11002 mask = isna(self) 

11003 np.putmask(y, mask, mask_a) 

11004 result = accum_func(y, axis) 

11005 np.putmask(result, mask, mask_b) 

11006 else: 

11007 result = accum_func(y, axis) 

11008 

11009 d = self._construct_axes_dict() 

11010 d['copy'] = False 

11011 return self._constructor(result, **d).__finalize__(self) 

11012 

11013 return set_function_name(cum_func, name, cls)

11016def _make_logical_function(cls, name, name1, name2, axis_descr, desc, f, 

11017 see_also, examples, empty_value): 

11018 @Substitution(outname=name, desc=desc, name1=name1, name2=name2, 

11019 axis_descr=axis_descr, see_also=see_also, examples=examples, 

11020 empty_value=empty_value) 

11021 @Appender(_bool_doc) 

11022 def logical_func(self, axis=0, bool_only=None, skipna=True, level=None, 

11023 **kwargs): 

11024 nv.validate_logical_func(tuple(), kwargs, fname=name) 

11025 if level is not None: 

11026 if bool_only is not None: 

11027 raise NotImplementedError("Option bool_only is not " 

11028 "implemented with option level.") 

11029 return self._agg_by_level(name, axis=axis, level=level, 

11030 skipna=skipna) 

11031 return self._reduce(f, name, axis=axis, skipna=skipna, 

11032 numeric_only=bool_only, filter_type='bool') 

11033 

11034 return set_function_name(logical_func, name, cls)
